{"title_page": "Deadmau5", "text_new": "{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{good article}}\n{{short description|Canadian musician}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- For individuals; see Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Deadmau5\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = File:Deadmau5 d.jpg\n| landscape           = yes\n| alt                 = DJ with a mouse head mask performing live \n| caption             = Deadmau5 in 2014\n| birth_name          = Joel Thomas Zimmerman\n| alias               = {{hlist|Halcyon441|Karma K|Testpilot<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixmag.net/words/news/deadmau5-joins-richie-hawtins-label-under-testpilot-alias|title=Deadmau5 joins Richie Hawtin's label under testpilot alias|publisher=[[Mixmag]]|date=March 4, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307065224/http://www.mixmag.net/words/news/deadmau5-joins-richie-hawtins-label-under-testpilot-alias|archivedate=March 7, 2014}}</ref>}}\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1981|1|5}}\n| birth_place         = [[Niagara Falls, Ontario]], Canada\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Progressive house]]|[[electro house]]|[[Electronic music|electronic]]}}\n| occupation          = {{hlist|[[Record producer]]|[[Disc jockey|DJ]]|[[musician]]}}\n| instrument          = {{hlist|[[Synthesizer]]|[[keyboard instrument|keyboard]]|[[piano]]| [[digital audio workstation]]|[[Programming (music)|programming]]}}\n| years_active        = 1998\u2013present\n| label               = {{hlist|[[Mau5trap]]|[[Virgin EMI Records|Virgin EMI]]|[[Ultra Music|Ultra]]|[[Astralwerks]]|[[Ministry of Sound]]|[[SongBird]]|[[Play Records|Play]]|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]|[[Parlophone]]}}\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|[[Kaskade]]|[[Rob Swire]]|[[Wolfgang Gartner]]|BSOD|WTF?|[[Eric Prydz]]}}\n| website             = {{URL|deadmau5.com}}\n| module          = \n  {{Infobox person\n   | child       = yes\n   | spouse      = {{marriage|Kelly Fedoni|2017}}\n   | residence   = [[Campbellville, Ontario|Campbellville]]; [[Milton, Ontario]], Canada\n  }}\n}}\n'''Joel Thomas Zimmerman''' (born January 5, 1981),<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/deadmau5 |title=Deadmau5 |first=Laura |last=Stanley |encyclopedia=The Canadian Encyclopedia |date=July 9, 2015 |access-date=January 2, 2019 }}</ref> known professionally as '''Deadmau5''' (stylized as '''deadmau5'''; pronounced \"dead mouse\"), is a Canadian [[electronic music]] producer, DJ, and musician. Zimmerman mainly produces [[progressive house]] music and sometimes other forms of [[electronic music]]. His works have been included in compilation albums such as [[Ti\u00ebsto]]'s ''[[In Search of Sunrise 6: Ibiza]]'' and presented on [[Armin van Buuren]]'s ''[[A State of Trance]]'' radio show.\n\nZimmerman has received six [[Grammy Award]] nominations for his work. He has worked with other DJs and producers, such as [[Kaskade]], MC Flipside, [[Rob Swire]] and [[Wolfgang Gartner]]. He has also collaborated with [[Steve Duda]] under the group name BSOD (Better Sounding On Drugs), and was part of the group named WTF? with Duda, [[Tommy Lee]], and DJ Aero. In 2007, he founded his own record label, [[Mau5trap]]. Deadmau5 is currently one of the highest paid electronic music producers in the world,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/eeel45jfeg/6-deadmau5-11-5-million/|title=Deadmau5 ($11.5 million) \u2013 In Photos: The World's Highest-Paid DJs|author=Zack O'Malley Greenburg|work=Forbes|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404230217/http://www.forbes.com/pictures/eeel45jfeg/6-deadmau5-11-5-million/|archivedate=April 4, 2016}}</ref> and is a masked music artist similar to [[Marshmello]] and [[Daft Punk]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thump.vice.com/en_us/article/masked-djs-history-orbital-deadmau5-daft-punk-marshmello|title=A Brief History of Masked DJs\u2014From Orbital to Marshmello|date=November 29, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130165129/http://thump.vice.com/en_us/article/masked-djs-history-orbital-deadmau5-daft-punk-marshmello|archivedate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, an early 12\" single produced on vinyl titled \"I Don't Want No Other\" was released by Joel Zimmerman and Derek Caesar under the group name Dred and Karma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trc.daily-beat.com/lifestyle/2015/01/first-ever-deadmau5-tracks-pressed-vinyl-play-de-record/|title=Unearthing First Ever Deadmau5 Tracks Pressed on Vinyl at Play de Record|last=Hooper|first=Kurtis|date=14 January 2015|website=Daily Beat Media|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref> A 2006 compilation album titled ''[[Deadmau5 Circa 1998\u20132002]]'' was self-released under the alias Halcyon441.<ref>{{cite web|title=Listen to \"Hiatus Fantasy\" \u2013 The longest deadmau5 song ever released|work=[[Dancing Astronaut]]|url=http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2016/10/listen-longest-deadmau5-song-ever-released/|accessdate=February 14, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215023632/http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2016/10/listen-longest-deadmau5-song-ever-released/|archivedate=February 15, 2018}}</ref> His debut studio album, ''[[Get Scraped]]'' was released in 2005, with follow-up ''[[Vexillology (album)|Vexillology]]'' in 2006. His breakthrough, ''[[Random Album Title]]'', was released in 2008 and was [[List of music recording certifications|certified gold]] in Canada, and silver the United Kingdom. The album includes seminal release \"[[Faxing Berlin]]\", \"[[Not Exactly]]\", and moderate chart hit \"[[I Remember (Deadmau5 and Kaskade song)|I Remember]]\" (with [[Kaskade]]). In 2009, his fourth studio album ''[[For Lack of a Better Name]]'' was released to critical acclaim, featuring [[Rob Swire]] collaboration \"[[Ghosts 'n' Stuff]]\", \"Hi Friend\", and the critically acclaimed \"[[Strobe (instrumental)|Strobe]]\". His fifth studio album, ''[[4\u00d74=12]]'', released in late 2010, supported by singles \"[[Some Chords]]\", \"[[Animal Rights (instrumental)|Animal Rights]]\", \"[[Sofi Needs a Ladder]]\", and \"[[Raise Your Weapon]]\".\n\nIn 2012, Zimmerman released singles \"[[The Veldt (song)|The Veldt]]\" and \"[[Professional Griefers]]\" (featuring [[Gerard Way]]) to commercial success. These singles were featured on his sixth studio album, ''[[Album Title Goes Here]]''. Following departure from long-time label [[Ultra Music|Ultra Records]], Zimmerman released his seventh studio album, ''[[While(1 Is Less Than 2)|While(1<2)]]'' through [[Astralwerks]] and [[Virgin EMI]] in 2014. The album's release was supported by its four singles; \"[[Avaritia (instrumental)|Avaritia]]\", \"[[Seeya (Deadmau5 song)|Seeya]]\", \"[[Infra Turbo Pigcart Racer]]\", and \"[[Phantoms Can't Hang]]\". After a brief hiatus, Zimmerman's eighth studio album, ''[[W:/2016Album/]]'' was released in late 2016, with singles \"[[Snowcone (instrumental)|Snowcone]]\" and \"[[Let Go (Deadmau5 song)|Let Go]]\".\n\n==Early life==\nZimmerman was born in [[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]], Ontario, Canada.<ref>{{citation|last=Birtles|first=Bryan|title=Deadmau5|url=http://www.vueweekly.com/music/story/deadmau5/|work=Vue Weekly|issue=793|accessdate=May 3, 2011|date=December 29, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103034700/http://www.vueweekly.com/music/story/deadmau5/|archivedate=November 3, 2013}}</ref> His mother, Nancy (n\u00e9e Johnson), is a visual artist, and his father, Rodney Thomas \"Rod\" Zimmerman, is a [[General Motors]] plant worker.<ref name=\"article01023\">{{cite web|last=Liss |first=Sarah |url=http://www.torontolife.com/daily/hype/print-edition/2011/11/01/man-in-the-mouse-deadmau5-profile/3/ |title=How Deadmau5\u2014a.k.a. DJ Joel Zimmerman\u2014came to make $100,000 a show and have four million Facebook fans \u00ab Page 3 of 6 |publisher=torontolife.com |date=November 1, 2011 |accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"genad1\">{{cite web |url=http://users.start.ca/users/bhurdle/fretz/dat87.html#2 |title=Genealogy Data |publisher=Start.ca |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006172624/http://users.start.ca/users/bhurdle/fretz/dat87.html#2 |archivedate=October 6, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He has two siblings, Jennifer (older) and Chris (younger).<ref name=\"article01023\" /> His ancestry includes [[German Canadian|German]], Swiss, and English.<ref name=\"genad1\" /><ref>{{cite web |publisher=nurun.com |url=http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2010/01/28/builder-first-to-skate-in-memorial-arena |title=Builder first to skate in Memorial Arena |work=Niagara Falls Review |date=January 28, 2010 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620042701/http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2010/01/28/builder-first-to-skate-in-memorial-arena |archivedate=June 20, 2013  }}</ref> He received his first keyboard for Christmas when he was a teenager.<ref name=\"article01023\" /><ref name=\"aritcle0101\">{{cite web |publisher=nurun.com |url=http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2011/10/30/deadmau5-rejects-his-father-and-grandfathers-advice-about-getting-a-real-job |title=deadmau5 rejects his father and grandfather's a... |work=Niagara Falls Review |date=October 30, 2011 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620021135/http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2011/10/30/deadmau5-rejects-his-father-and-grandfathers-advice-about-getting-a-real-job |archivedate=June 20, 2013  }}</ref> His music career began in the late 1990s, with a [[chiptune]] and [[demoscene]] movements-influenced sound with the [[Impulse Tracker]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.residentadvisor.net/feature.aspx?972 |publisher=residentadvisor.net |title=Deadmau5: It's complicated |date=September 30, 2008 |first=Todd L. |last=Burns |accessdate=September 3, 2014 |quote=''I was in my Mom's basement tooling away on Impulse Tracker on a 386 just doing Nintendo music until some Loop Library company hired me as a producer.'' |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007010942/http://www.residentadvisor.net/feature.aspx?972 |archivedate=October 7, 2014  }}</ref> \nZimmerman graduated from [[Westlane Secondary School]] in Niagara Falls. He then worked with an online music licensing company and as a programmer. He adopted the name Deadmau5, which referred to a dead mouse he found in his computer.<ref name=\"law\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Law |publisher=Welland Tribune |url=http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2010/11/24/deadmau5-the-mouse-that-roared |title=Deadmau5: The mouse that roared |newspaper=Niagara Falls Review |date=November 25, 2010 |accessdate=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614082908/http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2010/11/24/deadmau5-the-mouse-that-roared |archivedate=June 14, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1998\u20132006: ''Get Scraped'' and self-released compilations===\nZimmerman released his debut studio album, titled ''[[Get Scraped]]'' on July 26, 2005. The tracks \"Just Before 8bit\", \"Nice Try, Kiddo\" and \"Uploading and Downloading\" from ''[[Project 56 (album)|Project 56]]'' were edited and expanded upon in ''Get Scraped'' under the names \"8bit\", \"Try Again\", and \"Unspecial Effects\", respectively. Tracks \"Bored of Canada\", \"Intelstat\" and \"I Forget\" reappear on this album as is, as well as \"The Oshawa Connection\" from ''[[Deadmau5 Circa 1998\u20132002]]''.\n\nThree self-released compilations, ''Project 56'', ''Deadmau5 Circa 1998\u20132002'', and ''[[A Little Oblique]]'', were finished in 2006, with ''Project 56'' seeing an official release two years later.\n\n===2006\u201308: ''Vexillology'', Mau5trap, and ''Random Album Title''===\n[[File:Deadmau5 live.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Deadmau5 at Coachella 2008]]\nIn 2006, Zimmerman released his second studio album, ''[[Vexillology (album)|Vexillology]]'', on November 6, 2006 through [[Play Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/vexillology/id844225367|title=Vexillology on iTunes|accessdate=March 28, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329051252/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/vexillology/id844225367|archivedate=March 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Zimmerman founded his own record label, [[Mau5trap]], which, along with [[Ultra Records]] and [[Ministry of Sound]], released the 2008 album ''[[Random Album Title]]'', which saw the collaboration of Zimmerman and Chicago producer [[Kaskade]] with \"[[I Remember (Deadmau5 and Kaskade song)|I Remember]]\". ''Random Album Title'', saw a digital release on September 2, 2008, via [[Ultra Records]] in the United States and [[Ministry of Sound]] in the United Kingdom and Europe. Physical copies of the album were released in November 2008. Singles \"[[Faxing Berlin]]\" on October 25, 2006, and \"[[Not Exactly (song)|Not Exactly]]\" on August 27, 2007, were released prior to the album's release. Single \"I Remember\" (with Kaskade) was later released on September 15, 2008, before the album's release.\n\nIn the United States, Zimmerman's collaboration with [[Kaskade]], \"[[Move for Me]]\", reached number one on ''Billboard'' magazine's [[Dance/Mix Show Airplay]] chart in its September 6, 2008, issue.<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Deadmau5|chart=Dance/Mix Show Airplay}}|title= Current Hot Dance Airplay|work=Billboard}}</ref> Since then, Zimmerman has seen two more tracks, also collaborations (\"I Remember\" with [[Kaskade]] and \"[[Ghosts 'n' Stuff]]\" with [[Rob Swire]]), reach number one on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Dance/Mix Show Airplay chart, making him the only Canadian to have three number-one tracks on that chart. He is also the sixth Canadian to top that chart, following [[Deborah Cox]], [[Nelly Furtado]], [[Dragonette]], [[Justin Bieber]], and [[The Weeknd]], each with one apiece.\n\n===2009\u201311: ''For Lack of a Better Name'' and ''4\u00d74=12''===\n[[File:Deadmau5 LED Cube.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Deadmau5 performing at the Austin Music Hall, 2011]]\nOn September 22, 2009, [[Ultra Records]] released his album ''[[For Lack of a Better Name]]'' in the United States, and October 5 internationally. On a subsequent tour in the fall of 2009, Zimmerman's performances were recorded and made available for sale immediately following the concerts on USB wristband flash drives. ''For Lack of a Better Name'' includes two of Zimmerman's most popular songs, \"Ghosts 'n' Stuff\" (featuring Rob Swire) and \"[[Strobe (instrumental)|Strobe]]\". \"Ghosts 'n' Stuff\" was released on November 25, 2008, before the album, while \"Strobe\" was released on February 23, 2010, after the album's release.\n\nMTV named Zimmerman as the house DJ for the [[2010 MTV Video Music Awards]] and MTV PUSH artist of the week on August 16, 2010. He expressed gratitude towards [[Lady Gaga]] and [[David Guetta]] for bringing dance into the pop music scene and paving the way for him to the mainstream.<ref name=\"houseartist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1645817/deadmau5-named-house-artist-2010-mtv-vmas.jhtml|title=Deadmau5 Named House Artist For 2010 MTV VMAs|date=August 16, 2010|accessdate=January 21, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520043504/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1645817/deadmau5-named-house-artist-2010-mtv-vmas.jhtml|archivedate=May 20, 2011}}</ref> At the awards, Zimmerman performed with [[Jason Derulo]] and [[Travie McCoy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1647609/deadmau5-marvels-at-scope-vma-houseartist-gig.jhtml|title=Deadmau5 Marvels At 'Scope' Of VMA House-Artist Gig|first=James|last=Montgomery|date=September 11, 2010|accessdate=January 21, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113040546/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1647609/deadmau5-marvels-at-scope-vma-houseartist-gig.jhtml|archivedate=January 13, 2011}}</ref> His song \"Ghosts 'n' Stuff\" had been featured on the soundtrack for the MTV reality series ''[[Jersey Shore (TV series)|Jersey Shore]]'' earlier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/08/16/push-artist-of-the-week-dead-mau5/|title=PUSH Artist of the Week: deadmau5|date=September 11, 2010|accessdate=January 21, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030094325/http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/08/16/push-artist-of-the-week-dead-mau5/|archivedate=October 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis fifth studio album, ''[[4\u00d74=12]]'', was released on December 6, 2010, in the United Kingdom and December 7, 2010, in the United States. Singles \"[[Some Chords]]\" on May 3, 2010, \"[[Animal Rights (song)|Animal Rights]]\" (with [[Wolfgang Gartner]]) on September 6, and \"[[Sofi Needs a Ladder]]\" (featuring [[Sofia Toufa|SOFI]]) on November 1 were released and were featured on the album. \"[[Raise Your Weapon]]\" (featuring [[Greta Svabo Bech]]) was released later on May 23, 2011. \"Some Chords\" was featured on an episode of ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'' where Zimmerman made a cameo appearance, and an instrumental version of \"Sofi Needs a Ladder\" was featured in the film ''[[The Hangover Part II]]''. That year, he also released two non-album singles \"[[Aural Psynapse]]\" and \"HR 8938 Cephei\".\n\n===2012\u201314: ''Album Title Goes Here'' and ''While(1<2)''===\n[[File:Deadmau5 - Rock in Rio Madrid 2012 - 02.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Deadmau5 performing at [[Rock in Rio]] in [[Madrid]], 2012]]\n\nOn August 9, 2012, Zimmerman announced his sixth studio album, ''[[Album Title Goes Here]]'', which was released on September 24 of that year.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jesse Grushack |url=http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2012/08/deadmau5-to-release-album-title-goes-here-on-sept-25/ |title=Deadmau5 to release 'album title goes here' on Sept. 25 |publisher=Dancingastronaut.com |date=August 9, 2012 |accessdate=August 10, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812001909/http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2012/08/deadmau5-to-release-album-title-goes-here-on-sept-25/ |archivedate=August 12, 2012  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/480527/deadmau5s-album-title-gets-fall-release|work=Billboard|title=Deadmau5's 'Album Title' Gets Fall Release|first=Billboard|last=Staff|date=August 9, 2012|accessdate=August 9, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330042956/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/480527/deadmau5s-album-title-gets-fall-release|archivedate=March 30, 2013}}</ref> Singles from this album include \"[[Maths (instrumental)|Maths]]\" on February 17, 2012, \"[[The Veldt (song)|The Veldt]]\" (featuring Chris James) on May 8, and \"[[Professional Griefers]]\" (featuring [[Gerard Way]]) on August 14. Singles \"[[Channel 42 (instrumental)|Channel 42]]\" (with Wolfgang Gartner) on February 12, 2013, and \"[[Telemiscommunications]]\" (with [[Imogen Heap]]) on March 12 were released in 2013, after the album was released. His collaboration with Gerard Way on \"Professional Griefers\" was announced on Facebook prior to release. In December 2012, [[FUSE TV]] named \"Professional Griefers\" one of the top 40 songs of 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fuse.tv/2012/12/fuse-staff-picks-best-songs-of-2012#19 |title=The 40 Best Songs of 2012: Fuse Staff Picks \u2013 Fuse |publisher=Fuse.tv |date=December 24, 2012 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129063607/http://www.fuse.tv/2012/12/fuse-staff-picks-best-songs-of-2012#19 |archivedate=January 29, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Zimmerman deleted three years worth of music from his SoundCloud account, replacing them with an EP of seven melancholy piano sonatas, simply called ''7'', named after the Latin translations for the [[seven deadly sins]]: \"Acedia\", \"Avaritia\", \"Gula\", \"Invidia\", \"Ira\", \"Luxuria\", and \"Superbia\".<ref name=\"Tregoning\">{{cite news |last=Tregoning |first=Jack |url=http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/57212/In_other_Deadmau5_news_his_twodisc_epiclength_album_is_done |title=inthemix: In other Deadmau5 news, his two-disc, epic-length album is done |work=inthemix |date=January 7, 2014 |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116054627/http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/57212/In_other_Deadmau5_news_his_twodisc_epiclength_album_is_done |archivedate=January 16, 2014  }}</ref> Also in November 2013, Zimmerman left longtime label Ultra Records and signed with record label [[Astralwerks]], the famed NYC-based imprint that houses artists such as [[Swedish House Mafia]], [[David Guetta]], and [[The Chemical Brothers]]. Speaking on the partnership, Zimmerman admitted, \"I found a place that knows what to do with my music.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Buyanovsky |first=Dan |url=http://revolt.tv/news/deadmau5-teases-new-album-and-massive-2014-tour/99A22A8B-1DAC-4C8F-8598-1552B2200B74 |title=REVOLT.TV: Deadmau5 Teases New Album And Massive 2014 Tour |work=REVOLT.TV |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140121030749/http://revolt.tv/news/deadmau5-teases-new-album-and-massive-2014-tour/99A22A8B-1DAC-4C8F-8598-1552B2200B74 |archivedate=January 21, 2014  }}</ref>\n\nOn January 7, 2014, Zimmerman announced via his Twitter account that his much-anticipated new album is complete. \"In other news... I finished my album today,\" the tweet read. \"2 discs. 2 continuous mixes. 25 tracks. and something I'm proud of.\"<ref name=\"Tregoning\"/> On May 10, 2014, Deadmau5 announced through his subscription service that his upcoming album would be titled ''[[While(1 Is Less Than 2)|While(1<2)]]'' and would be released on June 17, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youredm.com/2014/05/10/deadmau5-announces-album-title-release-date/|title=Deadmau5 Announces Album Title And Release Date|author=Matthew Meadow|work=Your EDM|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401123155/http://www.youredm.com/2014/05/10/deadmau5-announces-album-title-release-date|archivedate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> The album was preceded by the release of four singles: \"[[Avaritia (song)|Avaritia]]\", \"[[Seeya (Deadmau5 song)|Seeya]]\" (featuring [[Colleen D'Agostino]]), \"[[Infra Turbo Pigcart Racer]]\" and \"[[Phantoms Can't Hang]]\". Starting on the week of May 20, 2014, each single was released weekly for a total of four weeks leading up to the release of the album.\n\n=== 2015\u201316: Depression, return, and ''W:/2016Album/''===\n[[File:Deamau5 at Veld Music Festival (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|240px|Deadmau5 performing on the Cube stage at [[VELD Music Festival]] in 2016]]\nOn January 13, 2015, it was announced that Deadmau5 would be a headlining act for the Bonnaroo Music and Arts Festival, in Manchester, Tennessee, which was held on June 11\u201315, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author=Weingarten, Christopher R|year=2015|title=Bonnaroo 2015: Billy Joel, Mumford and Sons, Deadmau5 Lead Lineup|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bonnaroo-2015-billy-joel-mumford-and-sons-deadmau5-lead-lineup-67451/|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ferreras, Jesse|year=2015|title=Bonnaroo 2015 Lineup: Billy Joel, Mumford & Sons, Deadmau5 Among Headliners|work=[[Huffington Post]]|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/01/13/bonnaroo-2015-lineup-billy-joel-mumford_n_6467306.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer_us=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvLnVrLw&guce_referrer_cs=j6Uk-VETUCOD8e0uM3r6HA|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> On February 2, 2015, it was announced he would appear at Reading and Leeds Festivals.<ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 \u2013 Acts \u2013 Reading + Leeds Festivals|work=[[BBC Music]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/ernxj5/acts/az5hj5|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The 20 Best Bands At Reading And Leeds 2015 In Order Of Greatness|author=Barker, Emily|year=2015|work=[[NME]]|url=https://www.nme.com/photos/the-20-best-bands-at-reading-and-leeds-2015-in-order-of-greatness-voted-for-by-nme-readers-1422764|accessdate=July 20, 2018}}</ref> On July 23, 2015, [[Valve Corporation|Valve]] announced that Deadmau5 was creating a series of sound clips to be featured in their video game ''[[Dota 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=McCarthy, Will|year=2015|title=Deadmau5 releases an album\u2019s worth of new music for \u2018Dota 2\u2019|work=[[Dancing Astronaut]]|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2015/07/deadmau5-dota-2/|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> The music pack was released alongside the announcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.dota2.com/2015/07/deadmau5-dieback-music-pack/|title=deadmau5 dieback music pack \u2013 Dota 2|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724080921/http://blog.dota2.com/2015/07/deadmau5-dieback-music-pack/|archivedate=July 24, 2015}}</ref> On August 8, 2015, Deadmau5 performed live at [[KeyArena]] in [[Seattle]] at the conclusion of the [[Dota 2]] competition [[The International 5]] (TI5).<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Trolls Millions At Surprise Dota 2 Finals Performance, Faces Backlash From Gamers|author=Sachs, Elliot|year=2015|url=https://www.youredm.com/2015/08/09/deadmau5-trolls-millions-at-surprise-dota-2-finals-performance-faces-backlash-from-gamers/|work=YourEDM|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Trolls DOTA 2 Finals With 'Levels' During Surprise Performance|author=Middleton, Ryan|work=Music Times|url=https://www.musictimes.com/articles/45106/20150809/deadmau5-dota-2-finals-levels-during-surprise-performance-soundtrack.htm|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> On October 7, 2015, Deadmau5 officially announced that he was leaving his then label Astralwerks and going entirely independent with his own label Mau5trap.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Leaves Astralwerks for Indie Platform|work=EDMTunes|url=https://www.edmtunes.com/2015/10/deadmau5-leaves-astralwerks-for-indie-platform/|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, 2015, it appeared that Zimmerman was either taking a leave of absence or ending his career altogether after deleting both his Twitter and Facebook accounts.<ref>{{cite web|author=Goldstien, Danielle|year=2015|title=Deadmau5 quits social media following Bieber rant and uploads new tracks|work=[[NME]]|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/deadmau5-2-4-1201158|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Diep, Eric|year=2015|title=Deadmau5 Deletes His Twitter and Facebook Following Justin Bieber Rant|work=Complex|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2015/12/deadmau-5-delete-twitter-facebook-new-track|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> His Instagram account, however, had not been deleted.<ref name=\"complexx\">{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Reveals Why He Deleted All of His Social Media|work=Complex|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2015/12/deadmau5-explains-why-he-deleted-all-of-his-social-media|author=Morris, Jessie|year=2015|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> On December 21, 2015, Zimmerman reopened his Twitter account and posted an apology to his Tumblr account explaining his disappearance from social media, saying that he was suffering from depression and would be returning to producing music after the new year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Britton, Luke Morgan|year=2015|title=Deadmau5 says \u2018sorry for being a dick\u2019 as he reveals struggles with depression|work=NME|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/deadmau5-2-3-1200245|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"complexx\"/>\n\nOn May 27, 2016, \"[[Snowcone (instrumental)|Snowcone]]\", the first single from Zimmerman in nearly two years, was released as a digital download.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7386056/deadmau5-snowcone-first-single-two-years-dance|title=Deadmau5 Releases 'Snowcone', First Single in Two Years|last=Medved|first=Matt|date=May 27, 2016|newspaper=Billboard|access-date=November 13, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129141609/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7386056/deadmau5-snowcone-first-single-two-years-dance|archivedate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> This track was later revealed to be the first single from his next album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmsauce.com/2016/11/04/deadmau5-announces-release-upcoming-album-w2016album/|title=Deadmau5 announces release of upcoming album 'W:/2016ALBUM/'|last=Braat|first=Taylor|date=November 4, 2016|website=EDM Sauce|access-date=November 13, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113181255/http://www.edmsauce.com/2016/11/04/deadmau5-announces-release-upcoming-album-w2016album/|archivedate=November 13, 2016}}</ref> On November 4, 2016, Zimmerman announced his next studio album, ''[[W:/2016Album/]]'', which was released on December 2, 2016, digitally,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7565637/deadmau5-w2016album|title=Deadmau5 Announces First Album Since 2014, 'W:/2016ALBUM/'|newspaper=Billboard|access-date=November 6, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105124400/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7565637/deadmau5-w2016album|archivedate=November 5, 2016}}</ref> with a vinyl and CD release on February 17, and March 17, 2017, respectively.\n\n=== 2017\u2013present: ''Stuff I Used to Do'', ''Where's the Drop?'', ''Polar'' soundtrack and ''Mau5ville''  ===\nOn January 7, 2017, Zimmerman announced a compilation of his earlier work ranging from the years of 1998 to 2007 on Twitter, titled ''[[Stuff I Used to Do]]''. Zimmerman also stated that the compilation would release in February of that year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://djmag.com/news/deadmau5-confirms-february-release-new-album-stuff-i-used-do|title=Deadmau5 Confirms February Release for 'New' Album, 'Stuff I Used to Do'|newspaper=DJ Mag|access-date=January 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110124046/https://djmag.com/news/deadmau5-confirms-february-release-new-album-stuff-i-used-do|archivedate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> On February 24, 2017, Zimmerman released a limited version of ''Stuff I Used to Do'' on [[WeTransfer]]. The edition, available until March 3, featured three tracks less than the full album. The album includes tracks from ''[[Get Scraped]]'' and early compilations, in addition to an alternative mix of \"Creep\" from ''[[While(1 Is Less Than 2)|While(1<2)]]''.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7702005/deadmau5-stuff-i-used-to-do-download|title=Download deadmau5's 'stuff i used to do' Album Via WeTransfer Now|work=Billboard|access-date=March 2, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226175847/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7702005/deadmau5-stuff-i-used-to-do-download|archivedate=February 26, 2017}}</ref> The album was officially released on [[Mau5trap]] a week later, on March 3, 2017.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\nOn March 25, 2017, Zimmerman began a [[concert tour]] with his new \"Cube 2.1\" stage set entitled [[Lots of Shows in a Row]] to promote the release of ''W:/2016Album/''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lots of shows in a row tour - gratefulweb.com|url=http://www.gratefulweb.com/articles/deadmau5-lots-shows-row-tour|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414081439/http://www.gratefulweb.com/articles/deadmau5-lots-shows-row-tour|archivedate=April 14, 2017}}</ref> Zimmerman toured around [[North America]] for two months, before touring the rest of the world from June 3, 2017, and Canada from October 6, 2017, with the tour concluding on October 31, 2017. On August 25, 2017, Zimmerman released a stand-alone single entitled \"[[Legendary (Deadmau5 and Shotty Horroh song)|Legendary]]\", featuring guest vocals from rapper [[Shotty Horroh]].<ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 Growls on 'Legendary' Hip-hop Tune with Shotty Horroh: Listen|work=Billboard|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7942016/deadmau5-new-song-legendary-shotty-horroh|accessdate=September 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026190441/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7942016/deadmau5-new-song-legendary-shotty-horroh|archivedate=October 26, 2017}}</ref> A music video for the song was released on Mau5trap's YouTube channel on September 11, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 x Shotty Horroh \u2013 Legendary [video]|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4c3FH6PheKM|accessdate=September 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102031246/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4c3FH6PheKM|archivedate=November 2, 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Zimmerman confirmed his next studio album is \"on the way\".<ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5's New Album is on the Way: \"She's a Comin'\"|work=Mixmag|url=http://mixmag.net/read/deadmau5s-new-album-is-on-the-way-shes-a-comin-news|access-date=October 1, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001111300/http://mixmag.net/read/deadmau5s-new-album-is-on-the-way-shes-a-comin-news|archivedate=October 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Zimmerman announced a compilation album comprising orchestral performances of previously released music, titled ''[[Where's the Drop?]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 announces full orchestra performance titled 'where's the drop?'|work=[[Mixmag]]|url=http://mixmag.net/read/deadmau5-announces-performance-with-a-full-orchestra-called-wheres-the-drop-news|accessdate=March 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309054016/http://mixmag.net/read/deadmau5-announces-performance-with-a-full-orchestra-called-wheres-the-drop-news|archivedate=March 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 Announces Orchestral Album After Live Tidal Performance|work=Billboard|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8238614/deadmau5-orchestral-album-live-tidal-performance|accessdate=March 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309182604/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8238614/deadmau5-orchestral-album-live-tidal-performance|archivedate=March 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Announces Upcoming Orchestral Album + New Live Show|website=Runthetrap.com|url=https://runthetrap.com/2018/03/07/deadmau5-announces-upcoming-orchestral-album/|accessdate=March 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309054457/https://runthetrap.com/2018/03/07/deadmau5-announces-upcoming-orchestral-album/|archivedate=March 9, 2018}}</ref> On March 30, 2018, the album was initially released exclusively on the [[music streaming]] service [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] for a period of three months. On June 29, 2018, the album was officially released on other digital download and streaming services, as well as vinyl.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8463437/deadmau5-orchestral-album-wheres-the-drop-spotify|title=deadmau5's Orchestral Album 'Where's the Drop?' Now on Spotify: Listen|last=Bein|first=Kat|date=June 29, 2018|work=Billboard|access-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629234055/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8463437/deadmau5-orchestral-album-wheres-the-drop-spotify|archivedate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://djmag.com/content/deadmau5%E2%80%98s-orchestral-album-%E2%80%98where%E2%80%99s-drop%E2%80%99-given-full-release|title=Deadmau5\u2018s orchestral album \u2018Where\u2019s the Drop?\u2019 is given full release|last=McCallum|first=Rob|date=June 29, 2018|work=DJMag.com|access-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629180230/https://djmag.com/content/deadmau5%E2%80%98s-orchestral-album-%E2%80%98where%E2%80%99s-drop%E2%80%99-given-full-release|archivedate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msopr.com/press-releases/deadmau5-orchestral-album-wheres-the-drop-available-everywhere-today-june-29-on-mau5trap/|title=deadmau5\u2032 Orchestral Album \u2018where\u2019s the drop?\u2019 Available Everywhere Today, June 29 on mau5trap|last=Thomson|first=Sean|date=June 29, 2018|website=Mitch Schneider Organization|language=en|access-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705052849/http://www.msopr.com/press-releases/deadmau5-orchestral-album-wheres-the-drop-available-everywhere-today-june-29-on-mau5trap/|archivedate=July 5, 2018}}</ref> On July 3, 2018, Zimmerman announced an EP and compilation album titled ''[[Mau5ville: Level 1]]'', featuring \"[[Monophobia (song)|Monophobia]]\", a collaboration with [[Rob Swire]], as well as tracks from [[Getter (DJ)|Getter]] and [[GTA (DJs)|GTA]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Reveals New EP \"mau5ville: Level 1\" Featuring Rob Swire, Getter, GTA and More|work=EDM.com|url=https://edm.com/news/deadmau5-announces-mau5ville|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 reveals release date of new EP \u2018Mau5ville: Level 1\u2019|work=We Rave You|url=https://weraveyou.com/2018/07/deadmau5-reveals-release-date-of-new-ep-mau5ville-level-1/|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref> It was released on July 13, 2018 through Mau5trap.<ref>{{cite web|author=Narozniak, Rachel|year=2018|title=deadmau5 releases long-awaited Rob Swire collaboration, \u2018Monophobia\u2019 on new \u2018mau5ville: Level 1\u2019 EP|work=[[Dancing Astronaut]]|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/07/deadmau5-releases-long-awaited-rob-swire-collaboration-monophobia-new-mauville-level-1-ep/|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Bein, Kat|year=2018|title=Deadmau5's 'Mau5ville Level 1' Compilation: Listen|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8465347/deadmau5-mau5ville-level-1-gta-getter-rob-swire|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref> On September 18, 2018, Zimmerman announced that he was in the process of producing his first ever original [[film score]] for the [[Netflix]] film \"[[Polar (film)|Polar]]\" directed by [[Jonas \u00c5kerlund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/deadmau5/status/1042074760283402240?s=19|title=Goat Lord on Twitter: \"well, the mouse is outta the bag,....working on my first film score for @constantinfilm @Netflix's #Polar...\"|website=[[Twitter]]|date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, the track listing of a follow-up EP, ''[[Mau5ville: Level 2]]'', was leaked, showing featured collaborations with [[Lights (musician)|Lights]] and Mr. Bill, with no release date confirmed at the time.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018mau5ville: Level 2\u2019 Leak Reveals Tracklist w/ Collabs, Remixes & Rare deadmau5 Track|work=Your EDM|url=https://www.youredm.com/2018/10/31/mau5ville-level-2-tracklist-revealed/|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5\u2019s \u2018Mau5ville: Level 2\u2019 Leak Reveals Tracklist & Rare Song|work=EDMSauce|url=https://www.edmsauce.com/2018/11/01/deadmau5s-mau5ville-level-2-leak-reveals-tracklist-rare-song/|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> The EP was released officially on November 16, 2018 through Mau5trap.\n\nOn January 25, 2019, ''Polar'' premiered on Netflix, with Zimmerman releasing the soundtrack album, ''[[Polar (Music from the Netflix Film)]]'', through Mau5trap.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 on His Scoring Debut for Netflix's 'Polar': \"I Wanted to Wait for the Right Thing\"|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8494943/deadmau5-interview-scoring-debut-netflix-polar-jonas-akerlund|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/3kAKiw0kRCuSXsTBWbBc9X|title=Polar (Music from the Netflix film) by deadmau5 on Spotify|website=[[Spotify]]|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> On February 1, 2019, the third installment in the ''Mau5ville'' series, ''[[Mau5ville: Level 3]]'' was released through Mau5trap. The compilation EP featured collaborations with Shotty Horroh, Scene of Action as well as tracks from No Mana and C.O.Z.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/4GeNdEYBTmiJ1BDhd9fazL|title=Mau5ville: Level 3 by deadmau5 on Spotify|website=[[Spotify]]|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edm.com/music-releases/deadmau5-mau5trap-mau5ville-level-3|title=Mau5trap Presents Mau5ville: Level 3|website=EDM.com|accessdate=February 2, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Zimmerman released three new singles, entitled \"Satrn\", \"Coasted\" and \"Fall\", released on the 16th, 22nd and 29th respectively.<ref>[https://weraveyou.com/2019/11/deadmau5-satrn/] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|author=Claire Shaffer |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/deadmau5-coasted-916112/ |title=Deadmau5 Premieres New Song 'Coasted' |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=2019-11-21 |accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youredm.com/2019/11/29/deadmau5-new-single-fall-listen/] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Video game appearances==\nZimmerman is a playable avatar in ''[[DJ Hero 2]]'', a video game released in October 2010.<ref>{{cite web |last=Vozick |first=Simon |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2010/07/14/dj-hero-2-artists/ |title='DJ Hero 2': Check out the exclusive list of artists here! &#124; ''Entertainment Weekly''. |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 14, 2010 |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205073758/http://music-mix.ew.com/2010/07/14/dj-hero-2-artists/ |archivedate=December 5, 2010  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/activision-announces-roster-of-award-winning-musical-talent-96282153.html |title=Activision Announces Roster of Award-Winning Musical Talent \u2013 Santa Monica, Calif., June 14 /PRNewswire-FirstCall/ |location=California |agency=PR Newswire |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617224334/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/activision-announces-roster-of-award-winning-musical-talent-96282153.html |archivedate=June 17, 2010  }}</ref><ref name=\"eurogamer review\">{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-10-19-dj-hero-2-review | title = DJ Hero 2 | date = October 19, 2010 | accessdate = January 14, 2011 | first = Keza | last = MacDonald | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101028125027/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-10-19-dj-hero-2-review | archivedate = October 28, 2010 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The game featured several tracks by the artist, including a mix of \"Ghosts 'n' Stuff\" with [[Lady Gaga]]'s \"[[Just Dance (song)|Just Dance]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/video/deadmau5-ghosts-dj-hero-2/701360 |title=DJ Hero 2 Video Game, Deadmau5 Ghosts & Stuff Vs Just Dance Trailer |publisher=GameTrailers.com |date=July 1, 2010 |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704170204/http://www.gametrailers.com/video/deadmau5-ghosts-dj-hero-2/701360 |archivedate=July 4, 2010  }}</ref> He is also featured as a secret unlockable character in the 2014 video game ''[[Goat Simulator]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeNicola|first1=Danielle|title=Goat Simulator Patch 1.1: How to Unlock New Goat Mutators|url=http://www.gameskinny.com/cifer/goat-simulator-patch-11-how-to-unlock-new-goat-mutators|website=Game Skinny|accessdate=June 11, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609140838/http://www.gameskinny.com/cifer/goat-simulator-patch-11-how-to-unlock-new-goat-mutators|archivedate=June 9, 2014}}</ref> His music has been included in other video game titles, including a custom soundtrack for ''[[Dota 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 dieback music pack|url=http://blog.dota2.com/2015/07/deadmau5-dieback-music-pack/|publisher=Dota 2|accessdate=August 20, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724080921/http://blog.dota2.com/2015/07/deadmau5-dieback-music-pack/|archivedate=July 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the mobile app ''Family Guy: The Quest for Stuff'' by TinyCo, Deadmau5 was available for purchase as a playable character during the \"PeterPalooza\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Makuch|first1=Eddie|title=Snoop Dogg, Deadmau5, Weird Al Invade Family Guy Game|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/snoop-dogg-deadmau5-weird-al-invade-family-guy-gam/1100-6429688/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=January 3, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121003522/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/snoop-dogg-deadmau5-weird-al-invade-family-guy-gam/1100-6429688/|archivedate=January 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA virtual version of his helmet is also an available accessory in ''[[Rocket League]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Makuch|first1=Eddie|title=Rocket League Adding Free Deadmau5 DLC in February|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rocket-league-adding-free-deadmau5-dlc-in-february/1100-6434257/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=January 3, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113022448/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rocket-league-adding-free-deadmau5-dlc-in-february/1100-6434257/|archivedate=November 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Deadmau5 head on.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Zimmerman unmasked]]\nOn July 30, 2010, at the [[9:30 Club]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], Zimmerman collapsed on stage, suffering from exhaustion and vomiting. This resulted in the cancellation of the rest of the show, as well as nine shows following the event.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ziegbe |first=Mawuse |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1644854/20100731/deadmau_five.jhtml |title=Deadmau5 Collapses Onstage, Cancels Tour Dates \u2013 Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV |date=July 31, 2010 |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924083756/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1644854/20100731/deadmau_five.jhtml |archivedate=September 24, 2010  }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Zimmerman began dating American [[tattoo artist]] and TV personality [[Kat Von D]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kat Von D Dating DJ Deadmau5!|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/kat-von-d-dating-dj-deadmau5-2012199|work=[[Us Weekly]]|accessdate=October 19, 2012|date=September 19, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016001348/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/kat-von-d-dating-dj-deadmau5-2012199|archivedate=October 16, 2012}}</ref> After breaking up in November 2012, they rekindled their relationship shortly afterwards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 and Kat von D break up|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/1286915--deadmau5-and-kat-von-d-break-up|work=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=December 16, 2012|date=November 13, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121226070754/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/1286915--deadmau5-and-kat-von-d-break-up|archivedate=December 26, 2012}}</ref> On December 15, 2012, Zimmerman proposed to Von D via [[Twitter]], and they announced that they would marry in August 2013 with an aquatic-themed wedding.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mike|last=Fleeman|title=Kat Von D Engaged to Deadmau5 \u2013 Who Proposed on Twitter!|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20657038,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=December 16, 2012|date=December 16, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121218234650/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20657038,00.html|archivedate=December 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://perezhilton.com/2013-04-16-kat-von-d-deadmau5-plan-underwater-themed-wedding |title=Kat Von D & Deadmau5 Are Getting Married The Little Mermaid Way! |publisher=PerezHilton.com |date=April 16, 2013 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130705105453/http://perezhilton.com/2013-04-16-kat-von-d-deadmau5-plan-underwater-themed-wedding |archivedate=July 5, 2013  }}</ref> They both have several matching tattoos, including the numbers \"289m3d22h\" on both of their arms, a sentimental reference to the day when they met, as well as two black stars underneath their eyes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.georgefm.co.nz/DEADMAU5-AND-GIRLFRIEND-KAT-VON-D-GET-MATCHING-TATTOOS/tabid/72/articleID/124111/Default.aspx |title=DEADMAU5 AND GIRLFRIEND KAT VON D GET MATCHING TATTOOS \u2013 News story \u2013 News |publisher=George FM |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702180142/http://www.georgefm.co.nz/DEADMAU5-AND-GIRLFRIEND-KAT-VON-D-GET-MATCHING-TATTOOS/tabid/72/articleID/124111/Default.aspx |archivedate=July 2, 2013  }}</ref> Zimmerman moved to [[Los Angeles]] to live with Von D.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kroq.cbslocal.com/2012/10/04/deadmau5-moves-to-l-a-hooks-up-with-kat-von-d-and-totally-needs-a-drivers-license/ |title=Deadmau5 Moves To L.A., Hooks Up With Kat Von D And Totally Needs A Driver's License \u00ab The World Famous KROQ |publisher=Kroq.cbslocal.com |date=October 4, 2012 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928170204/http://kroq.cbslocal.com/2012/10/04/deadmau5-moves-to-l-a-hooks-up-with-kat-von-d-and-totally-needs-a-drivers-license/ |archivedate=September 28, 2013  }}</ref> In June 2013, Von D announced that they had ended their engagement.<ref>{{cite web|first=Maggie|last=Coughlan|title=Deadmau5 and Kat Von D End Engagement|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20712900,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=July 8, 2013|date=June 27, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701173845/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20712900,00.html|archivedate=July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Zimmerman purchased a $5 million home in the [[Campbellville, Ontario|Campbellville]] area of [[Milton, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmsauce.com/2014/10/10/deadmau5-purchased-beautiful-5-million-house-canada/|title=Deadmau5 Purchased This Beautiful $5 Million House In Canada|author=Stevo|work=EDM Sauce|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408234142/http://www.edmsauce.com/2014/10/10/deadmau5-purchased-beautiful-5-million-house-canada/|archivedate=April 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/6084813-deadmau5-entertains-milton-students-encourages-creativity/|title=Deadmau5 entertains Milton students, encourages creativity|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108232835/http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/6084813-deadmau5-entertains-milton-students-encourages-creativity/|archivedate=November 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hdsb.ca/Newsroom/SpotlightonSchools/Pages/Popularelectronic-dancemusicianDeadmau5inspiresMiltonDistrictHighSchoolstudents.aspx|title=Electronic-dance musician Deadmau5 inspires Milton DHS students|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071308/http://www.hdsb.ca/Newsroom/SpotlightonSchools/Pages/Popularelectronic-dancemusicianDeadmau5inspiresMiltonDistrictHighSchoolstudents.aspx|archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://torontolife.com/real-estate/deadmau5s-condo-is-for-sale-and-this-is-what-it-looks-like-inside/|title=Deadmau5's condo is for sale, and this is what it looks like inside \u2013 Toronto Life|work=Toronto Life|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325085120/http://torontolife.com/real-estate/deadmau5s-condo-is-for-sale-and-this-is-what-it-looks-like-inside/|archivedate=March 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn August 12, 2017, Zimmerman married his fianc\u00e9e Kelly Fedoni.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/music/deadmau5-marries-kelly-fedoni/|title=deadmau5 marries Kelly Fedoni|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813104734/http://people.com/music/deadmau5-marries-kelly-fedoni/|archivedate=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn October 11, 2018, Zimmerman announced a leave of absence, due to mental health and personal reasons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youredm.com/2018/10/10/deadmau5-addresses-his-recent-insensitive-tweets-in-statement-admitting-he-needs-help/|title=BREAKING: Deadmau5 Apologizes, Admits He \"Needs Professional Help\" After Slushii Drama|date=October 10, 2018|work=Your EDM|access-date=October 13, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Name origin==\nZimmerman's father claims that when his son was in his early teens, he was chatting with a friend on his computer, which then abruptly shut off. According to Zimmerman's father, he said that it had a smell of burnt wire and had a strange odour. Zimmerman started to dismantle his computer and happened to find a dead mouse. Zimmerman then became known as the \"dead mouse guy\" among friends. He tried to change his name to \"Deadmouse\" in an online chat room, but it was too long, so he shortened it to \"Deadmau5\". \"Maus\" is the German word for \"mouse\" and is pronounced the same as in English; the ending 5 instead of an 's' is a form of [[leet]].<ref name=\"aritcle0101\" />\n\nZimmerman created the original logo\u2014called \"mau5head\"\u2014while learning how to use some 3D modelling software.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/video/2010/may/28/deadmau5|title=Paul Morley meets deadmau5 \u2013 The Guardian|accessdate=October 1, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615072350/http://www.theguardian.com/music/video/2010/may/28/deadmau5|archivedate=June 15, 2015}}</ref> The logo appears in many different colors and designs, and has been shown on the cover art of most of Zimmerman's albums. He was given the idea to wear a headdress based on the logo by one of his friends, [[Jay Gordon]] of the industrial metal band [[Orgy (band)|Orgy]]. In an interview with [[CBC Television]], Zimmerman said that he wants his logo to be an \"icon\". Fans often attend Deadmau5 concerts sporting their own copy of the Mau5head.\n\nHe created his website and began uploading songs to SectionZ and producing under the alias \"Deadmau5\" in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sectionz.com/detail.asp?rType=mp3&SZID=2720 |title=SectionZ Electronic Music Community \u2013 All Computer Music Enthusiasts Welcome |publisher=Web.archive.org |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070818172810/http://www.sectionz.com/detail.asp?rType=mp3&SZID=2720 |archivedate=August 18, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===DirtyCircuit===\nIn 2008, an artist called DirtyCircuit claimed to have been threatened with legal action after using a sample called \"LP_Faxing Berlin C_128bpm\"<ref name=\"createdigitalmusic.com\">{{cite web |url=http://createdigitalmusic.com/2008/12/01/all-fruity-no-loops-fl-studio-to-remove-all-melodic-samples/ |title=All Fruity, No Loops: FL Studio to Remove All Melodic Samples; Murky License, Content |publisher=Create Digital Music |date=November 20, 2008 |accessdate=June 5, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808090527/http://createdigitalmusic.com/2008/12/01/all-fruity-no-loops-fl-studio-to-remove-all-melodic-samples/ |archivedate=August 8, 2010  }}</ref> that came bundled with [[FL Studio]], and to which Zimmerman claimed copyright.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/tech/fl-studio-user-faces-legal-action-for-using-built-in-samples-183577|title=FL Studio user faces legal action for using built-in samples|author=Ben Rogerson|work=MusicRadar|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409180510/http://www.musicradar.com/news/tech/fl-studio-user-faces-legal-action-for-using-built-in-samples-183577|archivedate=April 9, 2016}}</ref> The sample was a direct clip of a full bar of the song. Zimmerman provided a \"Demo Track\" which came bundled with FL Studio, along with several loop samples. The case caused slight discomfort among the users of FL Studio,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futuremusic.co.uk/page/futuremusic?entry=don_t_use_fl_studio |title=Future Music |publisher=Future Music |date=November 20, 2008 |accessdate=June 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208080231/http://www.futuremusic.co.uk/page/futuremusic?entry=don_t_use_fl_studio |archivedate=December 8, 2008 }}</ref> and some have pointed out potential inconsistencies in the [[EULA]] of the software.<ref name=\"createdigitalmusic.com\" /> Subsequent versions, after FL Studio 8, no longer contained those loop samples.\n\n=== Disney trademark dispute ===\n{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right|width=200|image1=Deadmau5.png|caption1=Deadmau5 logo|image2=Mickey Mouse head and ears.svg|caption2=Basic geometrical representation of Mickey Mouse's head and ears}}\nIn a 2012 interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Zimmerman acknowledged possible similarities between his Mau5head logo and that of [[Mickey Mouse]], joking that \"someone at the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] patent office fell asleep on that one.\"<ref name=guardian-mickeymau5/>\n\nIn March 2014, it was reported that The Walt Disney Company had filed a request with the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] to investigate Zimmerman's application to register the Mau5head emblem as a [[trademark]], noting its resemblance to the figure of Mickey Mouse.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gardner|first1=Eriq|title=Is a Mickey Mouse v. Deadmau5 Trademark Battle Brewing?|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-v-mickey-mouse-trademark-692442|accessdate=September 5, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140926022938/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-v-mickey-mouse-trademark-692442|archivedate=September 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Disney takes on DJ deadmau5 over mouse-ears garb|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/09/04/disney-deadmau5-deadmouse-mickey-mouse/15106939/|accessdate=June 30, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220033510/http://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/09/04/disney-deadmau5-deadmouse-mickey-mouse/15106939/|archivedate=February 20, 2015}}</ref> Disney officially filed its opposition in September 2014, arguing that the mark is likely to cause confusion because it is \"nearly identical in appearance, connotation, and overall commercial impression\" to Disney's trademarked iconography of Mickey Mouse. In response to the opposition, Zimmerman attacked Disney on Twitter, arguing that the company thinks of people as being \"stupid\" because \"[they] might confuse an established electronic musician/performer with a cartoon mouse.\"<ref name=guardian-mickeymau5>{{cite news|title=Deadmau5 v Disney: mouse ear logo sparks legal dispute|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/sep/04/deadmau5-disney-mickey-mouse-ear-logo-legal-dispute|accessdate=September 5, 2014|work=The Guardian|date=September 4, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905083153/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/sep/04/deadmau5-disney-mickey-mouse-ear-logo-legal-dispute|archivedate=September 5, 2014}}</ref> Zimmerman also believed that he had been targeted by Disney due to their attempts to \"cash in\" on the EDM market, specifically alluding to ''[[Dconstructed]]''\u2014a recently released compilation album containing remixes of music from Disney properties by major electronic musicians such as [[Armin van Buuren]], [[Avicii]] and [[Kaskade]].<ref name=rollingstone-disneycd/>\n\nOn September 4, 2014, Zimmerman revealed on Twitter that Disney had used \"Ghosts 'n' Stuff\" in a Mickey Mouse \"re-micks\" video on their website and YouTube channel without his or his labels' permission, and posted pictures showing a [[DMCA takedown notice|takedown notice]] that had been sent to Disney by his lawyers. The letter also contained a trademark infringement accusation, arguing that the use of Deadmau5's name in material regarding the video falsely implied his endorsement of it. Disney argued that it had properly licensed the song and that there was \"no merit to his statement.\"<ref name=rollingstone-disneycd>{{cite news|title=Deadmau5 Sends Cease and Desist to Disney Over 'Infringing Video'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/deadmau5-cease-desist-disney-20140905|accessdate=September 6, 2014|work=Rolling Stone|date=September 5, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906123032/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/deadmau5-cease-desist-disney-20140905|archivedate=September 6, 2014}}</ref><ref name=inthemix-pwnage>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 drops some \"complete pwnage\" on Disney in legal war|url=http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/58904/Deadmau5_ramps_up_legal_war_against_Disney_with_Cease_Desist|website=inthemix.com.au|accessdate=September 5, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905075707/http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/58904/Deadmau5_ramps_up_legal_war_against_Disney_with_Cease_Desist|archivedate=September 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn an October 2014 USPTO filing, Zimmerman argued that Disney has attempted to co-exist with him in goodwill. Zimmerman presented evidence that Disney had been in contact with him regarding potential collaborative projects, including an offer to participate in a \"re-imagining\" of ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]'' as a live concert tour for the film's 75th anniversary.<ref name=billboard-deadmau5documents>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Says Archenemy Disney Wanted His Help on 'Fantasia' Anniversary|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-says-disney-approached-him-740615|website=Billboard.biz|accessdate=October 15, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016191046/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-says-disney-approached-him-740615|archivedate=October 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Zimmerman's attorney stated that he and Disney had \"amicably resolved their dispute.\"<ref name=thr-settled>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5, Disney Settle Dispute Over \"Mouse Head\" Logo|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-disney-settle-dispute-mouse-804072|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=June 22, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224051428/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-disney-settle-dispute-mouse-804072|archivedate=December 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Meowingtons trademark dispute ===\nIn 2015, Zimmerman attempted to register a trademark for the name of his pet cat, Professor Meowingtons, whom he adopted in 2010 and has incorporated into some of his own merchandising. However, the registration was rejected due to a pre-existing Meowingtons trademark held by an online retailer of the same name established in 2014,<ref name=\"thr-meowingtons\"/> which sells cat-themed accessories and clothing. After discovering the trademark, Zimmerman petitioned against it, citing his pre-existing uses.<ref name=\"billboard-meowingtonstm\">{{cite web|title=deadmau5 Files Trademark Petition to Protect His Cat Meowingtons' Brand|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7640508/deadmau5-files-trademark-petition-protect-cat-meowingtons-brand|website=Billboard|accessdate=March 26, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320015034/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7640508/deadmau5-files-trademark-petition-protect-cat-meowingtons-brand|archivedate=March 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Zimmerman was sued by Emma Bassiri (the owner of the website) for trademark infringement and unfair competition; the suit argued that claims by Zimmerman that she had named the site specifically after the cat was false. Zimmerman himself told ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' that \"from the very beginning I was working to find a way to resolve this situation amicably\", but that he had been forced to \"litigate this woman out of existence\".<ref name=\"thr-meowingtons\">{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Sued Over 'Meowingtons' Trademark|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-sued-meowingtons-trademark-986054|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=March 26, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326140129/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-sued-meowingtons-trademark-986054|archivedate=March 26, 2017}}</ref> On May 15, 2017, Deadmau5 filed a countersuit against Bassiri with the intention of seeking forfeiture of Bassiri's website and domain name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Escalates 'Meowingtons' Trademark Cat Fight With Countersuit|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7793109/deadmau5-meowingtons-trademark-countersuit|website=Billboard|accessdate=June 1, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519084108/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7793109/deadmau5-meowingtons-trademark-countersuit|archivedate=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, World Intellectual Property Review reported that Zimmerman and Bassiri had resolved their dispute.<ref>{{cite web|title=Claws sheathed in Deadmau5 cat fight|url=https://www.worldipreview.com/news/deadmau5-cat-fight-settled-15572|website=World Intellectual Property Review|accessdate=April 29, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705052849/https://www.worldipreview.com/news/deadmau5-cat-fight-settled-15572|archivedate=July 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Offensive slurs===\nIn October 2018, Zimmerman posted comments on Twitter during an argument including the statements \"I\u2019ll bet you suck a guy off for 40 grand zero fucking questions asked\" and \"women don't posses {{sic}} penises\". These comments were construed by readers as being homophobic and transphobic.<ref name=\"EDM\">{{cite news |first1= |title=deadmau5 Accused of Making Transphobic Remarks During Online Argument|url=https://edm.com/news/deadmau5-transphobic-remarks-online-argument |accessdate=25 February 2019 |publisher=EDM.com |date=8 October 2018}}</ref> Zimmerman apologized for his comments, saying that he \"wasn't trying to make blatant transphobic statements\", and had \"just got into a heated arguement {{sic}} with some dude online\", noting that his comments had been taken \"somewhere unintended\".<ref name=\"Duffy\">{{cite news |last1=Duffy |first1=Nick|title=Deadmau5 walks back \u2018homophobic, transphobic\u2019 comments|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/10/08/deadmau5-homophobic-transphobic-comments/ |accessdate=25 February 2019 |publisher=PinkNews |date=8 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nA few days later during a gaming stream he referred to a track by artist [[Slushii]] as \"AIDS fucking music\" and calling it \"autistic shit\". Slushii \u2013 who is on the [[autism spectrum]] \u2013 responded to these comments on Twitter, calling them \"really disappointing\".<ref name=\"Martin\">{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Laura |title=Deadmau5 forced to apologise for disgusting Aids and autism slurs |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/deadmau5-forced-apologise-disgusting-aids-13399028 |accessdate=25 February 2019 |publisher=Mirror Online |date=11 October 2018}}</ref> Zimmerman later apologized for these comments, citing mental health issues that required \"professional help\", and stating that he would take time \"off the radar\" to \"work on [himself]\".<ref name=\"Meadow\">{{cite news |last1=Meadow |first1=Matthew |title=Deadmau5 Addresses His Recent Insensitive Tweets In Statement Admitting He \"Needs Help\" |url=https://www.youredm.com/2018/10/10/deadmau5-addresses-his-recent-insensitive-tweets-in-statement-admitting-he-needs-help/ |accessdate=25 February 2019 |publisher=YourEDM |date=10 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, whilst playing ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]'' on a livestream on [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]], Zimmerman called another player a \"fucking cock-sucking stream sniper fag.\"<ref name=\"Cameron\">{{cite news |last1=Cameron |first1=John |title=DEADMAU5 USES HATE SPEECH DURING PUBG LIVE STREAM |url=https://edm.com/news/deadmau5-hate-speech-pubg-twitch |accessdate=18 February 2019 |publisher=EDM |date=11 February 2019}}</ref> Twitch banned Zimmerman from the platform for hate speech, after which Zimmerman posted: \"I know who I am, and I don\u2019t have to fucking sit here and cry and defend my fucking self with the obligatory 'I'm not that person, I am sorry' reflex.\"<ref name=\"Jackman\">{{cite news |last1=Jackman |first1=Josh |title=Deadmau5 deletes Twitch account after \u2018c**k-sucking fag\u2019 rant |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/02/13/deadmau5-deletes-twitch-sucking-fag-rant/ |accessdate=18 February 2019 |publisher=Pink News |date=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Deadmau5 discography}}\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Get Scraped]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Vexillology (album)|Vexillology]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Random Album Title]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[For Lack of a Better Name]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[4\u00d74=12]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Album Title Goes Here]]''<!--- Album title should not be stylized ---> (2012)\n* ''[[While(1 Is Less Than 2)|While(1<2)]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[W:/2016Album/]]'' (2016)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Deadmau5}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Music|Canada}}\n*[[List of ambient music artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n111. [https://gamerrewind.com/2020/03/23/how-to-fix-pubg-lite-not-available-in-your-region/ How To Fix Pubg Lite Not Available In Your Region] GamerRewind. Retrieved April 04, 2020.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Deadmau5}}\n* {{official website|http://www.deadmau5.com}}\n* [http://www.ultrarecords.com/artists/deadmau5/ Artist Site at Ultra Records]\n\n{{Deadmau5}}\n{{DJ Award for Best International DJ |state=collapsed}}\n{{DJ Award for Best Electro DJ |state=collapsed}}\n{{Mau5trap}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Deadmau5]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian musicians]]\n[[Category:Ableton Live users]]\n[[Category:Canadian DJs]]\n[[Category:Canadian electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian house musicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Swiss-German descent]]\n[[Category:Electro house musicians]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music DJs]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Dance Recording of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Masked musicians]]\n[[Category:Mau5trap artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:People from Niagara Falls, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Remixers]]\n[[Category:Tracker musicians]]\n[[Category:Ultra Records artists]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records artists]]\n[[Category:Progressive house musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{good article}}\n{{short description|Canadian musician}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- For individuals; see Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Deadmau5\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = File:Deadmau5 d.jpg\n| landscape           = yes\n| alt                 = DJ with a mouse head mask performing live \n| caption             = Deadmau5 in 2014\n| birth_name          = Joel Thomas Zimmerman\n| alias               = {{hlist|Halcyon441|Karma K|Testpilot<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixmag.net/words/news/deadmau5-joins-richie-hawtins-label-under-testpilot-alias|title=Deadmau5 joins Richie Hawtin's label under testpilot alias|publisher=[[Mixmag]]|date=March 4, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307065224/http://www.mixmag.net/words/news/deadmau5-joins-richie-hawtins-label-under-testpilot-alias|archivedate=March 7, 2014}}</ref>}}\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1981|1|5}}\n| birth_place         = [[Niagara Falls, Ontario]], Canada\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Progressive house]]|[[electro house]]|[[Electronic music|electronic]]}}\n| occupation          = {{hlist|[[Record producer]]|[[Disc jockey|DJ]]|[[musician]]}}\n| instrument          = {{hlist|[[Synthesizer]]|[[keyboard instrument|keyboard]]|[[piano]]| [[digital audio workstation]]|[[Programming (music)|programming]]}}\n| years_active        = 1998\u2013present\n| label               = {{hlist|[[Mau5trap]]|[[Virgin EMI Records|Virgin EMI]]|[[Ultra Music|Ultra]]|[[Astralwerks]]|[[Ministry of Sound]]|[[SongBird]]|[[Play Records|Play]]|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]|[[Parlophone]]}}\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|[[Kaskade]]|[[Rob Swire]]|[[Wolfgang Gartner]]|BSOD|WTF?|[[Eric Prydz]]}}\n| website             = {{URL|deadmau5.com}}\n| module          = \n  {{Infobox person\n   | child       = yes\n   | spouse      = {{marriage|Kelly Fedoni|2017}}\n   | residence   = [[Campbellville, Ontario|Campbellville]]; [[Milton, Ontario]], Canada\n  }}\n}}\n'''Joel Thomas Zimmerman''' (born January 5, 1981),<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/deadmau5 |title=Deadmau5 |first=Laura |last=Stanley |encyclopedia=The Canadian Encyclopedia |date=July 9, 2015 |access-date=January 2, 2019 }}</ref> known professionally as '''Deadmau5''' (stylized as '''deadmau5'''; pronounced \"dead mouse\"), is a Canadian [[electronic music]] producer, DJ, and musician. Zimmerman mainly produces [[progressive house]] music and sometimes other forms of [[electronic music]]. His works have been included in compilation albums such as [[Ti\u00ebsto]]'s ''[[In Search of Sunrise 6: Ibiza]]'' and presented on [[Armin van Buuren]]'s ''[[A State of Trance]]'' radio show.\n\nZimmerman has received six [[Grammy Award]] nominations for his work. He has worked with other DJs and producers, such as [[Kaskade]], MC Flipside, [[Rob Swire]] and [[Wolfgang Gartner]]. He has also collaborated with [[Steve Duda]] under the group name BSOD (Better Sounding On Drugs), and was part of the group named WTF? with Duda, [[Tommy Lee]], and DJ Aero. In 2007, he founded his own record label, [[Mau5trap]]. Deadmau5 is currently one of the highest paid electronic music producers in the world,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/pictures/eeel45jfeg/6-deadmau5-11-5-million/|title=Deadmau5 ($11.5 million) \u2013 In Photos: The World's Highest-Paid DJs|author=Zack O'Malley Greenburg|work=Forbes|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404230217/http://www.forbes.com/pictures/eeel45jfeg/6-deadmau5-11-5-million/|archivedate=April 4, 2016}}</ref> and is a masked music artist similar to [[Marshmello]] and [[Daft Punk]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thump.vice.com/en_us/article/masked-djs-history-orbital-deadmau5-daft-punk-marshmello|title=A Brief History of Masked DJs\u2014From Orbital to Marshmello|date=November 29, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130165129/http://thump.vice.com/en_us/article/masked-djs-history-orbital-deadmau5-daft-punk-marshmello|archivedate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, an early 12\" single produced on vinyl titled \"I Don't Want No Other\" was released by Joel Zimmerman and Derek Caesar under the group name Dred and Karma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://trc.daily-beat.com/lifestyle/2015/01/first-ever-deadmau5-tracks-pressed-vinyl-play-de-record/|title=Unearthing First Ever Deadmau5 Tracks Pressed on Vinyl at Play de Record|last=Hooper|first=Kurtis|date=14 January 2015|website=Daily Beat Media|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref> A 2006 compilation album titled ''[[Deadmau5 Circa 1998\u20132002]]'' was self-released under the alias Halcyon441.<ref>{{cite web|title=Listen to \"Hiatus Fantasy\" \u2013 The longest deadmau5 song ever released|work=[[Dancing Astronaut]]|url=http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2016/10/listen-longest-deadmau5-song-ever-released/|accessdate=February 14, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215023632/http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2016/10/listen-longest-deadmau5-song-ever-released/|archivedate=February 15, 2018}}</ref> His debut studio album, ''[[Get Scraped]]'' was released in 2005, with follow-up ''[[Vexillology (album)|Vexillology]]'' in 2006. His breakthrough, ''[[Random Album Title]]'', was released in 2008 and was [[List of music recording certifications|certified gold]] in Canada, and silver the United Kingdom. The album includes seminal release \"[[Faxing Berlin]]\", \"[[Not Exactly]]\", and moderate chart hit \"[[I Remember (Deadmau5 and Kaskade song)|I Remember]]\" (with [[Kaskade]]). In 2009, his fourth studio album ''[[For Lack of a Better Name]]'' was released to critical acclaim, featuring [[Rob Swire]] collaboration \"[[Ghosts 'n' Stuff]]\", \"Hi Friend\", and the critically acclaimed \"[[Strobe (instrumental)|Strobe]]\". His fifth studio album, ''[[4\u00d74=12]]'', released in late 2010, supported by singles \"[[Some Chords]]\", \"[[Animal Rights (instrumental)|Animal Rights]]\", \"[[Sofi Needs a Ladder]]\", and \"[[Raise Your Weapon]]\".\n\nIn 2012, Zimmerman released singles \"[[The Veldt (song)|The Veldt]]\" and \"[[Professional Griefers]]\" (featuring [[Gerard Way]]) to commercial success. These singles were featured on his sixth studio album, ''[[Album Title Goes Here]]''. Following departure from long-time label [[Ultra Music|Ultra Records]], Zimmerman released his seventh studio album, ''[[While(1 Is Less Than 2)|While(1<2)]]'' through [[Astralwerks]] and [[Virgin EMI]] in 2014. The album's release was supported by its four singles; \"[[Avaritia (instrumental)|Avaritia]]\", \"[[Seeya (Deadmau5 song)|Seeya]]\", \"[[Infra Turbo Pigcart Racer]]\", and \"[[Phantoms Can't Hang]]\". After a brief hiatus, Zimmerman's eighth studio album, ''[[W:/2016Album/]]'' was released in late 2016, with singles \"[[Snowcone (instrumental)|Snowcone]]\" and \"[[Let Go (Deadmau5 song)|Let Go]]\".\n\n==Early life==\nZimmerman was born in [[Niagara Falls, Ontario|Niagara Falls]], Ontario, Canada.<ref>{{citation|last=Birtles|first=Bryan|title=Deadmau5|url=http://www.vueweekly.com/music/story/deadmau5/|work=Vue Weekly|issue=793|accessdate=May 3, 2011|date=December 29, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103034700/http://www.vueweekly.com/music/story/deadmau5/|archivedate=November 3, 2013}}</ref> His mother, Nancy (n\u00e9e Johnson), is a visual artist, and his father, Rodney Thomas \"Rod\" Zimmerman, is a [[General Motors]] plant worker.<ref name=\"article01023\">{{cite web|last=Liss |first=Sarah |url=http://www.torontolife.com/daily/hype/print-edition/2011/11/01/man-in-the-mouse-deadmau5-profile/3/ |title=How Deadmau5\u2014a.k.a. DJ Joel Zimmerman\u2014came to make $100,000 a show and have four million Facebook fans \u00ab Page 3 of 6 |publisher=torontolife.com |date=November 1, 2011 |accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"genad1\">{{cite web |url=http://users.start.ca/users/bhurdle/fretz/dat87.html#2 |title=Genealogy Data |publisher=Start.ca |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006172624/http://users.start.ca/users/bhurdle/fretz/dat87.html#2 |archivedate=October 6, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He has two siblings, Jennifer (older) and Chris (younger).<ref name=\"article01023\" /> His ancestry includes [[German Canadian|German]], Swiss, and English.<ref name=\"genad1\" /><ref>{{cite web |publisher=nurun.com |url=http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2010/01/28/builder-first-to-skate-in-memorial-arena |title=Builder first to skate in Memorial Arena |work=Niagara Falls Review |date=January 28, 2010 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620042701/http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2010/01/28/builder-first-to-skate-in-memorial-arena |archivedate=June 20, 2013  }}</ref> He received his first keyboard for Christmas when he was a teenager.<ref name=\"article01023\" /><ref name=\"aritcle0101\">{{cite web |publisher=nurun.com |url=http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2011/10/30/deadmau5-rejects-his-father-and-grandfathers-advice-about-getting-a-real-job |title=deadmau5 rejects his father and grandfather's a... |work=Niagara Falls Review |date=October 30, 2011 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620021135/http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2011/10/30/deadmau5-rejects-his-father-and-grandfathers-advice-about-getting-a-real-job |archivedate=June 20, 2013  }}</ref> His music career began in the late 1990s, with a [[chiptune]] and [[demoscene]] movements-influenced sound with the [[Impulse Tracker]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.residentadvisor.net/feature.aspx?972 |publisher=residentadvisor.net |title=Deadmau5: It's complicated |date=September 30, 2008 |first=Todd L. |last=Burns |accessdate=September 3, 2014 |quote=''I was in my Mom's basement tooling away on Impulse Tracker on a 386 just doing Nintendo music until some Loop Library company hired me as a producer.'' |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007010942/http://www.residentadvisor.net/feature.aspx?972 |archivedate=October 7, 2014  }}</ref> \nZimmerman graduated from [[Westlane Secondary School]] in Niagara Falls. He then worked with an online music licensing company and as a programmer. He adopted the name Deadmau5, which referred to a dead mouse he found in his computer.<ref name=\"law\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Law |publisher=Welland Tribune |url=http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2010/11/24/deadmau5-the-mouse-that-roared |title=Deadmau5: The mouse that roared |newspaper=Niagara Falls Review |date=November 25, 2010 |accessdate=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614082908/http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2010/11/24/deadmau5-the-mouse-that-roared |archivedate=June 14, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===1998\u20132006: ''Get Scraped'' and self-released compilations===\nZimmerman released his debut studio album, titled ''[[Get Scraped]]'' on July 26, 2005. The tracks \"Just Before 8bit\", \"Nice Try, Kiddo\" and \"Uploading and Downloading\" from ''[[Project 56 (album)|Project 56]]'' were edited and expanded upon in ''Get Scraped'' under the names \"8bit\", \"Try Again\", and \"Unspecial Effects\", respectively. Tracks \"Bored of Canada\", \"Intelstat\" and \"I Forget\" reappear on this album as is, as well as \"The Oshawa Connection\" from ''[[Deadmau5 Circa 1998\u20132002]]''.\n\nThree self-released compilations, ''Project 56'', ''Deadmau5 Circa 1998\u20132002'', and ''[[A Little Oblique]]'', were finished in 2006, with ''Project 56'' seeing an official release two years later.\n\n===2006\u201308: ''Vexillology'', Mau5trap, and ''Random Album Title''===\n[[File:Deadmau5 live.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Deadmau5 at Coachella 2008]]\nIn 2006, Zimmerman released his second studio album, ''[[Vexillology (album)|Vexillology]]'', on November 6, 2006 through [[Play Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/vexillology/id844225367|title=Vexillology on iTunes|accessdate=March 28, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329051252/https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/vexillology/id844225367|archivedate=March 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Zimmerman founded his own record label, [[Mau5trap]], which, along with [[Ultra Records]] and [[Ministry of Sound]], released the 2008 album ''[[Random Album Title]]'', which saw the collaboration of Zimmerman and Chicago producer [[Kaskade]] with \"[[I Remember (Deadmau5 and Kaskade song)|I Remember]]\". ''Random Album Title'', saw a digital release on September 2, 2008, via [[Ultra Records]] in the United States and [[Ministry of Sound]] in the United Kingdom and Europe. Physical copies of the album were released in November 2008. Singles \"[[Faxing Berlin]]\" on October 25, 2006, and \"[[Not Exactly (song)|Not Exactly]]\" on August 27, 2007, were released prior to the album's release. Single \"I Remember\" (with Kaskade) was later released on September 15, 2008, before the album's release.\n\nIn the United States, Zimmerman's collaboration with [[Kaskade]], \"[[Move for Me]]\", reached number one on ''Billboard'' magazine's [[Dance/Mix Show Airplay]] chart in its September 6, 2008, issue.<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Deadmau5|chart=Dance/Mix Show Airplay}}|title= Current Hot Dance Airplay|work=Billboard}}</ref> Since then, Zimmerman has seen two more tracks, also collaborations (\"I Remember\" with [[Kaskade]] and \"[[Ghosts 'n' Stuff]]\" with [[Rob Swire]]), reach number one on ''Billboard''{{'}}s Dance/Mix Show Airplay chart, making him the only Canadian to have three number-one tracks on that chart. He is also the sixth Canadian to top that chart, following [[Deborah Cox]], [[Nelly Furtado]], [[Dragonette]], [[Justin Bieber]], and [[The Weeknd]], each with one apiece.\n\n===2009\u201311: ''For Lack of a Better Name'' and ''4\u00d74=12''===\n[[File:Deadmau5 LED Cube.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Deadmau5 performing at the Austin Music Hall, 2011]]\nOn September 22, 2009, [[Ultra Records]] released his album ''[[For Lack of a Better Name]]'' in the United States, and October 5 internationally. On a subsequent tour in the fall of 2009, Zimmerman's performances were recorded and made available for sale immediately following the concerts on USB wristband flash drives. ''For Lack of a Better Name'' includes two of Zimmerman's most popular songs, \"Ghosts 'n' Stuff\" (featuring Rob Swire) and \"[[Strobe (instrumental)|Strobe]]\". \"Ghosts 'n' Stuff\" was released on November 25, 2008, before the album, while \"Strobe\" was released on February 23, 2010, after the album's release.\n\nMTV named Zimmerman as the house DJ for the [[2010 MTV Video Music Awards]] and MTV PUSH artist of the week on August 16, 2010. He expressed gratitude towards [[Lady Gaga]] and [[David Guetta]] for bringing dance into the pop music scene and paving the way for him to the mainstream.<ref name=\"houseartist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1645817/deadmau5-named-house-artist-2010-mtv-vmas.jhtml|title=Deadmau5 Named House Artist For 2010 MTV VMAs|date=August 16, 2010|accessdate=January 21, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520043504/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1645817/deadmau5-named-house-artist-2010-mtv-vmas.jhtml|archivedate=May 20, 2011}}</ref> At the awards, Zimmerman performed with [[Jason Derulo]] and [[Travie McCoy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1647609/deadmau5-marvels-at-scope-vma-houseartist-gig.jhtml|title=Deadmau5 Marvels At 'Scope' Of VMA House-Artist Gig|first=James|last=Montgomery|date=September 11, 2010|accessdate=January 21, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113040546/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1647609/deadmau5-marvels-at-scope-vma-houseartist-gig.jhtml|archivedate=January 13, 2011}}</ref> His song \"Ghosts 'n' Stuff\" had been featured on the soundtrack for the MTV reality series ''[[Jersey Shore (TV series)|Jersey Shore]]'' earlier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/08/16/push-artist-of-the-week-dead-mau5/|title=PUSH Artist of the Week: deadmau5|date=September 11, 2010|accessdate=January 21, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030094325/http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2010/08/16/push-artist-of-the-week-dead-mau5/|archivedate=October 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHis fifth studio album, ''[[4\u00d74=12]]'', was released on December 6, 2010, in the United Kingdom and December 7, 2010, in the United States. Singles \"[[Some Chords]]\" on May 3, 2010, \"[[Animal Rights (song)|Animal Rights]]\" (with [[Wolfgang Gartner]]) on September 6, and \"[[Sofi Needs a Ladder]]\" (featuring [[Sofia Toufa|SOFI]]) on November 1 were released and were featured on the album. \"[[Raise Your Weapon]]\" (featuring [[Greta Svabo Bech]]) was released later on May 23, 2011. \"Some Chords\" was featured on an episode of ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'' where Zimmerman made a cameo appearance, and an instrumental version of \"Sofi Needs a Ladder\" was featured in the film ''[[The Hangover Part II]]''. That year, he also released two non-album singles \"[[Aural Psynapse]]\" and \"HR 8938 Cephei\".\n\n===2012\u201314: ''Album Title Goes Here'' and ''While(1<2)''===\n[[File:Deadmau5 - Rock in Rio Madrid 2012 - 02.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Deadmau5 performing at [[Rock in Rio]] in [[Madrid]], 2012]]\n\nOn August 9, 2012, Zimmerman announced his sixth studio album, ''[[Album Title Goes Here]]'', which was released on September 24 of that year.<ref>{{cite web |author=Jesse Grushack |url=http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2012/08/deadmau5-to-release-album-title-goes-here-on-sept-25/ |title=Deadmau5 to release 'album title goes here' on Sept. 25 |publisher=Dancingastronaut.com |date=August 9, 2012 |accessdate=August 10, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812001909/http://www.dancingastronaut.com/2012/08/deadmau5-to-release-album-title-goes-here-on-sept-25/ |archivedate=August 12, 2012  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/480527/deadmau5s-album-title-gets-fall-release|work=Billboard|title=Deadmau5's 'Album Title' Gets Fall Release|first=Billboard|last=Staff|date=August 9, 2012|accessdate=August 9, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330042956/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/480527/deadmau5s-album-title-gets-fall-release|archivedate=March 30, 2013}}</ref> Singles from this album include \"[[Maths (instrumental)|Maths]]\" on February 17, 2012, \"[[The Veldt (song)|The Veldt]]\" (featuring Chris James) on May 8, and \"[[Professional Griefers]]\" (featuring [[Gerard Way]]) on August 14. Singles \"[[Channel 42 (instrumental)|Channel 42]]\" (with Wolfgang Gartner) on February 12, 2013, and \"[[Telemiscommunications]]\" (with [[Imogen Heap]]) on March 12 were released in 2013, after the album was released. His collaboration with Gerard Way on \"Professional Griefers\" was announced on Facebook prior to release. In December 2012, [[FUSE TV]] named \"Professional Griefers\" one of the top 40 songs of 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fuse.tv/2012/12/fuse-staff-picks-best-songs-of-2012#19 |title=The 40 Best Songs of 2012: Fuse Staff Picks \u2013 Fuse |publisher=Fuse.tv |date=December 24, 2012 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129063607/http://www.fuse.tv/2012/12/fuse-staff-picks-best-songs-of-2012#19 |archivedate=January 29, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Zimmerman deleted three years worth of music from his SoundCloud account, replacing them with an EP of seven melancholy piano sonatas, simply called ''7'', named after the Latin translations for the [[seven deadly sins]]: \"Acedia\", \"Avaritia\", \"Gula\", \"Invidia\", \"Ira\", \"Luxuria\", and \"Superbia\".<ref name=\"Tregoning\">{{cite news |last=Tregoning |first=Jack |url=http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/57212/In_other_Deadmau5_news_his_twodisc_epiclength_album_is_done |title=inthemix: In other Deadmau5 news, his two-disc, epic-length album is done |work=inthemix |date=January 7, 2014 |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116054627/http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/57212/In_other_Deadmau5_news_his_twodisc_epiclength_album_is_done |archivedate=January 16, 2014  }}</ref> Also in November 2013, Zimmerman left longtime label Ultra Records and signed with record label [[Astralwerks]], the famed NYC-based imprint that houses artists such as [[Swedish House Mafia]], [[David Guetta]], and [[The Chemical Brothers]]. Speaking on the partnership, Zimmerman admitted, \"I found a place that knows what to do with my music.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Buyanovsky |first=Dan |url=http://revolt.tv/news/deadmau5-teases-new-album-and-massive-2014-tour/99A22A8B-1DAC-4C8F-8598-1552B2200B74 |title=REVOLT.TV: Deadmau5 Teases New Album And Massive 2014 Tour |work=REVOLT.TV |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140121030749/http://revolt.tv/news/deadmau5-teases-new-album-and-massive-2014-tour/99A22A8B-1DAC-4C8F-8598-1552B2200B74 |archivedate=January 21, 2014  }}</ref>\n\nOn January 7, 2014, Zimmerman announced via his Twitter account that his much-anticipated new album is complete. \"In other news... I finished my album today,\" the tweet read. \"2 discs. 2 continuous mixes. 25 tracks. and something I'm proud of.\"<ref name=\"Tregoning\"/> On May 10, 2014, Deadmau5 announced through his subscription service that his upcoming album would be titled ''[[While(1 Is Less Than 2)|While(1<2)]]'' and would be released on June 17, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youredm.com/2014/05/10/deadmau5-announces-album-title-release-date/|title=Deadmau5 Announces Album Title And Release Date|author=Matthew Meadow|work=Your EDM|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401123155/http://www.youredm.com/2014/05/10/deadmau5-announces-album-title-release-date|archivedate=April 1, 2016}}</ref> The album was preceded by the release of four singles: \"[[Avaritia (song)|Avaritia]]\", \"[[Seeya (Deadmau5 song)|Seeya]]\" (featuring [[Colleen D'Agostino]]), \"[[Infra Turbo Pigcart Racer]]\" and \"[[Phantoms Can't Hang]]\". Starting on the week of May 20, 2014, each single was released weekly for a total of four weeks leading up to the release of the album.\n\n=== 2015\u201316: Depression, return, and ''W:/2016Album/''===\n[[File:Deamau5 at Veld Music Festival (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|240px|Deadmau5 performing on the Cube stage at [[VELD Music Festival]] in 2016]]\nOn January 13, 2015, it was announced that Deadmau5 would be a headlining act for the Bonnaroo Music and Arts Festival, in Manchester, Tennessee, which was held on June 11\u201315, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author=Weingarten, Christopher R|year=2015|title=Bonnaroo 2015: Billy Joel, Mumford and Sons, Deadmau5 Lead Lineup|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bonnaroo-2015-billy-joel-mumford-and-sons-deadmau5-lead-lineup-67451/|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ferreras, Jesse|year=2015|title=Bonnaroo 2015 Lineup: Billy Joel, Mumford & Sons, Deadmau5 Among Headliners|work=[[Huffington Post]]|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/01/13/bonnaroo-2015-lineup-billy-joel-mumford_n_6467306.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer_us=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvLnVrLw&guce_referrer_cs=j6Uk-VETUCOD8e0uM3r6HA|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> On February 2, 2015, it was announced he would appear at Reading and Leeds Festivals.<ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 \u2013 Acts \u2013 Reading + Leeds Festivals|work=[[BBC Music]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/events/ernxj5/acts/az5hj5|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The 20 Best Bands At Reading And Leeds 2015 In Order Of Greatness|author=Barker, Emily|year=2015|work=[[NME]]|url=https://www.nme.com/photos/the-20-best-bands-at-reading-and-leeds-2015-in-order-of-greatness-voted-for-by-nme-readers-1422764|accessdate=July 20, 2018}}</ref> On July 23, 2015, [[Valve Corporation|Valve]] announced that Deadmau5 was creating a series of sound clips to be featured in their video game ''[[Dota 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=McCarthy, Will|year=2015|title=Deadmau5 releases an album\u2019s worth of new music for \u2018Dota 2\u2019|work=[[Dancing Astronaut]]|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2015/07/deadmau5-dota-2/|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> The music pack was released alongside the announcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.dota2.com/2015/07/deadmau5-dieback-music-pack/|title=deadmau5 dieback music pack \u2013 Dota 2|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724080921/http://blog.dota2.com/2015/07/deadmau5-dieback-music-pack/|archivedate=July 24, 2015}}</ref> On August 8, 2015, Deadmau5 performed live at [[KeyArena]] in [[Seattle]] at the conclusion of the [[Dota 2]] competition [[The International 5]] (TI5).<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Trolls Millions At Surprise Dota 2 Finals Performance, Faces Backlash From Gamers|author=Sachs, Elliot|year=2015|url=https://www.youredm.com/2015/08/09/deadmau5-trolls-millions-at-surprise-dota-2-finals-performance-faces-backlash-from-gamers/|work=YourEDM|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Trolls DOTA 2 Finals With 'Levels' During Surprise Performance|author=Middleton, Ryan|work=Music Times|url=https://www.musictimes.com/articles/45106/20150809/deadmau5-dota-2-finals-levels-during-surprise-performance-soundtrack.htm|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> On October 7, 2015, Deadmau5 officially announced that he was leaving his then label Astralwerks and going entirely independent with his own label Mau5trap.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Leaves Astralwerks for Indie Platform|work=EDMTunes|url=https://www.edmtunes.com/2015/10/deadmau5-leaves-astralwerks-for-indie-platform/|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 17, 2015, it appeared that Zimmerman was either taking a leave of absence or ending his career altogether after deleting both his Twitter and Facebook accounts.<ref>{{cite web|author=Goldstien, Danielle|year=2015|title=Deadmau5 quits social media following Bieber rant and uploads new tracks|work=[[NME]]|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/deadmau5-2-4-1201158|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Diep, Eric|year=2015|title=Deadmau5 Deletes His Twitter and Facebook Following Justin Bieber Rant|work=Complex|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2015/12/deadmau-5-delete-twitter-facebook-new-track|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> His Instagram account, however, had not been deleted.<ref name=\"complexx\">{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Reveals Why He Deleted All of His Social Media|work=Complex|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2015/12/deadmau5-explains-why-he-deleted-all-of-his-social-media|author=Morris, Jessie|year=2015|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> On December 21, 2015, Zimmerman reopened his Twitter account and posted an apology to his Tumblr account explaining his disappearance from social media, saying that he was suffering from depression and would be returning to producing music after the new year.<ref>{{cite web|author=Britton, Luke Morgan|year=2015|title=Deadmau5 says \u2018sorry for being a dick\u2019 as he reveals struggles with depression|work=NME|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/deadmau5-2-3-1200245|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"complexx\"/>\n\nOn May 27, 2016, \"[[Snowcone (instrumental)|Snowcone]]\", the first single from Zimmerman in nearly two years, was released as a digital download.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7386056/deadmau5-snowcone-first-single-two-years-dance|title=Deadmau5 Releases 'Snowcone', First Single in Two Years|last=Medved|first=Matt|date=May 27, 2016|newspaper=Billboard|access-date=November 13, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129141609/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7386056/deadmau5-snowcone-first-single-two-years-dance|archivedate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> This track was later revealed to be the first single from his next album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmsauce.com/2016/11/04/deadmau5-announces-release-upcoming-album-w2016album/|title=Deadmau5 announces release of upcoming album 'W:/2016ALBUM/'|last=Braat|first=Taylor|date=November 4, 2016|website=EDM Sauce|access-date=November 13, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113181255/http://www.edmsauce.com/2016/11/04/deadmau5-announces-release-upcoming-album-w2016album/|archivedate=November 13, 2016}}</ref> On November 4, 2016, Zimmerman announced his next studio album, ''[[W:/2016Album/]]'', which was released on December 2, 2016, digitally,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7565637/deadmau5-w2016album|title=Deadmau5 Announces First Album Since 2014, 'W:/2016ALBUM/'|newspaper=Billboard|access-date=November 6, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105124400/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7565637/deadmau5-w2016album|archivedate=November 5, 2016}}</ref> with a vinyl and CD release on February 17, and March 17, 2017, respectively.\n\n=== 2017\u2013present: ''Stuff I Used to Do'', ''Where's the Drop?'', ''Polar'' soundtrack and ''Mau5ville''  ===\nOn January 7, 2017, Zimmerman announced a compilation of his earlier work ranging from the years of 1998 to 2007 on Twitter, titled ''[[Stuff I Used to Do]]''. Zimmerman also stated that the compilation would release in February of that year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://djmag.com/news/deadmau5-confirms-february-release-new-album-stuff-i-used-do|title=Deadmau5 Confirms February Release for 'New' Album, 'Stuff I Used to Do'|newspaper=DJ Mag|access-date=January 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110124046/https://djmag.com/news/deadmau5-confirms-february-release-new-album-stuff-i-used-do|archivedate=January 10, 2017}}</ref> On February 24, 2017, Zimmerman released a limited version of ''Stuff I Used to Do'' on [[WeTransfer]]. The edition, available until March 3, featured three tracks less than the full album. The album includes tracks from ''[[Get Scraped]]'' and early compilations, in addition to an alternative mix of \"Creep\" from ''[[While(1 Is Less Than 2)|While(1<2)]]''.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7702005/deadmau5-stuff-i-used-to-do-download|title=Download deadmau5's 'stuff i used to do' Album Via WeTransfer Now|work=Billboard|access-date=March 2, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226175847/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7702005/deadmau5-stuff-i-used-to-do-download|archivedate=February 26, 2017}}</ref> The album was officially released on [[Mau5trap]] a week later, on March 3, 2017.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\nOn March 25, 2017, Zimmerman began a [[concert tour]] with his new \"Cube 2.1\" stage set entitled [[Lots of Shows in a Row]] to promote the release of ''W:/2016Album/''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lots of shows in a row tour - gratefulweb.com|url=http://www.gratefulweb.com/articles/deadmau5-lots-shows-row-tour|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414081439/http://www.gratefulweb.com/articles/deadmau5-lots-shows-row-tour|archivedate=April 14, 2017}}</ref> Zimmerman toured around [[North America]] for two months, before touring the rest of the world from June 3, 2017, and Canada from October 6, 2017, with the tour concluding on October 31, 2017. On August 25, 2017, Zimmerman released a stand-alone single entitled \"[[Legendary (Deadmau5 and Shotty Horroh song)|Legendary]]\", featuring guest vocals from rapper [[Shotty Horroh]].<ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 Growls on 'Legendary' Hip-hop Tune with Shotty Horroh: Listen|work=Billboard|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7942016/deadmau5-new-song-legendary-shotty-horroh|accessdate=September 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026190441/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7942016/deadmau5-new-song-legendary-shotty-horroh|archivedate=October 26, 2017}}</ref> A music video for the song was released on Mau5trap's YouTube channel on September 11, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 x Shotty Horroh \u2013 Legendary [video]|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4c3FH6PheKM|accessdate=September 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171102031246/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4c3FH6PheKM|archivedate=November 2, 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Zimmerman confirmed his next studio album is \"on the way\".<ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5's New Album is on the Way: \"She's a Comin'\"|work=Mixmag|url=http://mixmag.net/read/deadmau5s-new-album-is-on-the-way-shes-a-comin-news|access-date=October 1, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001111300/http://mixmag.net/read/deadmau5s-new-album-is-on-the-way-shes-a-comin-news|archivedate=October 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Zimmerman announced a compilation album comprising orchestral performances of previously released music, titled ''[[Where's the Drop?]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 announces full orchestra performance titled 'where's the drop?'|work=[[Mixmag]]|url=http://mixmag.net/read/deadmau5-announces-performance-with-a-full-orchestra-called-wheres-the-drop-news|accessdate=March 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309054016/http://mixmag.net/read/deadmau5-announces-performance-with-a-full-orchestra-called-wheres-the-drop-news|archivedate=March 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 Announces Orchestral Album After Live Tidal Performance|work=Billboard|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8238614/deadmau5-orchestral-album-live-tidal-performance|accessdate=March 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309182604/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8238614/deadmau5-orchestral-album-live-tidal-performance|archivedate=March 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Announces Upcoming Orchestral Album + New Live Show|website=Runthetrap.com|url=https://runthetrap.com/2018/03/07/deadmau5-announces-upcoming-orchestral-album/|accessdate=March 8, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309054457/https://runthetrap.com/2018/03/07/deadmau5-announces-upcoming-orchestral-album/|archivedate=March 9, 2018}}</ref> On March 30, 2018, the album was initially released exclusively on the [[music streaming]] service [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] for a period of three months. On June 29, 2018, the album was officially released on other digital download and streaming services, as well as vinyl.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8463437/deadmau5-orchestral-album-wheres-the-drop-spotify|title=deadmau5's Orchestral Album 'Where's the Drop?' Now on Spotify: Listen|last=Bein|first=Kat|date=June 29, 2018|work=Billboard|access-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629234055/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8463437/deadmau5-orchestral-album-wheres-the-drop-spotify|archivedate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://djmag.com/content/deadmau5%E2%80%98s-orchestral-album-%E2%80%98where%E2%80%99s-drop%E2%80%99-given-full-release|title=Deadmau5\u2018s orchestral album \u2018Where\u2019s the Drop?\u2019 is given full release|last=McCallum|first=Rob|date=June 29, 2018|work=DJMag.com|access-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180629180230/https://djmag.com/content/deadmau5%E2%80%98s-orchestral-album-%E2%80%98where%E2%80%99s-drop%E2%80%99-given-full-release|archivedate=June 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msopr.com/press-releases/deadmau5-orchestral-album-wheres-the-drop-available-everywhere-today-june-29-on-mau5trap/|title=deadmau5\u2032 Orchestral Album \u2018where\u2019s the drop?\u2019 Available Everywhere Today, June 29 on mau5trap|last=Thomson|first=Sean|date=June 29, 2018|website=Mitch Schneider Organization|language=en|access-date=July 5, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705052849/http://www.msopr.com/press-releases/deadmau5-orchestral-album-wheres-the-drop-available-everywhere-today-june-29-on-mau5trap/|archivedate=July 5, 2018}}</ref> On July 3, 2018, Zimmerman announced an EP and compilation album titled ''[[Mau5ville: Level 1]]'', featuring \"[[Monophobia (song)|Monophobia]]\", a collaboration with [[Rob Swire]], as well as tracks from [[Getter (DJ)|Getter]] and [[GTA (DJs)|GTA]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Reveals New EP \"mau5ville: Level 1\" Featuring Rob Swire, Getter, GTA and More|work=EDM.com|url=https://edm.com/news/deadmau5-announces-mau5ville|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 reveals release date of new EP \u2018Mau5ville: Level 1\u2019|work=We Rave You|url=https://weraveyou.com/2018/07/deadmau5-reveals-release-date-of-new-ep-mau5ville-level-1/|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref> It was released on July 13, 2018 through Mau5trap.<ref>{{cite web|author=Narozniak, Rachel|year=2018|title=deadmau5 releases long-awaited Rob Swire collaboration, \u2018Monophobia\u2019 on new \u2018mau5ville: Level 1\u2019 EP|work=[[Dancing Astronaut]]|url=https://dancingastronaut.com/2018/07/deadmau5-releases-long-awaited-rob-swire-collaboration-monophobia-new-mauville-level-1-ep/|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Bein, Kat|year=2018|title=Deadmau5's 'Mau5ville Level 1' Compilation: Listen|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8465347/deadmau5-mau5ville-level-1-gta-getter-rob-swire|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref> On September 18, 2018, Zimmerman announced that he was in the process of producing his first ever original [[film score]] for the [[Netflix]] film \"[[Polar (film)|Polar]]\" directed by [[Jonas \u00c5kerlund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/deadmau5/status/1042074760283402240?s=19|title=Goat Lord on Twitter: \"well, the mouse is outta the bag,....working on my first film score for @constantinfilm @Netflix's #Polar...\"|website=[[Twitter]]|date=September 18, 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, the track listing of a follow-up EP, ''[[Mau5ville: Level 2]]'', was leaked, showing featured collaborations with [[Lights (musician)|Lights]] and Mr. Bill, with no release date confirmed at the time.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018mau5ville: Level 2\u2019 Leak Reveals Tracklist w/ Collabs, Remixes & Rare deadmau5 Track|work=Your EDM|url=https://www.youredm.com/2018/10/31/mau5ville-level-2-tracklist-revealed/|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5\u2019s \u2018Mau5ville: Level 2\u2019 Leak Reveals Tracklist & Rare Song|work=EDMSauce|url=https://www.edmsauce.com/2018/11/01/deadmau5s-mau5ville-level-2-leak-reveals-tracklist-rare-song/|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref> The EP was released officially on November 16, 2018 through Mau5trap.\n\nOn January 25, 2019, ''Polar'' premiered on Netflix, with Zimmerman releasing the soundtrack album, ''[[Polar (Music from the Netflix Film)]]'', through Mau5trap.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 on His Scoring Debut for Netflix's 'Polar': \"I Wanted to Wait for the Right Thing\"|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8494943/deadmau5-interview-scoring-debut-netflix-polar-jonas-akerlund|accessdate=25 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/3kAKiw0kRCuSXsTBWbBc9X|title=Polar (Music from the Netflix film) by deadmau5 on Spotify|website=[[Spotify]]|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> On February 1, 2019, the third installment in the ''Mau5ville'' series, ''[[Mau5ville: Level 3]]'' was released through Mau5trap. The compilation EP featured collaborations with Shotty Horroh, Scene of Action as well as tracks from No Mana and C.O.Z.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/4GeNdEYBTmiJ1BDhd9fazL|title=Mau5ville: Level 3 by deadmau5 on Spotify|website=[[Spotify]]|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://edm.com/music-releases/deadmau5-mau5trap-mau5ville-level-3|title=Mau5trap Presents Mau5ville: Level 3|website=EDM.com|accessdate=February 2, 2019}}</ref> In November 2019, Zimmerman released three new singles, entitled \"Satrn\", \"Coasted\" and \"Fall\", released on the 16th, 22nd and 29th respectively.<ref>[https://weraveyou.com/2019/11/deadmau5-satrn/] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|author=Claire Shaffer |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/deadmau5-coasted-916112/ |title=Deadmau5 Premieres New Song 'Coasted' |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=2019-11-21 |accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youredm.com/2019/11/29/deadmau5-new-single-fall-listen/] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Video game appearances==\nZimmerman is a playable avatar in ''[[DJ Hero 2]]'', a video game released in October 2010.<ref>{{cite web |last=Vozick |first=Simon |url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2010/07/14/dj-hero-2-artists/ |title='DJ Hero 2': Check out the exclusive list of artists here! &#124; ''Entertainment Weekly''. |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 14, 2010 |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205073758/http://music-mix.ew.com/2010/07/14/dj-hero-2-artists/ |archivedate=December 5, 2010  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/activision-announces-roster-of-award-winning-musical-talent-96282153.html |title=Activision Announces Roster of Award-Winning Musical Talent \u2013 Santa Monica, Calif., June 14 /PRNewswire-FirstCall/ |location=California |agency=PR Newswire |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617224334/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/activision-announces-roster-of-award-winning-musical-talent-96282153.html |archivedate=June 17, 2010  }}</ref><ref name=\"eurogamer review\">{{cite web | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-10-19-dj-hero-2-review | title = DJ Hero 2 | date = October 19, 2010 | accessdate = January 14, 2011 | first = Keza | last = MacDonald | publisher = [[Eurogamer]] | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101028125027/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-10-19-dj-hero-2-review | archivedate = October 28, 2010 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> The game featured several tracks by the artist, including a mix of \"Ghosts 'n' Stuff\" with [[Lady Gaga]]'s \"[[Just Dance (song)|Just Dance]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/video/deadmau5-ghosts-dj-hero-2/701360 |title=DJ Hero 2 Video Game, Deadmau5 Ghosts & Stuff Vs Just Dance Trailer |publisher=GameTrailers.com |date=July 1, 2010 |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704170204/http://www.gametrailers.com/video/deadmau5-ghosts-dj-hero-2/701360 |archivedate=July 4, 2010  }}</ref> He is also featured as a secret unlockable character in the 2014 video game ''[[Goat Simulator]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=DeNicola|first1=Danielle|title=Goat Simulator Patch 1.1: How to Unlock New Goat Mutators|url=http://www.gameskinny.com/cifer/goat-simulator-patch-11-how-to-unlock-new-goat-mutators|website=Game Skinny|accessdate=June 11, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609140838/http://www.gameskinny.com/cifer/goat-simulator-patch-11-how-to-unlock-new-goat-mutators|archivedate=June 9, 2014}}</ref> His music has been included in other video game titles, including a custom soundtrack for ''[[Dota 2]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=deadmau5 dieback music pack|url=http://blog.dota2.com/2015/07/deadmau5-dieback-music-pack/|publisher=Dota 2|accessdate=August 20, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724080921/http://blog.dota2.com/2015/07/deadmau5-dieback-music-pack/|archivedate=July 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the mobile app ''Family Guy: The Quest for Stuff'' by TinyCo, Deadmau5 was available for purchase as a playable character during the \"PeterPalooza\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Makuch|first1=Eddie|title=Snoop Dogg, Deadmau5, Weird Al Invade Family Guy Game|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/snoop-dogg-deadmau5-weird-al-invade-family-guy-gam/1100-6429688/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=January 3, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160121003522/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/snoop-dogg-deadmau5-weird-al-invade-family-guy-gam/1100-6429688/|archivedate=January 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA virtual version of his helmet is also an available accessory in ''[[Rocket League]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Makuch|first1=Eddie|title=Rocket League Adding Free Deadmau5 DLC in February|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rocket-league-adding-free-deadmau5-dlc-in-february/1100-6434257/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=January 3, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113022448/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rocket-league-adding-free-deadmau5-dlc-in-february/1100-6434257/|archivedate=November 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Deadmau5 head on.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Zimmerman unmasked]]\nOn July 30, 2010, at the [[9:30 Club]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], Zimmerman collapsed on stage, suffering from exhaustion and vomiting. This resulted in the cancellation of the rest of the show, as well as nine shows following the event.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ziegbe |first=Mawuse |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1644854/20100731/deadmau_five.jhtml |title=Deadmau5 Collapses Onstage, Cancels Tour Dates \u2013 Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV |date=July 31, 2010 |accessdate=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924083756/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1644854/20100731/deadmau_five.jhtml |archivedate=September 24, 2010  }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Zimmerman began dating American [[tattoo artist]] and TV personality [[Kat Von D]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kat Von D Dating DJ Deadmau5!|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/kat-von-d-dating-dj-deadmau5-2012199|work=[[Us Weekly]]|accessdate=October 19, 2012|date=September 19, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016001348/http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/kat-von-d-dating-dj-deadmau5-2012199|archivedate=October 16, 2012}}</ref> After breaking up in November 2012, they rekindled their relationship shortly afterwards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 and Kat von D break up|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/1286915--deadmau5-and-kat-von-d-break-up|work=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=December 16, 2012|date=November 13, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121226070754/http://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/1286915--deadmau5-and-kat-von-d-break-up|archivedate=December 26, 2012}}</ref> On December 15, 2012, Zimmerman proposed to Von D via [[Twitter]], and they announced that they would marry in August 2013 with an aquatic-themed wedding.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mike|last=Fleeman|title=Kat Von D Engaged to Deadmau5 \u2013 Who Proposed on Twitter!|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20657038,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=December 16, 2012|date=December 16, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121218234650/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20657038,00.html|archivedate=December 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://perezhilton.com/2013-04-16-kat-von-d-deadmau5-plan-underwater-themed-wedding |title=Kat Von D & Deadmau5 Are Getting Married The Little Mermaid Way! |publisher=PerezHilton.com |date=April 16, 2013 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130705105453/http://perezhilton.com/2013-04-16-kat-von-d-deadmau5-plan-underwater-themed-wedding |archivedate=July 5, 2013  }}</ref> They both have several matching tattoos, including the numbers \"289m3d22h\" on both of their arms, a sentimental reference to the day when they met, as well as two black stars underneath their eyes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.georgefm.co.nz/DEADMAU5-AND-GIRLFRIEND-KAT-VON-D-GET-MATCHING-TATTOOS/tabid/72/articleID/124111/Default.aspx |title=DEADMAU5 AND GIRLFRIEND KAT VON D GET MATCHING TATTOOS \u2013 News story \u2013 News |publisher=George FM |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702180142/http://www.georgefm.co.nz/DEADMAU5-AND-GIRLFRIEND-KAT-VON-D-GET-MATCHING-TATTOOS/tabid/72/articleID/124111/Default.aspx |archivedate=July 2, 2013  }}</ref> Zimmerman moved to [[Los Angeles]] to live with Von D.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kroq.cbslocal.com/2012/10/04/deadmau5-moves-to-l-a-hooks-up-with-kat-von-d-and-totally-needs-a-drivers-license/ |title=Deadmau5 Moves To L.A., Hooks Up With Kat Von D And Totally Needs A Driver's License \u00ab The World Famous KROQ |publisher=Kroq.cbslocal.com |date=October 4, 2012 |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928170204/http://kroq.cbslocal.com/2012/10/04/deadmau5-moves-to-l-a-hooks-up-with-kat-von-d-and-totally-needs-a-drivers-license/ |archivedate=September 28, 2013  }}</ref> In June 2013, Von D announced that they had ended their engagement.<ref>{{cite web|first=Maggie|last=Coughlan|title=Deadmau5 and Kat Von D End Engagement|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20712900,00.html|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=July 8, 2013|date=June 27, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701173845/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20712900,00.html|archivedate=July 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Zimmerman purchased a $5 million home in the [[Campbellville, Ontario|Campbellville]] area of [[Milton, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmsauce.com/2014/10/10/deadmau5-purchased-beautiful-5-million-house-canada/|title=Deadmau5 Purchased This Beautiful $5 Million House In Canada|author=Stevo|work=EDM Sauce|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408234142/http://www.edmsauce.com/2014/10/10/deadmau5-purchased-beautiful-5-million-house-canada/|archivedate=April 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/6084813-deadmau5-entertains-milton-students-encourages-creativity/|title=Deadmau5 entertains Milton students, encourages creativity|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108232835/http://www.insidehalton.com/news-story/6084813-deadmau5-entertains-milton-students-encourages-creativity/|archivedate=November 8, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hdsb.ca/Newsroom/SpotlightonSchools/Pages/Popularelectronic-dancemusicianDeadmau5inspiresMiltonDistrictHighSchoolstudents.aspx|title=Electronic-dance musician Deadmau5 inspires Milton DHS students|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071308/http://www.hdsb.ca/Newsroom/SpotlightonSchools/Pages/Popularelectronic-dancemusicianDeadmau5inspiresMiltonDistrictHighSchoolstudents.aspx|archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://torontolife.com/real-estate/deadmau5s-condo-is-for-sale-and-this-is-what-it-looks-like-inside/|title=Deadmau5's condo is for sale, and this is what it looks like inside \u2013 Toronto Life|work=Toronto Life|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325085120/http://torontolife.com/real-estate/deadmau5s-condo-is-for-sale-and-this-is-what-it-looks-like-inside/|archivedate=March 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn August 12, 2017, Zimmerman married his fianc\u00e9e Kelly Fedoni.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/music/deadmau5-marries-kelly-fedoni/|title=deadmau5 marries Kelly Fedoni|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813104734/http://people.com/music/deadmau5-marries-kelly-fedoni/|archivedate=August 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn October 11, 2018, Zimmerman announced a leave of absence, due to mental health and personal reasons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youredm.com/2018/10/10/deadmau5-addresses-his-recent-insensitive-tweets-in-statement-admitting-he-needs-help/|title=BREAKING: Deadmau5 Apologizes, Admits He \"Needs Professional Help\" After Slushii Drama|date=October 10, 2018|work=Your EDM|access-date=October 13, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Name origin==\nZimmerman's father claims that when his son was in his early teens, he was chatting with a friend on his computer, which then abruptly shut off. According to Zimmerman's father, he said that it had a smell of burnt wire and had a strange odour. Zimmerman started to dismantle his computer and happened to find a dead mouse. Zimmerman then became known as the \"dead mouse guy\" among friends. He tried to change his name to \"Deadmouse\" in an online chat room, but it was too long, so he shortened it to \"Deadmau5\". \"Maus\" is the German word for \"mouse\" and is pronounced the same as in English; the ending 5 instead of an 's' is a form of [[leet]].<ref name=\"aritcle0101\" />\n\nZimmerman created the original logo\u2014called \"mau5head\"\u2014while learning how to use some 3D modelling software.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/video/2010/may/28/deadmau5|title=Paul Morley meets deadmau5 \u2013 The Guardian|accessdate=October 1, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615072350/http://www.theguardian.com/music/video/2010/may/28/deadmau5|archivedate=June 15, 2015}}</ref> The logo appears in many different colors and designs, and has been shown on the cover art of most of Zimmerman's albums. He was given the idea to wear a headdress based on the logo by one of his friends, [[Jay Gordon]] of the industrial metal band [[Orgy (band)|Orgy]]. In an interview with [[CBC Television]], Zimmerman said that he wants his logo to be an \"icon\". Fans often attend Deadmau5 concerts sporting their own copy of the Mau5head.\n\nHe created his website and began uploading songs to SectionZ and producing under the alias \"Deadmau5\" in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sectionz.com/detail.asp?rType=mp3&SZID=2720 |title=SectionZ Electronic Music Community \u2013 All Computer Music Enthusiasts Welcome |publisher=Web.archive.org |accessdate=June 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070818172810/http://www.sectionz.com/detail.asp?rType=mp3&SZID=2720 |archivedate=August 18, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n===DirtyCircuit===\nIn 2008, an artist called DirtyCircuit claimed to have been threatened with legal action after using a sample called \"LP_Faxing Berlin C_128bpm\"<ref name=\"createdigitalmusic.com\">{{cite web |url=http://createdigitalmusic.com/2008/12/01/all-fruity-no-loops-fl-studio-to-remove-all-melodic-samples/ |title=All Fruity, No Loops: FL Studio to Remove All Melodic Samples; Murky License, Content |publisher=Create Digital Music |date=November 20, 2008 |accessdate=June 5, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808090527/http://createdigitalmusic.com/2008/12/01/all-fruity-no-loops-fl-studio-to-remove-all-melodic-samples/ |archivedate=August 8, 2010  }}</ref> that came bundled with [[FL Studio]], and to which Zimmerman claimed copyright.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/tech/fl-studio-user-faces-legal-action-for-using-built-in-samples-183577|title=FL Studio user faces legal action for using built-in samples|author=Ben Rogerson|work=MusicRadar|accessdate=April 4, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409180510/http://www.musicradar.com/news/tech/fl-studio-user-faces-legal-action-for-using-built-in-samples-183577|archivedate=April 9, 2016}}</ref> The sample was a direct clip of a full bar of the song. Zimmerman provided a \"Demo Track\" which came bundled with FL Studio, along with several loop samples. The case caused slight discomfort among the users of FL Studio,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futuremusic.co.uk/page/futuremusic?entry=don_t_use_fl_studio |title=Future Music |publisher=Future Music |date=November 20, 2008 |accessdate=June 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208080231/http://www.futuremusic.co.uk/page/futuremusic?entry=don_t_use_fl_studio |archivedate=December 8, 2008 }}</ref> and some have pointed out potential inconsistencies in the [[EULA]] of the software.<ref name=\"createdigitalmusic.com\" /> Subsequent versions, after FL Studio 8, no longer contained those loop samples.\n\n=== Disney trademark dispute ===\n{{Multiple image|direction=vertical|align=right|width=200|image1=Deadmau5.png|caption1=Deadmau5 logo|image2=Mickey Mouse head and ears.svg|caption2=Basic geometrical representation of Mickey Mouse's head and ears}}\nIn a 2012 interview with ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', Zimmerman acknowledged possible similarities between his Mau5head logo and that of [[Mickey Mouse]], joking that \"someone at the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] patent office fell asleep on that one.\"<ref name=guardian-mickeymau5/>\n\nIn March 2014, it was reported that The Walt Disney Company had filed a request with the [[United States Patent and Trademark Office]] to investigate Zimmerman's application to register the Mau5head emblem as a [[trademark]], noting its resemblance to the figure of Mickey Mouse.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gardner|first1=Eriq|title=Is a Mickey Mouse v. Deadmau5 Trademark Battle Brewing?|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-v-mickey-mouse-trademark-692442|accessdate=September 5, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140926022938/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-v-mickey-mouse-trademark-692442|archivedate=September 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Disney takes on DJ deadmau5 over mouse-ears garb|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/09/04/disney-deadmau5-deadmouse-mickey-mouse/15106939/|accessdate=June 30, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220033510/http://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/09/04/disney-deadmau5-deadmouse-mickey-mouse/15106939/|archivedate=February 20, 2015}}</ref> Disney officially filed its opposition in September 2014, arguing that the mark is likely to cause confusion because it is \"nearly identical in appearance, connotation, and overall commercial impression\" to Disney's trademarked iconography of Mickey Mouse. In response to the opposition, Zimmerman attacked Disney on Twitter, arguing that the company thinks of people as being \"stupid\" because \"[they] might confuse an established electronic musician/performer with a cartoon mouse.\"<ref name=guardian-mickeymau5>{{cite news|title=Deadmau5 v Disney: mouse ear logo sparks legal dispute|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/sep/04/deadmau5-disney-mickey-mouse-ear-logo-legal-dispute|accessdate=September 5, 2014|work=The Guardian|date=September 4, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905083153/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/sep/04/deadmau5-disney-mickey-mouse-ear-logo-legal-dispute|archivedate=September 5, 2014}}</ref> Zimmerman also believed that he had been targeted by Disney due to their attempts to \"cash in\" on the EDM market, specifically alluding to ''[[Dconstructed]]''\u2014a recently released compilation album containing remixes of music from Disney properties by major electronic musicians such as [[Armin van Buuren]], [[Avicii]] and [[Kaskade]].<ref name=rollingstone-disneycd/>\n\nOn September 4, 2014, Zimmerman revealed on Twitter that Disney had used \"Ghosts 'n' Stuff\" in a Mickey Mouse \"re-micks\" video on their website and YouTube channel without his or his labels' permission, and posted pictures showing a [[DMCA takedown notice|takedown notice]] that had been sent to Disney by his lawyers. The letter also contained a trademark infringement accusation, arguing that the use of Deadmau5's name in material regarding the video falsely implied his endorsement of it. Disney argued that it had properly licensed the song and that there was \"no merit to his statement.\"<ref name=rollingstone-disneycd>{{cite news|title=Deadmau5 Sends Cease and Desist to Disney Over 'Infringing Video'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/deadmau5-cease-desist-disney-20140905|accessdate=September 6, 2014|work=Rolling Stone|date=September 5, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906123032/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/deadmau5-cease-desist-disney-20140905|archivedate=September 6, 2014}}</ref><ref name=inthemix-pwnage>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 drops some \"complete pwnage\" on Disney in legal war|url=http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/58904/Deadmau5_ramps_up_legal_war_against_Disney_with_Cease_Desist|website=inthemix.com.au|accessdate=September 5, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140905075707/http://www.inthemix.com.au/news/58904/Deadmau5_ramps_up_legal_war_against_Disney_with_Cease_Desist|archivedate=September 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn an October 2014 USPTO filing, Zimmerman argued that Disney has attempted to co-exist with him in goodwill. Zimmerman presented evidence that Disney had been in contact with him regarding potential collaborative projects, including an offer to participate in a \"re-imagining\" of ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]'' as a live concert tour for the film's 75th anniversary.<ref name=billboard-deadmau5documents>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Says Archenemy Disney Wanted His Help on 'Fantasia' Anniversary|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-says-disney-approached-him-740615|website=Billboard.biz|accessdate=October 15, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016191046/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-says-disney-approached-him-740615|archivedate=October 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Zimmerman's attorney stated that he and Disney had \"amicably resolved their dispute.\"<ref name=thr-settled>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5, Disney Settle Dispute Over \"Mouse Head\" Logo|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-disney-settle-dispute-mouse-804072|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=June 22, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224051428/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-disney-settle-dispute-mouse-804072|archivedate=December 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Meowingtons trademark dispute ===\nIn 2015, Zimmerman attempted to register a trademark for the name of his pet cat, Professor Meowingtons, whom he adopted in 2010 and has incorporated into some of his own merchandising. However, the registration was rejected due to a pre-existing Meowingtons trademark held by an online retailer of the same name established in 2014,<ref name=\"thr-meowingtons\"/> which sells cat-themed accessories and clothing. After discovering the trademark, Zimmerman petitioned against it, citing his pre-existing uses.<ref name=\"billboard-meowingtonstm\">{{cite web|title=deadmau5 Files Trademark Petition to Protect His Cat Meowingtons' Brand|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7640508/deadmau5-files-trademark-petition-protect-cat-meowingtons-brand|website=Billboard|accessdate=March 26, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320015034/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7640508/deadmau5-files-trademark-petition-protect-cat-meowingtons-brand|archivedate=March 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Zimmerman was sued by Emma Bassiri (the owner of the website) for trademark infringement and unfair competition; the suit argued that claims by Zimmerman that she had named the site specifically after the cat was false. Zimmerman himself told ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' that \"from the very beginning I was working to find a way to resolve this situation amicably\", but that he had been forced to \"litigate this woman out of existence\".<ref name=\"thr-meowingtons\">{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Sued Over 'Meowingtons' Trademark|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-sued-meowingtons-trademark-986054|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=March 26, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326140129/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/deadmau5-sued-meowingtons-trademark-986054|archivedate=March 26, 2017}}</ref> On May 15, 2017, Deadmau5 filed a countersuit against Bassiri with the intention of seeking forfeiture of Bassiri's website and domain name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deadmau5 Escalates 'Meowingtons' Trademark Cat Fight With Countersuit|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7793109/deadmau5-meowingtons-trademark-countersuit|website=Billboard|accessdate=June 1, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519084108/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7793109/deadmau5-meowingtons-trademark-countersuit|archivedate=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, World Intellectual Property Review reported that Zimmerman and Bassiri had resolved their dispute.<ref>{{cite web|title=Claws sheathed in Deadmau5 cat fight|url=https://www.worldipreview.com/news/deadmau5-cat-fight-settled-15572|website=World Intellectual Property Review|accessdate=April 29, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705052849/https://www.worldipreview.com/news/deadmau5-cat-fight-settled-15572|archivedate=July 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Offensive slurs===\nIn October 2018, Zimmerman posted comments on Twitter during an argument including the statements \"I\u2019ll bet you suck a guy off for 40 grand zero fucking questions asked\" and \"women don't posses {{sic}} penises\". These comments were construed by readers as being homophobic and transphobic.<ref name=\"EDM\">{{cite news |first1= |title=deadmau5 Accused of Making Transphobic Remarks During Online Argument|url=https://edm.com/news/deadmau5-transphobic-remarks-online-argument |accessdate=25 February 2019 |publisher=EDM.com |date=8 October 2018}}</ref> Zimmerman apologized for his comments, saying that he \"wasn't trying to make blatant transphobic statements\", and had \"just got into a heated arguement {{sic}} with some dude online\", noting that his comments had been taken \"somewhere unintended\".<ref name=\"Duffy\">{{cite news |last1=Duffy |first1=Nick|title=Deadmau5 walks back \u2018homophobic, transphobic\u2019 comments|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/10/08/deadmau5-homophobic-transphobic-comments/ |accessdate=25 February 2019 |publisher=PinkNews |date=8 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nA few days later during a gaming stream he referred to a track by artist [[Slushii]] as \"AIDS fucking music\" and calling it \"autistic shit\". Slushii \u2013 who is on the [[autism spectrum]] \u2013 responded to these comments on Twitter, calling them \"really disappointing\".<ref name=\"Martin\">{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Laura |title=Deadmau5 forced to apologise for disgusting Aids and autism slurs |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/deadmau5-forced-apologise-disgusting-aids-13399028 |accessdate=25 February 2019 |publisher=Mirror Online |date=11 October 2018}}</ref> Zimmerman later apologized for these comments, citing mental health issues that required \"professional help\", and stating that he would take time \"off the radar\" to \"work on [himself]\".<ref name=\"Meadow\">{{cite news |last1=Meadow |first1=Matthew |title=Deadmau5 Addresses His Recent Insensitive Tweets In Statement Admitting He \"Needs Help\" |url=https://www.youredm.com/2018/10/10/deadmau5-addresses-his-recent-insensitive-tweets-in-statement-admitting-he-needs-help/ |accessdate=25 February 2019 |publisher=YourEDM |date=10 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, whilst playing ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]'' on a livestream on [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]], Zimmerman called another player a \"fucking cock-sucking stream sniper fag.\"<ref name=\"Cameron\">{{cite news |last1=Cameron |first1=John |title=DEADMAU5 USES HATE SPEECH DURING PUBG LIVE STREAM |url=https://edm.com/news/deadmau5-hate-speech-pubg-twitch |accessdate=18 February 2019 |publisher=EDM |date=11 February 2019}}</ref> Twitch banned Zimmerman from the platform for hate speech, after which Zimmerman posted: \"I know who I am, and I don\u2019t have to fucking sit here and cry and defend my fucking self with the obligatory 'I'm not that person, I am sorry' reflex.\"<ref name=\"Jackman\">{{cite news |last1=Jackman |first1=Josh |title=Deadmau5 deletes Twitch account after \u2018c**k-sucking fag\u2019 rant |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/02/13/deadmau5-deletes-twitch-sucking-fag-rant/ |accessdate=18 February 2019 |publisher=Pink News |date=13 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Deadmau5 discography}}\n'''Studio albums'''\n* ''[[Get Scraped]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Vexillology (album)|Vexillology]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Random Album Title]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[For Lack of a Better Name]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[4\u00d74=12]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Album Title Goes Here]]''<!--- Album title should not be stylized ---> (2012)\n* ''[[While(1 Is Less Than 2)|While(1<2)]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[W:/2016Album/]]'' (2016)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Deadmau5}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Music|Canada}}\n*[[List of ambient music artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Deadmau5}}\n* {{official website|http://www.deadmau5.com}}\n* [http://www.ultrarecords.com/artists/deadmau5/ Artist Site at Ultra Records]\n\n{{Deadmau5}}\n{{DJ Award for Best International DJ |state=collapsed}}\n{{DJ Award for Best Electro DJ |state=collapsed}}\n{{Mau5trap}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Deadmau5]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian musicians]]\n[[Category:Ableton Live users]]\n[[Category:Canadian DJs]]\n[[Category:Canadian electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian house musicians]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Swiss-German descent]]\n[[Category:Electro house musicians]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music DJs]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for Dance Recording of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Masked musicians]]\n[[Category:Mau5trap artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:People from Niagara Falls, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Remixers]]\n[[Category:Tracker musicians]]\n[[Category:Ultra Records artists]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records artists]]\n[[Category:Progressive house musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Sanjay768", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deadmau5"}
{"title_page": "77 (number)", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=May 2010}}\n{{Infobox number\n| number = 77\n| divisor = 1, 7, 11, 77\n}}\n'''77''' ('''seventy-seven''') is the [[natural number]] following [[76 (number)|76]] and preceding [[78 (number)|78]]. Seventy-seven is the smallest positive integer requiring five syllables in [[English language|English]].\n\n==In mathematics==\n'''77''' is:\n\n*the 22nd discrete [[semiprime|biprime]] and the first of the (7.q) family.\n*a [[Blum integer]] since both 7 and 11 are [[Gaussian integer|Gaussian prime]]s.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|1=A016105|2=Blum integers|accessdate=2016-05-29}}</ref>\n*the sum of three consecutive squares, 4<sup>2</sup> + 5<sup>2</sup> + 6<sup>2</sup>.\n*the sum of the first eight [[prime number]]s.\n*the number of integer [[Partition (number theory)|partitions]] of the number 12.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|1=A000041|2=}}</ref>\n* the largest number that cannot be written as a sum of distinct numbers whose reciprocals sum to 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.stetson.edu/~efriedma/numbers.html|title=What's Special About This Number?|publisher=}}</ref>\n*the number of digits of the 12th [[perfect number]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primes.utm.edu/mersenne/index.html#known|title=Mersenne Primes: History, Theorems and Lists|first=Chris K.|last=Caldwell|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIt is possible for a [[sudoku]] puzzle to have as many as 77 givens, yet lack a unique solution.<ref>[http://www.cs.utexas.edu/~kuipers/readings/Sudoku-sciam-06.pdf The Science behind Sudoku, J.P. Delahaye]</ref>\n\nIt and its ''sibling'' 49 are the only 2-digit numbers whose [[home prime]]s (in base 10) have not been calculated.\n\n==In science==\n\n*The [[atomic number]] of [[iridium]]\n*The boiling point of [[nitrogen]]\n\n==In history==\nDuring [[World War&nbsp;II]] in [[Sweden]] at the border with [[Norway]], \"77\" was used as a [[shibboleth]] ([[password]]), because the tricky pronunciation in Swedish made it easy to instantly discern whether the speaker was native [[Sweden|Swedish]], [[Norway|Norwegian]], or [[Germany|German]].<ref>{{citation|title=Easy as Pi: The Countless Ways We Use Numbers Every Day|first=Jamie|last=Buchan|publisher=Penguin|year=2010|isbn=9781606522783|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P93tAbdyf2MC&pg=PT18}}.</ref>\n\n==In religion==\nIn the [[Islam]]ic tradition, \"77\" figures prominently. [[Muhammad]] is reported to have explained, \"Faith has sixty-odd, or seventy-odd branches, the highest and best of which is to declare that there is no god but God, and the lowest of which is to remove something harmful from a road. Shyness, too, is a branch of faith.\" While some scholars refrain from clarifying \"sixty-odd or seventy-odd\", various numbers have been suggested, 77 being the most common.<ref name=\"Jamia Ashrafia Online\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.jamiaashrafia.org/muh15.php |title=A Verdict of Mufti Muhammad Hassan |access-date=2008-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204224656/http://www.jamiaashrafia.org/muh15.php |archive-date=2008-12-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Some have gone so far as to delineate these branches.<ref name=\"SunniPath: The Online Islamic Academy\">{{cite web|url=http://qa.sunnipath.com/issue_view.asp?HD=1&ID=103&CATE=24|title=Imam al-Tahanawi on the Seventy-Seven Branches|access-date=2008-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620035424/http://qa.sunnipath.com/issue_view.asp?HD=1&ID=103&CATE=24|archive-date=2009-06-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Gospel of Luke]] lists 77 generations from [[Adam]] to [[Jesus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.textexcavation.com/genealogyjesus.html|title=The genealogy of Jesus.|publisher=}}</ref>\nIn the [[Gospel of Matthew]] Peter asks, \"How many times shall I forgive my brother?\". Jesus replies, \"Seventy-seven times.\"\n\n===In religious numerology===\nIn certain numerological systems based on the English alphabet, the number 77 is associated with [[Jesus Christ]]. CHRIST is C&nbsp;=&nbsp;3, H&nbsp;=&nbsp;8, R&nbsp;=&nbsp;18, I&nbsp;=&nbsp;9, S&nbsp;=&nbsp;19, T&nbsp;=&nbsp;20, which added together equal 77.\n\n'Liber 77' is the [[gematrian]] name for [[Liber OZ]]- a brief but popular publication by [[Aliester Crowley]]. The word 'oz', which means 'strength', is composed of two [[hebrew alphabet|hebrew letters]]- [[ayin]] and [[zayin]], which have gematrian values of 70 and 7 respectively, thus adding up to 77.\n\n==In other fields==\n{{See also|List of highways numbered 77}}\n'''Seventy-seven''' is also:\n* 10-77 &ndash; the New York City Fire Department's (FDNY) [[Ten-code|10 code]] for high-rise, multiple-dwelling fire <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fdnewyork.com/10code.asp|title=10 Codes|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Shortening of a 1950s-60s TV series, ''[[77 Sunset Strip]]''\n* [[Group of 77]], a group of developing nations at the [[United Nations]]\n* 77 &ndash; [[Talking Heads]]'s debut album (''[[Talking Heads: 77]]'') released in 1977\n* [[The 77's]], an American Rock band\n* The temperature, in Fahrenheit, some characteristics of [[semiconductor]]s are specifically given in a [[datasheet]] (77&nbsp;\u00b0F = 25&nbsp;\u00b0C).\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline|77 (number)}}\n\n{{Integers|zero}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:77 (Number)}}\n[[Category:Integers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=May 2010}}\n{{Infobox number\n| number = 77\n| divisor = 1, 7, 11, 77\n}}\n'''77''' ('''seventy-seven''') is the [[natural number]] following [[76 (number)|76]] and preceding [[78 (number)|78]]. Seventy-seven is the smallest positive integer requiring five syllables in [[English language|English]].\n\n==In mathematics==\n'''77''' is:\n\n*the 22nd discrete [[semiprime|biprime]] and the first of the (7.q) family.\n*a [[Blum integer]] since both 7 and 11 are [[Gaussian integer|Gaussian prime]]s.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|1=A016105|2=Blum integers|accessdate=2016-05-29}}</ref>\n*the sum of three consecutive squares, 4<sup>2</sup> + 5<sup>2</sup> + 6<sup>2</sup>.\n*the sum of the first eight [[prime number]]s.\n*the number of integer [[Partition (number theory)|partitions]] of the number 12.<ref>{{Cite OEIS|1=A000041|2=}}</ref>\n* the largest number that cannot be written as a sum of distinct numbers whose reciprocals sum to 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.stetson.edu/~efriedma/numbers.html|title=What's Special About This Number?|publisher=}}</ref>\n*the number of digits of the 12th [[perfect number]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primes.utm.edu/mersenne/index.html#known|title=Mersenne Primes: History, Theorems and Lists|first=Chris K.|last=Caldwell|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIt is possible for a [[sudoku]] puzzle to have as many as 77 givens, yet lack a unique solution.<ref>[http://www.cs.utexas.edu/~kuipers/readings/Sudoku-sciam-06.pdf The Science behind Sudoku, J.P. Delahaye]</ref>\n\nIt and its ''sibling'' 49 are the only 2-digit numbers whose [[home prime]]s (in base 10) have not been calculated.\n\n==In science==\n\n*The [[atomic number]] of [[iridium]]\n*The boiling point of [[nitrogen]]\n\n==In history==\nDuring [[World War&nbsp;II]] in [[Sweden]] at the border with [[Norway]], \"77\" was used as a [[shibboleth]] ([[password]]), because the tricky pronunciation in Swedish made it easy to instantly discern whether the speaker was native [[Sweden|Swedish]], [[Norway|Norwegian]], or [[Germany|German]].<ref>{{citation|title=Easy as Pi: The Countless Ways We Use Numbers Every Day|first=Jamie|last=Buchan|publisher=Penguin|year=2010|isbn=9781606522783|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P93tAbdyf2MC&pg=PT18}}.</ref>\n\n==In religion==\nIn the [[Islam]]ic tradition, \"77\" figures prominently. [[Muhammad]] is reported to have explained, \"Faith has sixty-odd, or seventy-odd branches, the highest and best of which is to declare that there is no god but God, and the lowest of which is to remove something harmful from a road. Shyness, too, is a branch of faith.\" While some scholars refrain from clarifying \"sixty-odd or seventy-odd\", various numbers have been suggested, 77 being the most common.<ref name=\"Jamia Ashrafia Online\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.jamiaashrafia.org/muh15.php |title=A Verdict of Mufti Muhammad Hassan |access-date=2008-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204224656/http://www.jamiaashrafia.org/muh15.php |archive-date=2008-12-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Some have gone so far as to delineate these branches.<ref name=\"SunniPath: The Online Islamic Academy\">{{cite web|url=http://qa.sunnipath.com/issue_view.asp?HD=1&ID=103&CATE=24|title=Imam al-Tahanawi on the Seventy-Seven Branches|access-date=2008-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620035424/http://qa.sunnipath.com/issue_view.asp?HD=1&ID=103&CATE=24|archive-date=2009-06-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Gospel of Luke]] lists 77 generations from [[Adam]] to [[Jesus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.textexcavation.com/genealogyjesus.html|title=The genealogy of Jesus.|publisher=}}</ref>\nIn the [[Gospel of Matthew]] Peter asks \"How many times shall i forgive my brother\". Jesus replies \"Seventy-seven times\"\n\n===In religious numerology===\nIn certain numerological systems based on the English alphabet, the number 77 is associated with [[Jesus Christ]]. CHRIST is C&nbsp;=&nbsp;3, H&nbsp;=&nbsp;8, R&nbsp;=&nbsp;18, I&nbsp;=&nbsp;9, S&nbsp;=&nbsp;19, T&nbsp;=&nbsp;20, which added together equal 77.\n\n'Liber 77' is the [[gematrian]] name for [[Liber OZ]]- a brief but popular publication by [[Aliester Crowley]]. The word 'oz', which means 'strength', is composed of two [[hebrew alphabet|hebrew letters]]- [[ayin]] and [[zayin]], which have gematrian values of 70 and 7 respectively, thus adding up to 77.\n\n==In other fields==\n{{See also|List of highways numbered 77}}\n'''Seventy-seven''' is also:\n* 10-77 &ndash; the New York City Fire Department's (FDNY) [[Ten-code|10 code]] for high-rise, multiple-dwelling fire <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fdnewyork.com/10code.asp|title=10 Codes|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Shortening of a 1950s-60s TV series, ''[[77 Sunset Strip]]''\n* [[Group of 77]], a group of developing nations at the [[United Nations]]\n* 77 &ndash; [[Talking Heads]]'s debut album (''[[Talking Heads: 77]]'') released in 1977\n* [[The 77's]], an American Rock band\n* The temperature, in Fahrenheit, some characteristics of [[semiconductor]]s are specifically given in a [[datasheet]] (77&nbsp;\u00b0F = 25&nbsp;\u00b0C).\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline|77 (number)}}\n\n{{Integers|zero}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:77 (Number)}}\n[[Category:Integers]]\n", "name_user": "Hic vitam est ridiculum", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn religion:Corrected some punctuation and grammar issues", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/77_(number)"}
{"title_page": "Bows against the Barons", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Bows Against the Barons\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = Bows Against the Barons (1966).jpg\n| caption = Cover of the 1966 revised edition\n| author        = [[Geoffrey Trease]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  =\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| subject       =\n| genre         = Children's novel, historical novel\n| publisher     = Martin Lawrence\n| pub_date      = 1934\n| english_pub_date =\n| media_type    = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages         = 152\n| isbn          =\n| oclc          = 6171653\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''Bows Against the Barons''''' is a 1934 children's novel by British author [[Geoffrey Trease]], based on the legend of [[Robin Hood]]. It tells the story of an adolescent boy who joins an [[outlaw]] band and takes part in a great rebellion against the [[Feudalism|feudal]] elite.  Trease's first novel, ''Bows Against the Barons'' marks the start of his prolific career as a historical novelist. It is notable for reinterpreting the Robin Hood legend and revitalizing the conventions of children's [[historical fiction]] in 20th-century Britain.\n\n==Plot introduction==\nSet in medieval England, ''Bows Against the Barons'' relates the adventures of a [[peasant]] boy who becomes an outlaw and joins the band of Robin Hood. Together, they take up arms against the masters of England and fight for the rights of the common people. The protagonist's former master tries to suppress them, but at great cost.\n\nThe title refers to the primary weapon of the outlaws \u2013 the [[longbow]].\n\n==Plot summary==\n''Bows Against the Barons'' takes place during the final months of Robin Hood's life, beginning in early June, and ending in the following year about February. It is largely told from the viewpoint of Dickon, a sixteen-year-old peasant boy from the village of [[Oxton, Nottinghamshire|Oxton]].\n\n===Chapters 1\u20139===\nThe novel opens by depicting Dickon's hardships as a [[serf]] on a [[baron]]ial [[Manorialism|manor]]. The boy being whipped by his [[bailiff]] for missing work and harassed by the village priest for not paying [[tithe]]. Despite his youth, Dickon has to serve as his family's breadwinner because his father Dick has been conscripted as an archer for the [[Crusades]]. His troubles are compounded when the King's deer from nearby [[Sherwood Forest]] ravage his garden's.  Moved by anger, Dickon kills one of the deer with an arrow. He then flees into Sherwood to avoid the penalties of [[poaching]]. Eventually, he meets [[Alan-a-Dale]], who leads him to Robin Hood's band. Proving adept at archery, Dickon is welcomed into their company.\n\nDisguised as a weaver's apprentice, Dickon becomes Robin's messenger to all of [[Nottingham]]'s rebels. Led by a bridle-smith, Dickon and the populace assemble in the market-place to protest working conditions and demand the release of imprisoned workers. The [[Sheriff of Nottingham]] attempts to disperse them, but Robin and his outlaws arrive and overwhelm the Sheriff. In the resulting riot the imprisoned workers are freed. However, mounted soldiers from [[Nottingham Castle]] arrive to quash the revolt.\n\nPursued by a horseman, Dickon escapes through secret passages and reaches the safety of Sherwood, but he is captured by [[royal forest]]ers and escorted north to be tried for poaching. However, Alan manages to make contact with Dickon, having disguised himself as a blind [[minstrel]] and his messages as [[doggerel]]. On Alan's instructions, Dickon attempts to delay the foresters' journey. His plans almost go awry when he meets his former master Sir Rolf D'Eyncourt, who has returned from the Crusades and now attempts to reclaim Dickon. Fortunately, the head forester refuses to hand over the boy, insisting on the priority of royal justice. As his journey resumes, Dickon vows revenge when he learns that his father has been killed in battle.  When Dickon and the foresters eventually reach a village, the blacksmith and the villagers protest Dickon's captivity. In the ensuing struggle, a forester almost kills Dickon, but Alan arrives in time and saves him. Together, they join the villagers in defeating the foresters.\n\nLater, soldiers are dispatched from Nottingham to punish the villagers, but Robin and his band ambush and defeat them before they reach their destination.\n\n===Chapters 10\u201320===\nIn the meantime, Sir Rolf exploits and oppresses his tenants in his pursuit of wealth and luxury. The outlaws of Sherwood oppose him, stirring up the serfs to resist his tyranny. Allied with neighboring barons, Sir Rolf pens the outlaws in Sherwood and attempts to hunt them down. The outlaws defeat them by hiding in trees and picking off his men from camouflaged positions. As they celebrate their victory, Robin reveals his ultimate goal \u2013 the overthrow of all masters and freedom for the people of England.\n\nThe outlaws now prepare for an attack on D'Eyncourt Castle, gathering money for their needs. Alan leads Dickon and others to waylay the Abbot of Rufford, disguising themselves as  knights and luring him into an ambush. Seeing Dickon's talent for disguises, Robin sends the boy to infiltrate D'Eyncourt Castle and acquire information about its defences. Disguised as a [[Page (servant)|page]] with bleached hair, Dickon manages to penetrate D'Eyncourt on Christmas, but is betrayed by an undyed lock of hair. Pursued, he hides on the chapel's beams and eventually escapes from the castle, surviving a [[crossbow]] shot.\n\nWith Dickon's information, the outlaws finally attack D'Eyncourt Castle during winter. Alan leads Dickon and a group of outlaws to infiltrate and capture the castle [[keep]]. Taking up positions on its [[battlement]]s, they pick off D'Eyncourt's defenders with their arrows while Robin launches the main assault on the outer walls. His combined force of outlaws and serfs eventually breaks through and razes the castle. Dickon kills his former bailiff, while [[Little John]] kills Sir Rolf.\n\nHeartened by their success, the outlaws attempt to march on Nottingham itself. However, the [[Earl of Wessex]] traps them in a [[pincer movement]] between Nottingham and [[Newark-on-Trent|Newark]] and defeats them all. When his ally the Archbishop wonders aloud why the rebels die so willingly on the swords of his soldiers the Earl replies grimly: \"because they know that they are going to win - but not in my time\".\n\nAlan, [[Friar Tuck]] and [[Will Scarlet]] are among those killed. Dickon, Robin and Little John survive the battle and flee north with other survivors to [[Yorkshire]], undergoing much hardship on their journey. Dickon almost drowns in a [[bog]]. Wounded, Robin takes refuge in [[Kirklees, Kirklees|Kirklees]], whose prioress [[Bloodletting|bleeds]] him to death to claim a reward from the Earl. Alerted by an arrow shot by Robin from his deathbed, the outlaws reclaim his body and burn down the priory in revenge.\n\nAfter burying Robin, the outlaw band breaks up. Dickon and Little John are the only ones who remain dedicated to Robin's cause. They depart for the [[High Peak (upland)|High Peak]] in Derbyshire, determined to continue Robin's work and fulfill his visionary ideal.\n\n==Characters==\n\n===Fictional characters===\nIn order of appearance:\n* '''Dickon''': The protagonist. Depicted as a sixteen-year-old peasant boy with tousled black hair. He has a mother and three younger brothers.\n* '''William''': The bailiff of D'Eyncourt. Characterized by his harsh treatment of Sir Rolf's tenants.\n* '''Thomas Pole''': A Nottingham weaver serving as Robin's contact for the Nottingham riot.\n* '''King's foresters''': Six Gascon royal foresters who capture Dickon after the Nottingham riot. One of them, Guy, attempts to kill the boy during the villagers' attack.\n* '''Hal the Harper''': A persona adopted by Alan for his disguise as a blind minstrel.\n* '''Sir Rolf D'Eyncourt''': Dickon's former master. A violent and exploitative baron; the novel compares him to a [[Mail (armour)|mailed]] fist. His last name is possibly derived from a family surname of [[Alfred Tennyson, 1st Baron Tennyson|Lord Tennyson]].<ref name=\"Knight 180\">Knight 180.</ref>\n* '''Martin''': A former apprentice from [[Barnsley]] and outlaw friend of Dickon. Nicknamed Ginger for his red hair.\n* '''The Abbot of Rufford''': A greedy, lecherous priest robbed by the outlaws.\n* '''Etienne''': A page who sees through Dickon's disguise during his D'Eyncourt mission.\n* '''Ulric, Gurth''': Two outlaws who join Alan's group to infiltrate D'Eyncourt's keep.\n* '''The Earl of Wessex''': A nobleman responsible for crushing Robin's rebellion. Originally a [[duke]] in the first edition, his peerage was changed in subsequent editions when Trease discovered that it did not exist during his novel's historical era.<ref name=\"Trease, Fifty years on, 151\">Trease, \"Fifty years on\", 151.</ref>\n* '''The Archbishop of York''': An ally of the Earl of Wessex who helps the noble to forestall further uprisings by spreading anti-rebellion propaganda through his clerics and suppressing written records of Robin's deeds. Depicted as an old, cowardly priest.\n\n===Folklore figures===\n* '''[[Robin Hood]]''': A central character. Depicted as an ageing but charismatic leader with \"foxy-gold\" hair and \"steel-blue\" eyes.<ref name=\"Chapter 3\">Chapter 3.</ref> Strongly [[egalitarian]], he once rebukes Dickon for addressing him as \"sir\": \"We're comrades in Sherwood, all equal. What's the sense of getting rid of one master and taking a new one?\"<ref name=\"Chapter 3\"/>\n* '''[[Alan-a-Dale]]''': A major character. Depicted as a good-natured trickster.\n* '''[[Little John]]''': A supporting character. Depicted as a good-natured giant and formidable fighter.\n* '''[[Friar Tuck]]''': A minor character. Depicted as a vigorous, worldly man.\n* '''[[Will Scarlet]]''': A minor character. Appears briefly in a dissenting role during the Abbot of Rufford robbery.\n* '''[[Maid Marian]]''': A minor character. Appears briefly as Robin's companion.\n* '''The [[Sheriff of Nottingham]]''': A minor character. Appears briefly during the Nottingham riot.\n* '''[[Kirklees, Kirklees|The Prioress of Kirklees Priory]]''': Appears in the last chapter as Robin's murderer. Depicted as a pale, sinister nun.\n\n==Setting==\n''Bows Against the Barons'' takes place largely in the [[English Midlands]], primarily in [[Nottinghamshire]]. In the last two chapters, it shifts north through the [[Peak District]] of [[Derbyshire]] into [[Yorkshire]]. As a Robin Hood novel, ''Bows Against the Barons'' features many places associated with the legend: [[Sherwood Forest]], [[Nottingham]], [[Kirklees, Kirklees|Kirklees]], [[Hathersage]]. [[Barnsdale]] is mentioned several times as an alternative refuge and destination for Sherwood's outlaws. The novel also alludes briefly to [[Edwinstowe]].\n\nThe novel takes place during the period of the [[Crusades]], although it does not specify which one. It mentions that Sir Rolf has campaigned in the [[Holy Land]] and visited the \"rotting courts of Eastern Europe\",<ref name=\"Chapter 10\">Chapter 10.</ref> an allusion to the [[Byzantine Empire]] in its decline. Sir Rolf's tyranny is attributed in part to \"[[Derogatory use of \"Byzantine\"|new notions of cruelty and luxury]]\" picked up in the latter place.<ref name=\"Chapter 10\"/> The novel also alludes to the [[Norman Conquest]] as a historical background, depicting Nottingham as a town divided between [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxon]] and [[Normans|Norman]] [[borough]]s, and comparing the battle between Robin and Wessex to the [[Battle of Hastings]].\n\nIn his 1948 foreword and 1966 postscript, Trease compares his novel's events to the [[English peasants' revolt of 1381]], and his version of Robin Hood to medieval rebels such as [[Wat Tyler]], [[Kett's Rebellion|Robert Kett]] and [[Jack Cade]].<ref name=\"Trease, Foreword, 7\">Trease, Foreword, 7.</ref><ref name=\"Trease, Postscript, 151\">Trease, Postscript, 151.</ref>\n\n==Major themes==\n[[File:Bows Against the Barons (Boland).jpg|thumb|right|Foreground from the first-edition illustration of the Nottingham riot.]] ''Bows Against the Barons'' is notable for its leftwing [[Revisionism (fictional)|revision]] of the Robin Hood legend. In contrast to earlier depictions of the outlaw as a nobleman and loyal subject of the king, it portrays Robin as a [[Populism|populist]] figure of the [[Far left|radical left]].<ref name=\"Knight 178-180\">Knight 178\u2013180.</ref><ref>Watson 714 on \"Geoffrey Trease\": \"Politically, he stood well to the left, and the Robin Hood and his comrades of Trease's first novel, ''Bows Against the Barons'' (1934), would have been more at home in Moscow than in Hollywood.\"</ref> The novel depicts Robin's outlaws as guerilla rebels who aid workers in a medieval [[class struggle]] against their masters,<ref name=\"Knight 178-180\"/> and it employs much revolutionary rhetoric, bearing chapter titles such as \"Comrades of the Forest\" and \"The People Speak\".<ref name=\"Knight 178\">Knight 178.</ref> The Robin Hood scholar [[Stephen Thomas Knight]] describes the novel as being \"rich with the leftist enthusiasm of the mid 1930s\",<ref name=\"Knight 178\"/> comparing the Nottingham riot scene to [[Sergei Eisenstein]]'s ''[[The Battleship Potemkin]]''.<ref name=\"Knight 178\"/>\n\nThe first edition of ''Bows Against the Barons'' supplemented the novel's leftist rhetoric with illustrations of a similar nature. For example, one of these illustrations depicts the Nottingham riot as a crowd scene filled with [[Hammer and sickle|hammer-and-sickle]] imagery.<ref name=\"Knight 178\"/> (See image to the right.)\n\n''Bows Against the Barons'' is also a [[Coming of age|coming-of-age]] story that depicts an adolescent protagonist's attempts to overcome difficulties and understand his place in the world.<ref name=\"Barnhouse\">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4063/is_200301/ai_n9183036 Barnhouse] 3.</ref>\n\n==Literary context==\n\n===Background===\nTrease began composing ''Bows Against the Barons'' in 1933.<ref>Trease, \"Fifty years on\", 150.</ref> In his 1948 foreword and 1966 postscript to the novel, he explained his motivation for doing so.<ref name=\"Trease, Foreword, 7\"/><ref name=\"Trease, Postscript, 151\"/> Since childhood, he had enjoyed reading stories about Robin Hood but also felt doubtful about some details in these stories \u2013 for example, the portrayal of outlaw life with its hardships as \"jolly\",<ref name=\"Trease, Foreword, 7\"/><ref name=\"Trease, Postscript, 151\"/> and Robin's subservience to the king. Trease thus wanted to \"create a new picture of Sherwood Forest which should be truer to life\".<ref name=\"Trease, Foreword, 7\"/><ref name=\"Trease, Postscript, 151\"/>\n\nIn a 1996 essay, Trease provided a more detailed context for his novel's composition:\n \n{{quote|As a child, I had been a [[G. A. Henty|Henty]] addict... [and] had absorbed the Henty values \u2013 the glories of war, the superiority of the [[British Empire]] and a white skin, the inferiority of the female... You sided with the [[Cavaliers]] against the [[Roundheads]], the French aristocrats against the howling mob. The working class were tolerated only if faithful retainers. By the end of my schooldays I was abandoning such values.... [I]n 1933 I was a rather naive Left-wing member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], newly married and struggling to survive as a freelance writer.... [A]fter a rejected novel and other disappointments the desperate idea came to me, though even then it was largely prompted by my political sympathies. Why should children be educated \u2013 indeed indoctrinated \u2013 with Right-wing views and then later have to be laboriously converted, one by one, to the Left-wing gospel? Could we not catch them young?<ref>Trease, \"Sixty years on\", 132\u2013133.</ref>}}\n\nTo realise his idea, Trease approached a publisher associated with the [[Communist Party of Great Britain]] and made his proposal for a leftist Robin Hood novel.<ref name=\"Trease, Sixty Years on, 133\">Trease, \"Sixty Years on\", 133.</ref> It was accepted. ''Bows Against the Barons'' was written \"at white-hot speed\"<ref name=\"Trease, Sixty Years on, 133\"/> and published in the following year.\n\nIn later years, Trease was critical about his own novel. He found fault with its historical errors and lack of research, both of which he attributed to youthful over-confidence,<ref name=\"Trease, Fifty years on, 151\"/> and made efforts to \"remove the worst blemishes\" in later editions.<ref name=\"Trease, Fifty years on, 152\">Trease, \"Fifty years on\", 152.</ref> He also criticised the novel for being \"propagandist\"<ref name=\"Trease, Fifty years on, 151\"/> and toned down its leftist rhetoric in later editions \u2013 for example, removing the words \"[[working class|workers]]\" and \"[[comrade]]\" from much of the text.<ref name=\"Knight 180\"/> However, Trease also acknowledged its \"vitality\"<ref name=\"Trease, Fifty years on, 152\"/> as a \"young man's book\".<ref>Trease, Postscript, 152.</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nInitially, the novel met a largely indifferent response in Britain and the United States. As the author later recalled, it was \"neither denounced nor derided but largely ignored\".<ref name=\"Trease, Sixty Years on, 133\"/> However, it was an immediate success in the [[Soviet Union]], which resulted in a five-month visit there by the author and his wife to collect [[royalties]] in 1935.<ref name=\"Trease, Sixty Years on, 133\"/><ref>[http://www.collectingbooksandmagazines.com/history.html#trease British Children's Historical Novels: Geoffrey Trease.]</ref> It was at this time that he contributed to a journal called 'International Literature: Organ of the International Union of Revolutionary Writers' Number 7 (1935) with an article 'Revolutionary Literature for the Young' in which he lays out some principles of what this should be and suggests that there should be a new kind of hero in children's books.\n\nIn ''The Oxford Companion to Children's Literature'' (1984), [[Humphrey Carpenter]] and Mari Prichard criticised ''Bows Against the Barons'' for its \"political preaching\",<ref name=\"Carpenter and Prichard 541\">Carpenter and Prichard 541.</ref> especially for making \"Robin [speak] like a member of the British Communist Party during the 1930s\".<ref name=\"Carpenter and Prichard 541\"/> However, they also praised the novel as \"a well-crafted adventure story, showing the narrative skill which is characteristic of all Trease's fiction\".<ref name=\"Carpenter and Prichard 541\"/>\n\n===Significance===\nAs Trease's first novel, ''Bows Against the Barons'' marks his debut in children's historical fiction. He would continue contributing to this genre until 1997.<ref>See the main [[Geoffrey Trease]] article for a list of his books.</ref>\n\n''Bows Against the Barons'' is notable for its radical reworking of conventions for children's historical fiction in Britain. Its anti-authoritarian stance challenged the conservative values that had dominated the genre since the 19th century,<ref>Watson 7 on \"adventure fiction\": \"G.A. Henty's numerous historical adventure stories[']... choice of setting, character and action express[es] the ideals of contemporary British imperialism. [W.E. Johns' ''Biggles'' series is characterized by] anachronistic attitudes to race, gender, class and patriotism... As society's attitudes to conflict and morality shifted, the historical adventure story of the 19th century changed. The change began with Geoffrey Trease's ''Bows Against the Barons'' (1934), a radical retelling of the Robin Hood stories.\"</ref><ref>Hollindale 205: \"The last fifty years have seen a sea-change in historical fiction for children.... The first change came in England in the 1930s, most notably in Geoffrey Trease's groundbreaking ''Bows Against the Barons''. Trease's novel, a left-wing representation of the Robin Hood story, signaled a dissatisfaction with romantic and patriotic stereotypes in historical fiction, and a belief that historical stories could be more politically sophisticated, more carefully researched, and more skeptical of self-gratifying national myths than stories of this kind had previously been.\"</ref> especially the [[imperialist]] works of [[G. A. Henty]].<ref>Watson 7.</ref> Its modern prose style, [[Egalitarianism|egalitarian]] characterisation, and [[Realism (arts)|realist]] attention to the harshness of medieval life all mark significant departures from the [[Aristocracy|aristocratic]] focus and [[Romanticism|romantic]] glamour that had dominated the genre since the 19th century.<ref>Watson 335 on \"historical fiction\": \"In Britain in the middle of the 20th century, the innovations of Geoffrey Trease introduced a fresh modern style and a democratic point of view to a genre that had become fossilized.... As early as 1934, when he wrote ''Bows Against the Barons''..., he was determined... to show not the glamour of its hero, but the brutal conditions in which the peasants lived. This represented a marked change in the outlook of children's historical fiction, which in the 19th century had worked on the assumption that a middle-class readership would be primarily interested in the lives of the aristocracy.\"</ref><ref>Fisher 491: \"[The] early books [of juvenile historical fiction] were in the main adventures or historical romances, rather than attempts to create a living past. In 1934 Geoffrey Trease wrote ''Bows Against the Barons'' and changed the nature of the genre. He painted a picture of a man fighting injustice and oppression, not the swashbuckling Robin Hood of legend but a revolutionary character, a real living person who just happened to be from the past, full of colour and vigour.\"</ref> These changes anticipate the mid-20th-century renewal of children's historical fiction by writers such as [[Rosemary Sutcliff]], [[Henry Treece]], [[Cynthia Harnett]] and Trease himself.<ref>Watson 7, 335. He credits them with continuing Trease's \"liberalisation of the historical adventure novel\" (7) and inaugurating the \"golden age\" of children's historical fiction (335).</ref>\n\nIn a 1995 ''[[Socialist Review]]'' article on children's fiction, [[Alan Gibbons]] cites ''Bows Against the Barons'' as a seminal work of socialist literature for children, praising it as an \"inspirational read\" and comparing its conclusion to [[Howard Fast]]'s ''[[Spartacus (Fast novel)|Spartacus]]''.<ref>[http://pubs.socialistreviewindex.org.uk/sr190/gibbons.htm \"Once upon a time.\"]</ref>\n\nA 2003 ''[[The Assembly on Literature for Adolescents|ALAN Review]]'' article credits ''Bows Against the Barons'' with founding the genre of the [[young adult fiction|young adult]] Robin Hood novel.<ref name=\"Barnhouse\"/> Subsequent contributions to this genre have included [[Monica Furlong]]'s ''Robin's Country'', [[Theresa Tomlinson]]'s ''Forestwife'' trilogy, [[Nancy Springer]]'s ''Rowan Hood'' series, [[Robin McKinley]]'s ''The Outlaws of Sherwood'' and Michael Cadnum's ''Forbidden Forest''.<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4063/is_200301/ai_n9183036 Barnhouse] 4\u20138.</ref>\n\n==Publication history==\n* 1934, UK, Martin Lawrence, [http://worldcat.org/oclc/6171653 OCLC 6171653], Hardcover. First edition. Illustrated by Michael Boland.\n* 1948, UK, [[Lawrence & Wishart]], [http://worldcat.org/oclc/9211980 OCLC 9211980], Hardcover. New edition. Illustrated by Jack Matthew.\n* 1966, UK, [[Hodder & Stoughton]], {{ISBN|0-340-04043-2}}, Hardcover. Revised edition. Illustrated by [[C. Walter Hodges]].\n* 2004, UK, Elliott & Thompson, {{ISBN|1-904027-26-1}}, Paperback. Young Spitfire reprint of 1966 edition.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Barnhouse, Rebecca. (Winter 2003). [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4063/is_200301/ai_n9183036/ \"Robin Hood comes of age.\"] ''[[The Assembly on Literature for Adolescents|ALAN Review]]''. URL retrieved May 2008.\n* [[Humphrey Carpenter|Carpenter, Humphrey]], and Mari Prichard. (1984). ''The Oxford Companion to Children's Literature''. Oxford: Oxford University Press.\n* Fisher, Janet. (2004). \"Historical Fiction.\" ''International Companion Encyclopedia of Children's Literature''. Ed. [[Peter Hunt (literary critic)|Peter Hunt]]. 2nd edition. London and New York: Routledge, pp 490\u2013498.\n* [[Alan Gibbons|Gibbons, Alan]]. (October 1995). [http://pubs.socialistreviewindex.org.uk/sr190/gibbons.htm \"Once upon a time.\"] ''[[Socialist Review]]''. URL retrieved May 2008.\n* [[Peter Hollindale|Hollindale, Peter]]. (December 1997). \"'Children of Eyam': The Dramatization of History.\" ''Children\u2018s Literature in Education''. Volume 28, Number 4, pp 205\u2013218.\n* [[Stephen Thomas Knight|Knight, Stephen Thomas]]. (2003). ''Robin Hood: A Mythic Biography''. Ithaca and London: Cornell University Press.\n* [[Geoffrey Trease|Trease, Geoffrey]]. (1948). Foreword (\"To the reader\"). ''Bows Against the Barons''. New edition. UK: Lawrence and Wishart, pp 7\u20138.\n* Trease, Geoffrey. (1966). Postscript (\"Author's note\"). ''Bows Against the Barons''. Revised edition. UK: Hodder & Stoughton, pp 151\u2013152.\n* Trease, Geoffrey. (September 1983). \"Fifty years on: a writer looks back.\" ''Children\u2018s Literature in Education''. Volume 14, Number 3, pp 149\u2013159.\n* Trease, Geoffrey. (September 1996). \"Sixty years on.\" ''Children\u2018s Literature in Education''. Volume 27, Number 3, pp 131\u2013141.\n* Watson, Victor, ed. (2001). ''The Cambridge Guide to Children's Books in English''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.collectingbooksandmagazines.com/history.html#trease British Children's Historical Novels: Geoffrey Trease] \u2013 discusses the author's career and novel's context.\n\n[[Category:1934 British novels]]\n[[Category:1934 children's books]]\n[[Category:British children's novels]]\n[[Category:Children's historical novels by Geoffrey Trease]]\n[[Category:Novels about rebels]]\n[[Category:Robin Hood books]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Nottinghamshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Bows Against the Barons\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = Bows Against the Barons (1966).jpg\n| caption = Cover of the 1966 revised edition\n| author        = [[Geoffrey Trease]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  =\n| country       = United Kingdom\n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| subject       =\n| genre         = Children's novel, historical novel\n| publisher     = Martin Lawrence\n| pub_date      = 1934\n| english_pub_date =\n| media_type    = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages         = 152\n| isbn          =\n| oclc          = 6171653\n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   =\n}}\n\n'''''Bows Against the Barons''''' is a 1934 children's novel by British author [[Geoffrey Trease]], based on the legend of [[Robin Hood]]. It tells the story of an adolescent boy who joins an [[outlaw]] band and takes part in a great rebellion against the [[Feudalism|feudal]] elite.  Trease's first novel, ''Bows Against the Barons'' marks the start of his prolific career as a historical novelist. It is notable for reinterpreting the Robin Hood legend and revitalizing the conventions of children's [[historical fiction]] in 20th-century Britain.\n\n==Plot introduction==\nSet in medieval England, ''Bows Against the Barons'' relates the adventures of a [[peasant]] boy who becomes an outlaw and joins the band of Robin Hood. Together, they take up arms against the masters of England and fight for the rights of the common people. The protagonist's former master tries to suppress them, but at great cost.\n\nThe title refers to the primary weapon of the outlaws \u2013 the [[longbow]].\n\n==Plot summary==\n''Bows Against the Barons'' takes place during the final months of Robin Hood's life, beginning in early June, and ending in the following year about February. It is largely told from the viewpoint of Dickon, a sixteen-year-old peasant boy from the village of [[Oxton, Nottinghamshire|Oxton]].\n\n===Chapters 1\u20139===\nThe novel opens by depicting Dickon's hardships as a [[serf]] on a [[baron]]ial [[Manorialism|manor]]. The boy being whipped by his [[bailiff]] for missing work and harassed by the village priest for not paying [[tithe]]. Despite his youth, Dickon has to serve as his family's breadwinner because his father Dick has been conscripted as an archer for the [[Crusades]]. His troubles are compounded when the King's deer from nearby [[Sherwood Forest]] ravage his garden's.  Moved by anger, Dickon kills one of the deer with an arrow. He then flees into Sherwood to avoid the penalties of [[poaching]]. Eventually, he meets [[Alan-a-Dale]], who leads him to Robin Hood's band. Proving adept at archery, Dickon is welcomed into their company.\n\nDisguised as a weaver's apprentice, Dickon becomes Robin's messenger to all of [[Nottingham]]'s rebels. Led by a bridle-smith, Dickon and the populace assemble in the market-place to protest working conditions and demand the release of imprisoned workers. The [[Sheriff of Nottingham]] attempts to disperse them, but Robin and his outlaws arrive and overwhelm the Sheriff. In the resulting riot the imprisoned workers are freed. However, mounted soldiers from [[Nottingham Castle]] arrive to quash the revolt.\n\nPursued by a horseman, Dickon escapes through secret passages and reaches the safety of Sherwood, but he is captured by [[royal forest]]ers and escorted north to be tried for poaching. However, Alan manages to make contact with Dickon, having disguised himself as a blind [[minstrel]] and his messages as [[doggerel]]. On Alan's instructions, Dickon attempts to delay the foresters' journey. His plans almost go awry when he meets his former master Sir Rolf D'Eyncourt, who has returned from the Crusades and now attempts to reclaim Dickon. Fortunately, the head forester refuses to hand over the boy, insisting on the priority of royal justice. As his journey resumes, Dickon vows revenge when he learns that his father has been killed in battle.  When Dickon and the foresters eventually reach a village, the blacksmith and the villagers protest Dickon's captivity. In the ensuing struggle, a forester almost kills Dickon, but Alan arrives in time and saves him. Together, they join the villagers in defeating the foresters.\n\nLater, soldiers are dispatched from Nottingham to punish the villagers, but Robin and his band ambush and defeat them before they reach their destination.\n\n===Chapters 10\u201320===\nIn the meantime, Sir Rolf exploits and oppresses his tenants in his pursuit of wealth and luxury. The outlaws of Sherwood oppose him, stirring up the serfs to resist his tyranny. Allied with neighboring barons, Sir Rolf pens the outlaws in Sherwood and attempts to hunt them down. The outlaws defeat them by hiding in trees and picking off his men from camouflaged positions. As they celebrate their victory, Robin reveals his ultimate goal \u2013 the overthrow of all masters and freedom for the people of England.\n\nThe outlaws now prepare for an attack on D'Eyncourt Castle, gathering money for their needs. Alan leads Dickon and others to waylay the Abbot of Rufford, disguising themselves as  knights and luring him into an ambush. Seeing Dickon's talent for disguises, Robin sends the boy to infiltrate D'Eyncourt Castle and acquire information about its defences. Disguised as a [[Page (servant)|page]] with bleached hair, Dickon manages to penetrate D'Eyncourt on Christmas, but is betrayed by an undyed lock of hair. Pursued, he hides on the chapel's beams and eventually escapes from the castle, surviving a [[crossbow]] shot.\n\nWith Dickon's information, the outlaws finally attack D'Eyncourt Castle during winter. Alan leads Dickon and a group of outlaws to infiltrate and capture the castle [[keep]]. Taking up positions on its [[battlement]]s, they pick off D'Eyncourt's defenders with their arrows while Robin launches the main assault on the outer walls. His combined force of outlaws and serfs eventually breaks through and razes the castle. Dickon kills his former bailiff, while [[Little John]] kills Sir Rolf.\n\nHeartened by their success, the outlaws attempt to march on Nottingham itself. However, the [[Earl of Wessex]] traps them in a [[pincer movement]] between Nottingham and [[Newark-on-Trent|Newark]] and defeats them all. When his ally the Archbishop wonders aloud why the rebels die so willingly on the swords of his soldiers the Earl replies grimly: \"because they know that they are going to win - but not in my time\".\n\nAlan, [[Friar Tuck]] and [[Will Scarlet]] are among those killed. Dickon, Robin and Little John survive the battle and flee north with other survivors to [[Yorkshire]], undergoing much hardship on their journey. Dickon almost drowns in a [[bog]]. Wounded, Robin takes refuge in [[Kirklees, Kirklees|Kirklees]], whose prioress [[Bloodletting|bleeds]] him to death to claim a reward from the Earl. Alerted by an arrow shot by Robin from his deathbed, the outlaws reclaim his body and burn down the priory in revenge.\n\nAfter burying Robin, the outlaw band breaks up. Dickon and Little John are the only ones who remain dedicated to Robin's cause. They depart for the [[High Peak (England)|High Peak]] in Derbyshire, determined to continue Robin's work and fulfill his visionary ideal.\n\n==Characters==\n\n===Fictional characters===\nIn order of appearance:\n* '''Dickon''': The protagonist. Depicted as a sixteen-year-old peasant boy with tousled black hair. He has a mother and three younger brothers.\n* '''William''': The bailiff of D'Eyncourt. Characterized by his harsh treatment of Sir Rolf's tenants.\n* '''Thomas Pole''': A Nottingham weaver serving as Robin's contact for the Nottingham riot.\n* '''King's foresters''': Six Gascon royal foresters who capture Dickon after the Nottingham riot. One of them, Guy, attempts to kill the boy during the villagers' attack.\n* '''Hal the Harper''': A persona adopted by Alan for his disguise as a blind minstrel.\n* '''Sir Rolf D'Eyncourt''': Dickon's former master. A violent and exploitative baron; the novel compares him to a [[Mail (armour)|mailed]] fist. His last name is possibly derived from a family surname of [[Alfred Tennyson, 1st Baron Tennyson|Lord Tennyson]].<ref name=\"Knight 180\">Knight 180.</ref>\n* '''Martin''': A former apprentice from [[Barnsley]] and outlaw friend of Dickon. Nicknamed Ginger for his red hair.\n* '''The Abbot of Rufford''': A greedy, lecherous priest robbed by the outlaws.\n* '''Etienne''': A page who sees through Dickon's disguise during his D'Eyncourt mission.\n* '''Ulric, Gurth''': Two outlaws who join Alan's group to infiltrate D'Eyncourt's keep.\n* '''The Earl of Wessex''': A nobleman responsible for crushing Robin's rebellion. Originally a [[duke]] in the first edition, his peerage was changed in subsequent editions when Trease discovered that it did not exist during his novel's historical era.<ref name=\"Trease, Fifty years on, 151\">Trease, \"Fifty years on\", 151.</ref>\n* '''The Archbishop of York''': An ally of the Earl of Wessex who helps the noble to forestall further uprisings by spreading anti-rebellion propaganda through his clerics and suppressing written records of Robin's deeds. Depicted as an old, cowardly priest.\n\n===Folklore figures===\n* '''[[Robin Hood]]''': A central character. Depicted as an ageing but charismatic leader with \"foxy-gold\" hair and \"steel-blue\" eyes.<ref name=\"Chapter 3\">Chapter 3.</ref> Strongly [[egalitarian]], he once rebukes Dickon for addressing him as \"sir\": \"We're comrades in Sherwood, all equal. What's the sense of getting rid of one master and taking a new one?\"<ref name=\"Chapter 3\"/>\n* '''[[Alan-a-Dale]]''': A major character. Depicted as a good-natured trickster.\n* '''[[Little John]]''': A supporting character. Depicted as a good-natured giant and formidable fighter.\n* '''[[Friar Tuck]]''': A minor character. Depicted as a vigorous, worldly man.\n* '''[[Will Scarlet]]''': A minor character. Appears briefly in a dissenting role during the Abbot of Rufford robbery.\n* '''[[Maid Marian]]''': A minor character. Appears briefly as Robin's companion.\n* '''The [[Sheriff of Nottingham]]''': A minor character. Appears briefly during the Nottingham riot.\n* '''[[Kirklees, Kirklees|The Prioress of Kirklees Priory]]''': Appears in the last chapter as Robin's murderer. Depicted as a pale, sinister nun.\n\n==Setting==\n''Bows Against the Barons'' takes place largely in the [[English Midlands]], primarily in [[Nottinghamshire]]. In the last two chapters, it shifts north through the [[Peak District]] of [[Derbyshire]] into [[Yorkshire]]. As a Robin Hood novel, ''Bows Against the Barons'' features many places associated with the legend: [[Sherwood Forest]], [[Nottingham]], [[Kirklees, Kirklees|Kirklees]], [[Hathersage]]. [[Barnsdale]] is mentioned several times as an alternative refuge and destination for Sherwood's outlaws. The novel also alludes briefly to [[Edwinstowe]].\n\nThe novel takes place during the period of the [[Crusades]], although it does not specify which one. It mentions that Sir Rolf has campaigned in the [[Holy Land]] and visited the \"rotting courts of Eastern Europe\",<ref name=\"Chapter 10\">Chapter 10.</ref> an allusion to the [[Byzantine Empire]] in its decline. Sir Rolf's tyranny is attributed in part to \"[[Derogatory use of \"Byzantine\"|new notions of cruelty and luxury]]\" picked up in the latter place.<ref name=\"Chapter 10\"/> The novel also alludes to the [[Norman Conquest]] as a historical background, depicting Nottingham as a town divided between [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxon]] and [[Normans|Norman]] [[borough]]s, and comparing the battle between Robin and Wessex to the [[Battle of Hastings]].\n\nIn his 1948 foreword and 1966 postscript, Trease compares his novel's events to the [[English peasants' revolt of 1381]], and his version of Robin Hood to medieval rebels such as [[Wat Tyler]], [[Kett's Rebellion|Robert Kett]] and [[Jack Cade]].<ref name=\"Trease, Foreword, 7\">Trease, Foreword, 7.</ref><ref name=\"Trease, Postscript, 151\">Trease, Postscript, 151.</ref>\n\n==Major themes==\n[[File:Bows Against the Barons (Boland).jpg|thumb|right|Foreground from the first-edition illustration of the Nottingham riot.]] ''Bows Against the Barons'' is notable for its leftwing [[Revisionism (fictional)|revision]] of the Robin Hood legend. In contrast to earlier depictions of the outlaw as a nobleman and loyal subject of the king, it portrays Robin as a [[Populism|populist]] figure of the [[Far left|radical left]].<ref name=\"Knight 178-180\">Knight 178\u2013180.</ref><ref>Watson 714 on \"Geoffrey Trease\": \"Politically, he stood well to the left, and the Robin Hood and his comrades of Trease's first novel, ''Bows Against the Barons'' (1934), would have been more at home in Moscow than in Hollywood.\"</ref> The novel depicts Robin's outlaws as guerilla rebels who aid workers in a medieval [[class struggle]] against their masters,<ref name=\"Knight 178-180\"/> and it employs much revolutionary rhetoric, bearing chapter titles such as \"Comrades of the Forest\" and \"The People Speak\".<ref name=\"Knight 178\">Knight 178.</ref> The Robin Hood scholar [[Stephen Thomas Knight]] describes the novel as being \"rich with the leftist enthusiasm of the mid 1930s\",<ref name=\"Knight 178\"/> comparing the Nottingham riot scene to [[Sergei Eisenstein]]'s ''[[The Battleship Potemkin]]''.<ref name=\"Knight 178\"/>\n\nThe first edition of ''Bows Against the Barons'' supplemented the novel's leftist rhetoric with illustrations of a similar nature. For example, one of these illustrations depicts the Nottingham riot as a crowd scene filled with [[Hammer and sickle|hammer-and-sickle]] imagery.<ref name=\"Knight 178\"/> (See image to the right.)\n\n''Bows Against the Barons'' is also a [[Coming of age|coming-of-age]] story that depicts an adolescent protagonist's attempts to overcome difficulties and understand his place in the world.<ref name=\"Barnhouse\">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4063/is_200301/ai_n9183036 Barnhouse] 3.</ref>\n\n==Literary context==\n\n===Background===\nTrease began composing ''Bows Against the Barons'' in 1933.<ref>Trease, \"Fifty years on\", 150.</ref> In his 1948 foreword and 1966 postscript to the novel, he explained his motivation for doing so.<ref name=\"Trease, Foreword, 7\"/><ref name=\"Trease, Postscript, 151\"/> Since childhood, he had enjoyed reading stories about Robin Hood but also felt doubtful about some details in these stories \u2013 for example, the portrayal of outlaw life with its hardships as \"jolly\",<ref name=\"Trease, Foreword, 7\"/><ref name=\"Trease, Postscript, 151\"/> and Robin's subservience to the king. Trease thus wanted to \"create a new picture of Sherwood Forest which should be truer to life\".<ref name=\"Trease, Foreword, 7\"/><ref name=\"Trease, Postscript, 151\"/>\n\nIn a 1996 essay, Trease provided a more detailed context for his novel's composition:\n \n{{quote|As a child, I had been a [[G. A. Henty|Henty]] addict... [and] had absorbed the Henty values \u2013 the glories of war, the superiority of the [[British Empire]] and a white skin, the inferiority of the female... You sided with the [[Cavaliers]] against the [[Roundheads]], the French aristocrats against the howling mob. The working class were tolerated only if faithful retainers. By the end of my schooldays I was abandoning such values.... [I]n 1933 I was a rather naive Left-wing member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], newly married and struggling to survive as a freelance writer.... [A]fter a rejected novel and other disappointments the desperate idea came to me, though even then it was largely prompted by my political sympathies. Why should children be educated \u2013 indeed indoctrinated \u2013 with Right-wing views and then later have to be laboriously converted, one by one, to the Left-wing gospel? Could we not catch them young?<ref>Trease, \"Sixty years on\", 132\u2013133.</ref>}}\n\nTo realise his idea, Trease approached a publisher associated with the [[Communist Party of Great Britain]] and made his proposal for a leftist Robin Hood novel.<ref name=\"Trease, Sixty Years on, 133\">Trease, \"Sixty Years on\", 133.</ref> It was accepted. ''Bows Against the Barons'' was written \"at white-hot speed\"<ref name=\"Trease, Sixty Years on, 133\"/> and published in the following year.\n\nIn later years, Trease was critical about his own novel. He found fault with its historical errors and lack of research, both of which he attributed to youthful over-confidence,<ref name=\"Trease, Fifty years on, 151\"/> and made efforts to \"remove the worst blemishes\" in later editions.<ref name=\"Trease, Fifty years on, 152\">Trease, \"Fifty years on\", 152.</ref> He also criticised the novel for being \"propagandist\"<ref name=\"Trease, Fifty years on, 151\"/> and toned down its leftist rhetoric in later editions \u2013 for example, removing the words \"[[working class|workers]]\" and \"[[comrade]]\" from much of the text.<ref name=\"Knight 180\"/> However, Trease also acknowledged its \"vitality\"<ref name=\"Trease, Fifty years on, 152\"/> as a \"young man's book\".<ref>Trease, Postscript, 152.</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nInitially, the novel met a largely indifferent response in Britain and the United States. As the author later recalled, it was \"neither denounced nor derided but largely ignored\".<ref name=\"Trease, Sixty Years on, 133\"/> However, it was an immediate success in the [[Soviet Union]], which resulted in a five-month visit there by the author and his wife to collect [[royalties]] in 1935.<ref name=\"Trease, Sixty Years on, 133\"/><ref>[http://www.collectingbooksandmagazines.com/history.html#trease British Children's Historical Novels: Geoffrey Trease.]</ref> It was at this time that he contributed to a journal called 'International Literature: Organ of the International Union of Revolutionary Writers' Number 7 (1935) with an article 'Revolutionary Literature for the Young' in which he lays out some principles of what this should be and suggests that there should be a new kind of hero in children's books.\n\nIn ''The Oxford Companion to Children's Literature'' (1984), [[Humphrey Carpenter]] and Mari Prichard criticised ''Bows Against the Barons'' for its \"political preaching\",<ref name=\"Carpenter and Prichard 541\">Carpenter and Prichard 541.</ref> especially for making \"Robin [speak] like a member of the British Communist Party during the 1930s\".<ref name=\"Carpenter and Prichard 541\"/> However, they also praised the novel as \"a well-crafted adventure story, showing the narrative skill which is characteristic of all Trease's fiction\".<ref name=\"Carpenter and Prichard 541\"/>\n\n===Significance===\nAs Trease's first novel, ''Bows Against the Barons'' marks his debut in children's historical fiction. He would continue contributing to this genre until 1997.<ref>See the main [[Geoffrey Trease]] article for a list of his books.</ref>\n\n''Bows Against the Barons'' is notable for its radical reworking of conventions for children's historical fiction in Britain. Its anti-authoritarian stance challenged the conservative values that had dominated the genre since the 19th century,<ref>Watson 7 on \"adventure fiction\": \"G.A. Henty's numerous historical adventure stories[']... choice of setting, character and action express[es] the ideals of contemporary British imperialism. [W.E. Johns' ''Biggles'' series is characterized by] anachronistic attitudes to race, gender, class and patriotism... As society's attitudes to conflict and morality shifted, the historical adventure story of the 19th century changed. The change began with Geoffrey Trease's ''Bows Against the Barons'' (1934), a radical retelling of the Robin Hood stories.\"</ref><ref>Hollindale 205: \"The last fifty years have seen a sea-change in historical fiction for children.... The first change came in England in the 1930s, most notably in Geoffrey Trease's groundbreaking ''Bows Against the Barons''. Trease's novel, a left-wing representation of the Robin Hood story, signaled a dissatisfaction with romantic and patriotic stereotypes in historical fiction, and a belief that historical stories could be more politically sophisticated, more carefully researched, and more skeptical of self-gratifying national myths than stories of this kind had previously been.\"</ref> especially the [[imperialist]] works of [[G. A. Henty]].<ref>Watson 7.</ref> Its modern prose style, [[Egalitarianism|egalitarian]] characterisation, and [[Realism (arts)|realist]] attention to the harshness of medieval life all mark significant departures from the [[Aristocracy|aristocratic]] focus and [[Romanticism|romantic]] glamour that had dominated the genre since the 19th century.<ref>Watson 335 on \"historical fiction\": \"In Britain in the middle of the 20th century, the innovations of Geoffrey Trease introduced a fresh modern style and a democratic point of view to a genre that had become fossilized.... As early as 1934, when he wrote ''Bows Against the Barons''..., he was determined... to show not the glamour of its hero, but the brutal conditions in which the peasants lived. This represented a marked change in the outlook of children's historical fiction, which in the 19th century had worked on the assumption that a middle-class readership would be primarily interested in the lives of the aristocracy.\"</ref><ref>Fisher 491: \"[The] early books [of juvenile historical fiction] were in the main adventures or historical romances, rather than attempts to create a living past. In 1934 Geoffrey Trease wrote ''Bows Against the Barons'' and changed the nature of the genre. He painted a picture of a man fighting injustice and oppression, not the swashbuckling Robin Hood of legend but a revolutionary character, a real living person who just happened to be from the past, full of colour and vigour.\"</ref> These changes anticipate the mid-20th-century renewal of children's historical fiction by writers such as [[Rosemary Sutcliff]], [[Henry Treece]], [[Cynthia Harnett]] and Trease himself.<ref>Watson 7, 335. He credits them with continuing Trease's \"liberalisation of the historical adventure novel\" (7) and inaugurating the \"golden age\" of children's historical fiction (335).</ref>\n\nIn a 1995 ''[[Socialist Review]]'' article on children's fiction, [[Alan Gibbons]] cites ''Bows Against the Barons'' as a seminal work of socialist literature for children, praising it as an \"inspirational read\" and comparing its conclusion to [[Howard Fast]]'s ''[[Spartacus (Fast novel)|Spartacus]]''.<ref>[http://pubs.socialistreviewindex.org.uk/sr190/gibbons.htm \"Once upon a time.\"]</ref>\n\nA 2003 ''[[The Assembly on Literature for Adolescents|ALAN Review]]'' article credits ''Bows Against the Barons'' with founding the genre of the [[young adult fiction|young adult]] Robin Hood novel.<ref name=\"Barnhouse\"/> Subsequent contributions to this genre have included [[Monica Furlong]]'s ''Robin's Country'', [[Theresa Tomlinson]]'s ''Forestwife'' trilogy, [[Nancy Springer]]'s ''Rowan Hood'' series, [[Robin McKinley]]'s ''The Outlaws of Sherwood'' and Michael Cadnum's ''Forbidden Forest''.<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4063/is_200301/ai_n9183036 Barnhouse] 4\u20138.</ref>\n\n==Publication history==\n* 1934, UK, Martin Lawrence, [http://worldcat.org/oclc/6171653 OCLC 6171653], Hardcover. First edition. Illustrated by Michael Boland.\n* 1948, UK, [[Lawrence & Wishart]], [http://worldcat.org/oclc/9211980 OCLC 9211980], Hardcover. New edition. Illustrated by Jack Matthew.\n* 1966, UK, [[Hodder & Stoughton]], {{ISBN|0-340-04043-2}}, Hardcover. Revised edition. Illustrated by [[C. Walter Hodges]].\n* 2004, UK, Elliott & Thompson, {{ISBN|1-904027-26-1}}, Paperback. Young Spitfire reprint of 1966 edition.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Barnhouse, Rebecca. (Winter 2003). [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa4063/is_200301/ai_n9183036/ \"Robin Hood comes of age.\"] ''[[The Assembly on Literature for Adolescents|ALAN Review]]''. URL retrieved May 2008.\n* [[Humphrey Carpenter|Carpenter, Humphrey]], and Mari Prichard. (1984). ''The Oxford Companion to Children's Literature''. Oxford: Oxford University Press.\n* Fisher, Janet. (2004). \"Historical Fiction.\" ''International Companion Encyclopedia of Children's Literature''. Ed. [[Peter Hunt (literary critic)|Peter Hunt]]. 2nd edition. London and New York: Routledge, pp 490\u2013498.\n* [[Alan Gibbons|Gibbons, Alan]]. (October 1995). [http://pubs.socialistreviewindex.org.uk/sr190/gibbons.htm \"Once upon a time.\"] ''[[Socialist Review]]''. URL retrieved May 2008.\n* [[Peter Hollindale|Hollindale, Peter]]. (December 1997). \"'Children of Eyam': The Dramatization of History.\" ''Children\u2018s Literature in Education''. Volume 28, Number 4, pp 205\u2013218.\n* [[Stephen Thomas Knight|Knight, Stephen Thomas]]. (2003). ''Robin Hood: A Mythic Biography''. Ithaca and London: Cornell University Press.\n* [[Geoffrey Trease|Trease, Geoffrey]]. (1948). Foreword (\"To the reader\"). ''Bows Against the Barons''. New edition. UK: Lawrence and Wishart, pp 7\u20138.\n* Trease, Geoffrey. (1966). Postscript (\"Author's note\"). ''Bows Against the Barons''. Revised edition. UK: Hodder & Stoughton, pp 151\u2013152.\n* Trease, Geoffrey. (September 1983). \"Fifty years on: a writer looks back.\" ''Children\u2018s Literature in Education''. Volume 14, Number 3, pp 149\u2013159.\n* Trease, Geoffrey. (September 1996). \"Sixty years on.\" ''Children\u2018s Literature in Education''. Volume 27, Number 3, pp 131\u2013141.\n* Watson, Victor, ed. (2001). ''The Cambridge Guide to Children's Books in English''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.collectingbooksandmagazines.com/history.html#trease British Children's Historical Novels: Geoffrey Trease] \u2013 discusses the author's career and novel's context.\n\n[[Category:1934 British novels]]\n[[Category:1934 children's books]]\n[[Category:British children's novels]]\n[[Category:Children's historical novels by Geoffrey Trease]]\n[[Category:Novels about rebels]]\n[[Category:Robin Hood books]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Nottinghamshire]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHigh Peak(link changed toHigh Peak (upland)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bows_against_the_Barons"}
{"title_page": "Corruption in the Democratic Republic of the Congo", "text_new": "{{short description|Institutional corruption in the country}}\n{{Political corruption sidebar|image=[[File:Flag of the Democratic Republic of the Congo.svg|150 px]]}} \n'''Corruption in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]''', once legendary, has diminished in recent years, but continues to exceed corruption in most states. The [[BBC]]'s DRC country profile calls its recent history \"one of civil war and corruption.\"<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-13283212\n|title=DR Congo country profile\n|date= 10 February 2016\n|accessdate=29 July 2016\n}}\n</ref> [[President of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|President]] [[Joseph Kabila]] established the Commission of Repression of Economic Crimes upon his ascension to power in 2001.<ref name=d>\n{{cite book\n|last=Werve\n|first=Jonathan\n|year=2006\n|title=The Corruption Notebooks 2006\n|pages=57\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n[[Mobutu Sese Seko]] ruled [[Zaire]] from 1965 to 1997, looting his country's wealth for personal use to such a degree that critics coined the term \"[[kleptocracy]]\". A relative once explained how the government illicitly collected revenue: \"Mobutu would ask one of us to go to the bank and take out a million. We'd go to an intermediary and tell him to get five million. He would go to the bank with Mobutu's authority, and take out ten. Mobutu got one, and we took the other nine.\"<ref name=a>\n{{cite book\n|last=Ludwig\n|first=Arnold M.\n|year=2002\n|title=King of the Mountain: The Nature of Political Leadership\n|url=https://archive.org/details/45776029503226643287\n|pages=72\n}}\n</ref>\nThe Congolese explained the lack of support from the government by the humorous ''[[article 15 (Democratic Republic of the Congo)|article 15]]'': ''D\u00e9brouillez-vous'' (\"Figure it yourself\").\n\nMobutu institutionalized corruption to prevent political rivals from challenging his control, leading to an [[Economy of the Democratic Republic of the Congo#1990s|economic collapse in 1996]].<ref name=b>\n{{cite book\n|last=Nafziger\n|first=E. Wayne\n|author2=Raimo Frances Stewart\n|year=2000|title=War, Hunger, and Displacement: The Origins of Humanitarian Emergencies\n|pages=261\n}}</ref> Mobutu allegedly stole up to US$4 billion while in office.<ref name=c>\n{{cite book\n|last=Mesquita\n|first=Bruce Bueno de\n|authorlink=Bruce Bueno de Mesquita\n|year=2003\n|title=The Logic of Political Survival\n|pages=167\n|title-link=The Logic of Political Survival\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Reuters]] unveiled a scheme involving overpriced [[biometric passport]]s.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/congo-passports/\n|title=Congo's pricey passport scheme sends millions of dollars offshore\n|date= 13 April 2017\n|accessdate=14 April 2017\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Corruption Perception Index==\n{{Main|Corruption Perception Index}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold\"  valign=\"bottom\"\n| width=\"93.75\" Height=\"11.25\"| Year\n| width=\"93.75\" | Ranking\n| width=\"92.25\" | Countries ranked\n| width=\"92.25\" | Rating\n\n|-   valign=\"bottom\"\n| Height=\"11.25\" | 2004\n | 133\n | 145\n | 2.0<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2004|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2004|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130134848/http://transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2004|archive-date=2010-11-30|access-date=2008-01-22}}</ref>\n | -\n\n|-   valign=\"bottom\"\n| Height=\"11.25\" | 2005\n | 144\n | 158\n | 2.1<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2005|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2005|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512023516/http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2005|archive-date=2008-05-12|access-date=2008-01-22}}</ref>\n | -\n\n|-   valign=\"bottom\"\n| Height=\"11.25\" | 2006\n | 156\n | 163\n | 2.0<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2006|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2006|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110416023729/http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2006|archive-date=2011-04-16|access-date=2008-01-22}}</ref>\n | -\n\n|-   valign=\"bottom\"\n| Height=\"11.25\" | 2007\n | 168\n | 179\n | 1.9<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2007|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2007|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418031106/http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2007|archive-date=2012-04-18|access-date=2009-06-11}}</ref>\n | -\n\n|-   valign=\"bottom\"\n| Height=\"11.25\" | 2008\n | 171\n | 180\n | 1.7<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2008|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2008|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228083800/http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2008|archive-date=2011-02-28|access-date=2009-06-11}}</ref>\n | -\n\n|}\n\nIn 2015 [[Transparency International]] ranked the DRC 147 out of 167 countries in the [[Corruption Perception Index]], tying [[Chad]] and the [[Republic of the Congo]] with a score of 22/100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/cpi2015#results-table|title=Transparency International - The Global Anti-Corruption Coalition|last=e.V.|date=|website=www.transparency.org|publisher=Transparency International|access-date=2016-11-04}}</ref>\n\n== The Kabila Regime ==\n[[Laurent Kabila]] led an [[insurgence]] group against [[Mobutu Sese Seko|Mobutu]] and quickly assumed power after [[Mobutu Sese Seko|Mobutu]] was overthrown.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.antigenocide.org/images/D.R._Congo_7_Dec_06_Kabila_Promises_New_Era_for_Congo_Nation_Inaugurates_First_Freely_Elected_Leader_Since_1960.pdf|title=Kabila Promises New Era for Congo|last=Isango|first=Eddy|date=December 7, 2006|website=Antigenocide.org}}</ref> During this time period, [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Kabila]] issued a statement making himself president with near absolute power in the government.<ref name=\":3\">https://search.proquest.com/docview/200705711</ref> With people supporting him for overthrowing Mobutu, he was not initially met with much public opposition.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Schatzberg|first=Michael G.|date=1997-10-01|title=Beyond Mobutu: Kabila and the Congo|journal=Journal of Democracy|language=en|volume=8|issue=4|pages=70\u201384|doi=10.1353/jod.1997.0065|issn=1086-3214}}</ref> However, [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Kabila's]] and his government's goals for the regime were said to be unclear and vague.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nHe refused immediate elections in fear of the country returning to [[Mobutuism]], and continued to postpone promised elections.<ref name=\":3\" /> The constitution was not changed, and he and his peers exploited resources for their personal benefit.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.internationalrivers.org/sites/default/files/attached-files/corruption_in_the_drc_.pdf|title=Corruption and Infrastructure Megaprojects in the DR Congo|last=Nguh|first=Augustin|date=December 2013|website=International Rivers}}</ref> [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Laurent Kabila]], led a regime that upheld corruption through [[clientelism]] by appointing his clients as cabinet members.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|journal=Africa Today|volume=56|issue=4|pages=42\u201361|language=en|doi=10.2979/aft.2010.56.4.42|jstor=10.2979/aft.2010.56.4.42|year=2010|last1=Matti|title=The Democratic Republic of the Congo? Corruption, Patronage, and Competitive Authoritarianism in the DRC}}</ref> Under the [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Kabila]] regime, the DRC has failed to pull itself out of its \u201c[[State collapse|collapsed state]]\u201d status from when [[Mobutu Sese Seko|Mobutu]] was in power.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reyntjens|first=Filip|date=2001|title=Briefing: The Democratic Republic of Congo, from Kabila to Kabila|journal=African Affairs|volume=100|issue=399|pages=311\u2013317|jstor=3518770|doi=10.1093/afraf/100.399.311}}</ref>\n\nThe government has not implemented security and human rights reforms, free media, and the decentralization of power.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dizolele|first=Mvemba|date=July 2010|title=The Mirage of Democracy in the DRC|url=http://friendsofthecongo.org/pdf/dizolele_democracy.pdf|journal=Journal of Democracy|volume=21|issue=3|pages=143\u2013157|via=National Endowment for Democracy and The Johns Hopkins University Press|doi=10.1353/jod.0.0189}}</ref> The economy plummeted, forcing workers to be underpaid and living conditions to deteriorate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africaportal.org|title=Africa Portal|last=Mills|first=Greg|date=February 2002|website=Africa Portal|access-date=2018-10-11}}</ref> [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Laurent Kabila]] was killed in 2001 by one of his body guards in an attempted [[coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Christensen|first=Christian|date=2004|title=Political Victims and Media Focus: The Killings of Laurent Kabila, Zoran Djindjic, Anna Lindh and Pim Fortuyn|url=http://site.iugaza.edu.ps/tissa/files/2010/02/Political_Victims_and_Media_Focus.pdf|journal=Journal for Crime, Conflict and the Media|volume=2|pages=17|via=JC2M}}</ref>\n\nDuring that time period, The [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Democratic Republic of Congo]] received a score of 1.9 out of 10 in the [[Corruption Perceptions Index|Corruption Perception Index]], which reveals high levels of corruption.<ref name=\":5\"/>\n\nHis son, [[Joseph Kabila]] was elected president after [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Laurent Kabila]]'s death.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Joseph Kabila]] is working with the [[World Bank Group|World Bank]] to curtail corruption and improve economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unpan1.un.org/intradoc/groups/public/documents/UN/UNPAN023260.pdf|title=Democratic Republic of Congo|website=United Nations}}</ref> In addition, the Commission of Economic Crimes was implemented in 2001 by President [[Joseph Kabila]]. Nonetheless, there are still reports of high ranking officials exploiting resources for their personal benefit and other forms of corruption.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2006, the constitution changed the president's minimum age from 35 to 30 years old to include [[Joseph Kabila]], who was 33 at the time.<ref name=\":5\"/> Similar to his father, [[Joseph Kabila]] has also been reported to minimize [[freedom of speech]] and [[freedom of the press]] by imprisoning opponents.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Resource Extraction in the Democratic Republic of Congo]]\n*[[Democratic Republic of the Congo passport]]\n*[[Corruption in Angola]]\n\n'''General:'''\n*[[Crime in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n*[[Kleptocracy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://edutube.org/interactive/corruption-perception-index-cpi-interactive-world-map Interactive world map of the Corruption Perception Index]\n\n{{DRC topics}}\n{{Africa topic|Corruption in}}\n\n[[Category:Corruption by country|Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Corruption in Africa|Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Crime in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Economy of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Institutional corruption in the country}}\n{{Political corruption sidebar|image=[[File:Flag of the Democratic Republic of the Congo.svg|150 px]]}} \n'''Corruption in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]''', once legendary, has diminished in recent years, but continues to exceed corruption in most states. The [[BBC]]'s DRC country profile calls its recent history \"one of civil war and corruption.\"<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-13283212\n|title=DR Congo country profile\n|date= 10 February 2016\n|accessdate=29 July 2016\n}}\n</ref> [[President of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|President]] [[Joseph Kabila]] established the Commission of Repression of Economic Crimes upon his ascension to power in 2001.<ref name=d>\n{{cite book\n|last=Werve\n|first=Jonathan\n|year=2006\n|title=The Corruption Notebooks 2006\n|pages=57\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n[[Mobutu Sese Seko]] ruled [[Zaire]] from 1965 to 1997, looting his country's wealth for personal use to such a degree that critics coined the term \"[[kleptocracy]]\". A relative once explained how the government illicitly collected revenue: \"Mobutu would ask one of us to go to the bank and take out a million. We'd go to an intermediary and tell him to get five million. He would go to the bank with Mobutu's authority, and take out ten. Mobutu got one, and we took the other nine.\"<ref name=a>\n{{cite book\n|last=Ludwig\n|first=Arnold M.\n|year=2002\n|title=King of the Mountain: The Nature of Political Leadership\n|url=https://archive.org/details/45776029503226643287\n|pages=72\n}}\n</ref>\nThe Congolese explained the lack of support from the government by the humorous ''[[article 15 (Democratic Republic of the Congo)]]'': ''D\u00e9brouillez-vous'' (\"Figure it yourself\").\n\nMobutu institutionalized corruption to prevent political rivals from challenging his control, leading to an [[Economy of the Democratic Republic of the Congo#1990s|economic collapse in 1996]].<ref name=b>\n{{cite book\n|last=Nafziger\n|first=E. Wayne\n|author2=Raimo Frances Stewart\n|year=2000|title=War, Hunger, and Displacement: The Origins of Humanitarian Emergencies\n|pages=261\n}}</ref> Mobutu allegedly stole up to US$4 billion while in office.<ref name=c>\n{{cite book\n|last=Mesquita\n|first=Bruce Bueno de\n|authorlink=Bruce Bueno de Mesquita\n|year=2003\n|title=The Logic of Political Survival\n|pages=167\n|title-link=The Logic of Political Survival\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Reuters]] unveiled a scheme involving overpriced [[biometric passport]]s.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/congo-passports/\n|title=Congo's pricey passport scheme sends millions of dollars offshore\n|date= 13 April 2017\n|accessdate=14 April 2017\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Corruption Perception Index==\n{{Main|Corruption Perception Index}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold\"  valign=\"bottom\"\n| width=\"93.75\" Height=\"11.25\"| Year\n| width=\"93.75\" | Ranking\n| width=\"92.25\" | Countries ranked\n| width=\"92.25\" | Rating\n\n|-   valign=\"bottom\"\n| Height=\"11.25\" | 2004\n | 133\n | 145\n | 2.0<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2004|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2004|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130134848/http://transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2004|archive-date=2010-11-30|access-date=2008-01-22}}</ref>\n | -\n\n|-   valign=\"bottom\"\n| Height=\"11.25\" | 2005\n | 144\n | 158\n | 2.1<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2005|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2005|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512023516/http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2005|archive-date=2008-05-12|access-date=2008-01-22}}</ref>\n | -\n\n|-   valign=\"bottom\"\n| Height=\"11.25\" | 2006\n | 156\n | 163\n | 2.0<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2006|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2006|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110416023729/http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2006|archive-date=2011-04-16|access-date=2008-01-22}}</ref>\n | -\n\n|-   valign=\"bottom\"\n| Height=\"11.25\" | 2007\n | 168\n | 179\n | 1.9<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2007|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2007|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418031106/http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2007|archive-date=2012-04-18|access-date=2009-06-11}}</ref>\n | -\n\n|-   valign=\"bottom\"\n| Height=\"11.25\" | 2008\n | 171\n | 180\n | 1.7<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2008|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2008|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110228083800/http://www.transparency.org/policy_research/surveys_indices/cpi/2008|archive-date=2011-02-28|access-date=2009-06-11}}</ref>\n | -\n\n|}\n\nIn 2015 [[Transparency International]] ranked the DRC 147 out of 167 countries in the [[Corruption Perception Index]], tying [[Chad]] and the [[Republic of the Congo]] with a score of 22/100.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.transparency.org/cpi2015#results-table|title=Transparency International - The Global Anti-Corruption Coalition|last=e.V.|date=|website=www.transparency.org|publisher=Transparency International|access-date=2016-11-04}}</ref>\n\n== The Kabila Regime ==\n[[Laurent Kabila]] led an [[insurgence]] group against [[Mobutu Sese Seko|Mobutu]] and quickly assumed power after [[Mobutu Sese Seko|Mobutu]] was overthrown.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.antigenocide.org/images/D.R._Congo_7_Dec_06_Kabila_Promises_New_Era_for_Congo_Nation_Inaugurates_First_Freely_Elected_Leader_Since_1960.pdf|title=Kabila Promises New Era for Congo|last=Isango|first=Eddy|date=December 7, 2006|website=Antigenocide.org}}</ref> During this time period, [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Kabila]] issued a statement making himself president with near absolute power in the government.<ref name=\":3\">https://search.proquest.com/docview/200705711</ref> With people supporting him for overthrowing Mobutu, he was not initially met with much public opposition.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Schatzberg|first=Michael G.|date=1997-10-01|title=Beyond Mobutu: Kabila and the Congo|journal=Journal of Democracy|language=en|volume=8|issue=4|pages=70\u201384|doi=10.1353/jod.1997.0065|issn=1086-3214}}</ref> However, [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Kabila's]] and his government's goals for the regime were said to be unclear and vague.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nHe refused immediate elections in fear of the country returning to [[Mobutuism]], and continued to postpone promised elections.<ref name=\":3\" /> The constitution was not changed, and he and his peers exploited resources for their personal benefit.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.internationalrivers.org/sites/default/files/attached-files/corruption_in_the_drc_.pdf|title=Corruption and Infrastructure Megaprojects in the DR Congo|last=Nguh|first=Augustin|date=December 2013|website=International Rivers}}</ref> [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Laurent Kabila]], led a regime that upheld corruption through [[clientelism]] by appointing his clients as cabinet members.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|journal=Africa Today|volume=56|issue=4|pages=42\u201361|language=en|doi=10.2979/aft.2010.56.4.42|jstor=10.2979/aft.2010.56.4.42|year=2010|last1=Matti|title=The Democratic Republic of the Congo? Corruption, Patronage, and Competitive Authoritarianism in the DRC}}</ref> Under the [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Kabila]] regime, the DRC has failed to pull itself out of its \u201c[[State collapse|collapsed state]]\u201d status from when [[Mobutu Sese Seko|Mobutu]] was in power.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reyntjens|first=Filip|date=2001|title=Briefing: The Democratic Republic of Congo, from Kabila to Kabila|journal=African Affairs|volume=100|issue=399|pages=311\u2013317|jstor=3518770|doi=10.1093/afraf/100.399.311}}</ref>\n\nThe government has not implemented security and human rights reforms, free media, and the decentralization of power.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dizolele|first=Mvemba|date=July 2010|title=The Mirage of Democracy in the DRC|url=http://friendsofthecongo.org/pdf/dizolele_democracy.pdf|journal=Journal of Democracy|volume=21|issue=3|pages=143\u2013157|via=National Endowment for Democracy and The Johns Hopkins University Press|doi=10.1353/jod.0.0189}}</ref> The economy plummeted, forcing workers to be underpaid and living conditions to deteriorate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africaportal.org|title=Africa Portal|last=Mills|first=Greg|date=February 2002|website=Africa Portal|access-date=2018-10-11}}</ref> [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Laurent Kabila]] was killed in 2001 by one of his body guards in an attempted [[coup d'\u00e9tat]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Christensen|first=Christian|date=2004|title=Political Victims and Media Focus: The Killings of Laurent Kabila, Zoran Djindjic, Anna Lindh and Pim Fortuyn|url=http://site.iugaza.edu.ps/tissa/files/2010/02/Political_Victims_and_Media_Focus.pdf|journal=Journal for Crime, Conflict and the Media|volume=2|pages=17|via=JC2M}}</ref>\n\nDuring that time period, The [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Democratic Republic of Congo]] received a score of 1.9 out of 10 in the [[Corruption Perceptions Index|Corruption Perception Index]], which reveals high levels of corruption.<ref name=\":5\"/>\n\nHis son, [[Joseph Kabila]] was elected president after [[Laurent-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Kabila|Laurent Kabila]]'s death.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Joseph Kabila]] is working with the [[World Bank Group|World Bank]] to curtail corruption and improve economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://unpan1.un.org/intradoc/groups/public/documents/UN/UNPAN023260.pdf|title=Democratic Republic of Congo|website=United Nations}}</ref> In addition, the Commission of Economic Crimes was implemented in 2001 by President [[Joseph Kabila]]. Nonetheless, there are still reports of high ranking officials exploiting resources for their personal benefit and other forms of corruption.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2006, the constitution changed the president's minimum age from 35 to 30 years old to include [[Joseph Kabila]], who was 33 at the time.<ref name=\":5\"/> Similar to his father, [[Joseph Kabila]] has also been reported to minimize [[freedom of speech]] and [[freedom of the press]] by imprisoning opponents.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Resource Extraction in the Democratic Republic of Congo]]\n*[[Democratic Republic of the Congo passport]]\n*[[Corruption in Angola]]\n\n'''General:'''\n*[[Crime in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n*[[Kleptocracy]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://edutube.org/interactive/corruption-perception-index-cpi-interactive-world-map Interactive world map of the Corruption Perception Index]\n\n{{DRC topics}}\n{{Africa topic|Corruption in}}\n\n[[Category:Corruption by country|Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Corruption in Africa|Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Crime in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Economy of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Politics of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n", "name_user": "Error", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:|", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corruption_in_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo"}
{"title_page": "Toddbrook Reservoir", "text_new": "{{short description|English reservoir}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox lake\n| name = Toddbrook Reservoir\n| image = Toddbrook Reservoir (northern end) - geograph.org.uk - 77856.jpg\n| caption = Looking southeast towards the dam, from the northern corner\n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[High Peak (upland)|High Peak]], [[Derbyshire]]\n| coords = {{coord|53|19|30|N|1|59|37|W|type:waterbody_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| type = [[reservoir]]\n| inflow = \n| outflow = \n| catchment = {{convert|1700|ha|abbr=on}}\n| basin_countries = United Kingdom\n| length = \n| width = \n| area = {{convert|14.6|ha|abbr=on}}\n| depth = \n| max-depth = {{convert|23.8|m|abbr=on}} <ref name=crtupdate>[https://canalrivertrust.org.uk/news-and-views/news/toddbrook-reservoir-update Toddbrook Reservoir update], Canal & River Trust, accessed 2. August 2019</ref> \n| volume ={{convert|1288000|m3|impgal}}<ref name=tedd140 />\n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|185.69|m|abbr=on}} <ref name=crtupdate>[https://canalrivertrust.org.uk/news-and-views/news/toddbrook-reservoir-update Toddbrook Reservoir update], Canal & River Trust, accessed 2. August 2019</ref> \n| frozen = \n| islands = None\n| cities = \n}}\n'''Toddbrook Reservoir''', a feeder for the [[Peak Forest Canal]], opened in 1838.<ref name=Labrum9>{{cite book |editor1-last=Labrum |editor1-first=E.A |date=1994 |title=Civil Engineering Heritage: Eastern and central England |publisher=Institution of Civil Engineers |pages=9\u201310 |isbn=072771970X}}</ref> It is sited above the town of [[Whaley Bridge]] in the [[Derbyshire]] [[High Peak (upland)|High Peak]] area of England. The reservoir is a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSI) providing habitats for [[Grey Heron|herons]], [[duck]]s and other animals and fish, while rare [[moss]]es and [[Marchantiophyta|liverwort]]s grow on its shores, particularly short-lived species that grow on seasonally exposed mud.<ref name=\"sssi\">{{cite web | url = http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/citation/citation_photo/1001257.pdf | title = Toddbrook Reservoir [SSSI citation] | publisher = Natural England | date =1981 | accessdate = 12 July 2012}}</ref> The reservoir is used for [[sailing]]<ref name=tbk>[http://www.toddbrooksailingclub.org.uk/ Toddbrook Sailing Club] accessed 16 May 2008</ref> and [[angling]]. The reservoir is owned by the [[Canal & River Trust]] and, like the nearby [[Combs, Derbyshire|Combs]] reservoir, is a feeder reservoir for the Peak Forest Canal. The feeder runs through Whaley Bridge, and with the Combs feed enters the canal system in a pool close to the transhipment shed at the Whaley Bridge canal basin.\n\nThe reservoir is fed from the Todd Brook, a stream which has a catchment area of around {{convert|1700|ha}} including the moorland on [[Shining Tor]] and farmland around [[Kettleshulme]] village. Water enters the reservoir on its north bank via a small waterfall. The first several inches of water do not flow into the reservoir but flow down the reservoir's run-off into the [[River Goyt]]. The reservoir often receives little or no inflow during periods when rainfall does not allow the level to exceed the barrier, and this often affects  the reservoir's water level, particularly in the summer months.\n\nThe reservoir's dam is built from earth with a [[puddle clay]] core. The embankment is straight in plan and approximately 310m long. The average crest level is 187.3mAOD. In August 2019, concrete panels on its spillway were dislodged after heavy rain, triggering the evacuation of parts of Whaley Bridge and the surrounding area due to the possibility of the dam collapsing.\n\n==Dam works==\n{{More citations needed section|date=August 2019}}\n\nGrowth of traffic on the Peak Forest Canal meant that that water supply from Combs Reservoir proved insufficient, despite the trustees of the [[Macclesfield Canal]] allowing the transfer of water from the summit level of their [[Sutton Lane Ends|Sutton]] Reservoir. The General Assembly of the Peak Forest Canal company approved the adoption of the site of Toddbrook Reservoir in June 1834 on the advice of Samuel Taylor, a land surveyor (a further reservoir on the Hockham Brook above [[Chapel Milton]] was never completed). Negotiations for the sale of the land began in June 1834 but were not concluded until 1839. Work did not go smoothly: from the start, concerns were expressed over the geology of the site and the known existence of coal workings below the valley, and various sites were considered for the dam. John Wood drew up the first plans, though these were amended on the advice of various consultant engineers, including Robert Matthews (engineer of the [[Rochdale Canal]]) and Nicholas Brown, who had experience of building reservoirs.<ref>{{harvnb|Boyes|2012|p=75\u201376}}</ref> Contracts for the reservoir construction were awarded to William Collinge and Richard and William Walker in August 1836. Geological problems continued to dog the project, and the site of the dam was altered on the advice of [[William Mackenzie (contractor)|William Mackenzie]] in 1837. As a stopgap, waters from the Todd Brook were diverted around the reservoir site and into the canal, and this solution proved so effective that consideration was even given to abandoning the reservoir project. Ultimately, however, construction continued using new plans supervised by Mackenzie and the reservoir's completion was reported in the canal committee's annual report of June 1841. The {{convert|24|m|adj=on}} dam was at the time the tallest ever built for a canal reservoir.<ref>{{harvnb|Boyes|2012|p=77\u201378}}</ref>\n\nConsultant engineer Nicholas Brown's report of 1836 had specified a puddle trench varying from 12 feet at the brook end to 6 feet in width,<ref>{{harvnb|Boyes|2012|p=190}}</ref> but investigations in the late 20th century led to doubt as to whether it was constructed as laid out on original drawings or with more porous core material. The peak of the dam wall is supported either side by embankments with a slope of 1:2.<ref name=tedd140 /> Underneath the dam, the geology includes glacial sands and gravel, [[Till|glacial till]] overlying mudstones, sandstones, shales and coal measures.<ref name=civeng>{{cite web|url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/engineers-battle-night-save-derbyshire-dam-02-08-2019 |title=Engineers battle through night to prevent catastrophic dam failure |last=Horgan |first=Rob  |publisher= New Civil Engineer |access-date= 4 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was known that local coal mining had been a threat to the dam's integrity for many years, with complaints dating from 1880 that water was leaking into coal mines.<ref name=Labrum9 /> After the Whaley Bridge Colliery proposed to work coal below the site, the [[Manchester, Sheffield and Lincolnshire Railway]], who owned the canal at the time, purchased coal measures beneath the reservoir site for \u00a38,550 after evidence of subsidence came to light.<ref>{{harvnb|Boyes|2012|p=79}}</ref>\n\nLeakage was observed from the foot of the dam and investigated in 1931. The leak coincided with a hollow in the upstream slope of the dam which was filled in. In November 1975, low water revealed that another hollow had formed in the same area which led to regular monitoring of the dam. In 1977 it was noted that there had been {{convert|12|cm}} of subsidence since 1975. The reservoir was drained and a four metre wide hole was discovered, partly filled by silt and a tree which appeared to have been drawn in by the flow of water into the hole. Between 1978 and 1980, further investigations included drilling  bore holes into the affected areas. In 1981 a {{convert|1.2|m|adj=on}} diameter masonry culvert was discovered which had probably been built into the dam wall at the time of its construction to divert ground water, which can undermine a dam from below. Leaks had developed around it, as had happened to other dams where pipework or drainage had been built through a clay dam wall creating a weak spot.<ref name=tedd140 /> Repairs were made and a layer of waterproof clay was laid over the weak spot on the upstream face of the dam. The clay core was reinforced by injecting grout along a 60 metre length and the reservoir was refilled in December 1983.<ref name=tedd140 /><!--From Boyes: In 1976\u201377 both Toddbrook and Combs Reservoirs were drained to allow the dams to be checked. A depression {{convert|8|m}} in diameter was discovered on the inner face of the Toddbrook embankment, considered to have resulted from a weakness where the brook passed under the dam, the fault of the original contractor. Grouting was applied and a new wave wall added to the embankment.<ref>{{harvnb|Boyes|2012|p=80}}</ref>-->\n\n[[File:Toddbrook_Reservoir,_the_dam_-_geograph.org.uk_-_77850.jpg|thumb|left |The 1969 dam wall spillway in 2005. Note channel for original spillway in foreground.]]\nIn December 1964, high rainfall resulted in damage to the dam\u2019s [[spillway]]. The water level rose to one metre above the overflow spillway at the side of the reservoir and remained high for 24 hours but did not rise above the main dam wall and the spillway prevented the water flowing over it and washing the earth embankment away. However, the high volume of water damaged the lower part of the spillway channel and escaping water started to erode the right bank at the base of the dam. The damage was repaired in 1965 but flood studies judged the spillway to be inadequate. It was noted by the [[Environment Agency]] that damage had occurred to nine other dams of similar design where the spillway delivered water to the foot of the dam.<ref name=tedd140 />\n\nIn 1969 an additional concrete spillway was built on the downstream face of the dam along a length of {{convert|75|m}}. This new [[weir]] was formed by adding concrete capping to the earth embankment to protect it from flowing water and was set above the existing spillway so that excess water would initially overflow along the original path.<ref name=tedd140>{{cite web |url=http://evidence.environment-agency.gov.uk/FCERM/Libraries/FCERM_Project_Documents/Lessons_from_Historical_Dam_Incidents.sflb.ashx |title=Delivering Benefits Through Evidence Lessons from Historical Dam Incidents |last1=Charles |first1=J Andrew|last2=Tedd |first2=Paul|last3=Warren |first3=Alan |publisher=Environment Agency |access-date=1 August 2019 |page=140}}</ref><ref name=Labrum9 />  In the 1980s, [[British Waterways]] carried out significant repair works to deal with leaks involving the mine shafts around the dam and a culvert was constructed under the current beach/launching area of the reservoir. A stone marker on the main beach showed its location for many years, but was relocated to the footpath opposite Toddbrook Lodge during access work for the 2009 draining.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nThe reservoir was partially drained again in 2009 for inspection<ref>{{Cite|url=http://www.whaleybridge.net/forum/posts/t189-Toddbrook-Reservoir/page2|title = Toddbrook Reservoir forum posts at whalyebridge.net|date=14 September 2009}}</ref> before being fully drained for repairs in 2010. The \u00a3500,000 project entailed fish stocks being moved to other locations before repairing pitching to the wall of the dam. Other work  involved repairs to the 100-year-old pipework used to feed water stored in the reservoir at a controlled rate into the Peak Forest Canal and included; clearing silt and debris from pipework inlets, removing old valves and connections to pipework, cleaning, inspecting and repairing old pipework, re-lining old pipework with a resin \u201csock\u201d liner cured under pressure using ultraviolet lights, replacement of valves, testing of the new system and replacement of screens to intakes.<ref>{{Cite|url=http://www.whaleybridge.com/2011/01/toddbrook-reservoir-refilling-to-start-in-new-year/|title = Toddbrook Reservoir refilling to start in new year|date=5 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==2019 incident==\n[[File:Playground under construction (geograph 3891775).jpg|thumb|right|A view looking down the spillway in 2014 before the concrete slabs to the left of the picture were damaged in 2019]]\nOn 1 August 2019, a major incident was declared and 1,500 residents were evacuated from parts of [[Whaley Bridge]], [[Furness Vale]] and [[New Mills]] after concrete slabs on the 1969 overflow spillway were partially dislodged by high volumes of water following several days of heavy rain.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-49189955 | title = Whaley Bridge dam collapse: Town evacuated over Toddbrook Reservoir fears| publisher = BBC News | date = 1 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/reservoir-sealed-police-people-told-16681771|title=Thousands of Whaley Bridge residents evacuated as 'danger to life' warning issued over fears dam could burst|work=[[Manchester Evening News]] |first1=Chris |last1=Slater |first2=Damon |last2=Wilkinson |first3=Paul |last3=Britton |first4=Todd| last4=Fitzgerald |first5=Sam |last5=Yarwood |date=1 August 2019 |accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=RAF>{{cite news |date= 2 August 2019 |title=Whaley Bridge dam collapse: RAF Chinook brought in |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-49201467 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=2 August 2019 }}</ref> The [[Environment Agency]] issued a 'danger to life' warning due to the possibility of the dam collapsing. High-volume pumps were deployed to take water from the reservoir to prevent it from overflowing and reduce pressure on the dam. An [[RAF]] [[Boeing Chinook (UK variants)|Chinook helicopter]] dropped 400 tonnes of [[Construction aggregate|aggregate]] into the damaged area<ref name=\"RAF\" /> and specialist contractors added concrete grouting between the bags of ballast to bind them together to support the spillway.<ref>{{cite news |title=Whaley Bridge dam: Threat of storms as repairs continue |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-49217887 |date=3 August 2019 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August the Canal & River Trust confirmed that the target reduction in water level of {{convert|8|m}} had been achieved and that the reservoir was down to 25% of its capacity, which would allow a full inspection of the damage to the structure to be made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-derbyshire-49247226|title=Water level target reached at Whaley Bridge dam|date=6 August 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Fifty residents were allowed to return to their homes on the evening of 6 August and, following a final safety inspection on 7 August, [[Derbyshire Constabulary]] declared that it was safe for the rest of the residents to return also.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rucki |first1=Alexandra |title=Thousands of people evacuated in Whaley Bridge can FINALLY return to their homes after Toddbrook Reservoir deemed safe |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/people-allowed-home-whaley-bridge-16715362 |accessdate=7 August 2019 |work=Manchester Evening News |agency=M.E.N Media |date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported on 7 August that a representative of the Canal & River Trust had told residents, at a meeting on 6 August, that the whole of the reservoir, including the dam, would be completely reconstructed, in a project that would span a number of years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scheerhout, Britton |first1=John |last2=Britton |first2=Paul |title=Toddbrook Reservoir in Whaley Bridge to be completely rebuilt after dam emergency, evacuated residents told at public meeting |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/reservoir-rebuilt-after-dam-emergency-16711011 |accessdate=7 August 2019 |work=Manchester Evening News |publisher=M.E.N. Media |date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |title=\"The Peak Forest Canal and railway: an engineering and business history\" |first=Grahame |last=Boyes |date=2012 |isbn=9780901461599 |publisher=The Railway and Canal Historical Society |location=Oxford|ref=harv}}{{refend}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n[[Category:Reservoirs of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Canal reservoirs in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English reservoir}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox lake\n| name = Toddbrook Reservoir\n| image = Toddbrook Reservoir (northern end) - geograph.org.uk - 77856.jpg\n| caption = Looking southeast towards the dam, from the northern corner\n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[High Peak (England)|High Peak]], [[Derbyshire]]\n| coords = {{coord|53|19|30|N|1|59|37|W|type:waterbody_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| type = [[reservoir]]\n| inflow = \n| outflow = \n| catchment = {{convert|1700|ha|abbr=on}}\n| basin_countries = United Kingdom\n| length = \n| width = \n| area = {{convert|14.6|ha|abbr=on}}\n| depth = \n| max-depth = {{convert|23.8|m|abbr=on}} <ref name=crtupdate>[https://canalrivertrust.org.uk/news-and-views/news/toddbrook-reservoir-update Toddbrook Reservoir update], Canal & River Trust, accessed 2. August 2019</ref> \n| volume ={{convert|1288000|m3|impgal}}<ref name=tedd140 />\n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = {{convert|185.69|m|abbr=on}} <ref name=crtupdate>[https://canalrivertrust.org.uk/news-and-views/news/toddbrook-reservoir-update Toddbrook Reservoir update], Canal & River Trust, accessed 2. August 2019</ref> \n| frozen = \n| islands = None\n| cities = \n}}\n'''Toddbrook Reservoir''', a feeder for the [[Peak Forest Canal]], opened in 1838.<ref name=Labrum9>{{cite book |editor1-last=Labrum |editor1-first=E.A |date=1994 |title=Civil Engineering Heritage: Eastern and central England |publisher=Institution of Civil Engineers |pages=9\u201310 |isbn=072771970X}}</ref> It is sited above the town of [[Whaley Bridge]] in the [[Derbyshire]] [[High Peak (upland)|High Peak]] area of England. The reservoir is a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSI) providing habitats for [[Grey Heron|herons]], [[duck]]s and other animals and fish, while rare [[moss]]es and [[Marchantiophyta|liverwort]]s grow on its shores, particularly short-lived species that grow on seasonally exposed mud.<ref name=\"sssi\">{{cite web | url = http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/citation/citation_photo/1001257.pdf | title = Toddbrook Reservoir [SSSI citation] | publisher = Natural England | date =1981 | accessdate = 12 July 2012}}</ref> The reservoir is used for [[sailing]]<ref name=tbk>[http://www.toddbrooksailingclub.org.uk/ Toddbrook Sailing Club] accessed 16 May 2008</ref> and [[angling]]. The reservoir is owned by the [[Canal & River Trust]] and, like the nearby [[Combs, Derbyshire|Combs]] reservoir, is a feeder reservoir for the Peak Forest Canal. The feeder runs through Whaley Bridge, and with the Combs feed enters the canal system in a pool close to the transhipment shed at the Whaley Bridge canal basin.\n\nThe reservoir is fed from the Todd Brook, a stream which has a catchment area of around {{convert|1700|ha}} including the moorland on [[Shining Tor]] and farmland around [[Kettleshulme]] village. Water enters the reservoir on its north bank via a small waterfall. The first several inches of water do not flow into the reservoir but flow down the reservoir's run-off into the [[River Goyt]]. The reservoir often receives little or no inflow during periods when rainfall does not allow the level to exceed the barrier, and this often affects  the reservoir's water level, particularly in the summer months.\n\nThe reservoir's dam is built from earth with a [[puddle clay]] core. The embankment is straight in plan and approximately 310m long. The average crest level is 187.3mAOD. In August 2019, concrete panels on its spillway were dislodged after heavy rain, triggering the evacuation of parts of Whaley Bridge and the surrounding area due to the possibility of the dam collapsing.\n\n==Dam works==\n{{More citations needed section|date=August 2019}}\n\nGrowth of traffic on the Peak Forest Canal meant that that water supply from Combs Reservoir proved insufficient, despite the trustees of the [[Macclesfield Canal]] allowing the transfer of water from the summit level of their [[Sutton Lane Ends|Sutton]] Reservoir. The General Assembly of the Peak Forest Canal company approved the adoption of the site of Toddbrook Reservoir in June 1834 on the advice of Samuel Taylor, a land surveyor (a further reservoir on the Hockham Brook above [[Chapel Milton]] was never completed). Negotiations for the sale of the land began in June 1834 but were not concluded until 1839. Work did not go smoothly: from the start, concerns were expressed over the geology of the site and the known existence of coal workings below the valley, and various sites were considered for the dam. John Wood drew up the first plans, though these were amended on the advice of various consultant engineers, including Robert Matthews (engineer of the [[Rochdale Canal]]) and Nicholas Brown, who had experience of building reservoirs.<ref>{{harvnb|Boyes|2012|p=75\u201376}}</ref> Contracts for the reservoir construction were awarded to William Collinge and Richard and William Walker in August 1836. Geological problems continued to dog the project, and the site of the dam was altered on the advice of [[William Mackenzie (contractor)|William Mackenzie]] in 1837. As a stopgap, waters from the Todd Brook were diverted around the reservoir site and into the canal, and this solution proved so effective that consideration was even given to abandoning the reservoir project. Ultimately, however, construction continued using new plans supervised by Mackenzie and the reservoir's completion was reported in the canal committee's annual report of June 1841. The {{convert|24|m|adj=on}} dam was at the time the tallest ever built for a canal reservoir.<ref>{{harvnb|Boyes|2012|p=77\u201378}}</ref>\n\nConsultant engineer Nicholas Brown's report of 1836 had specified a puddle trench varying from 12 feet at the brook end to 6 feet in width,<ref>{{harvnb|Boyes|2012|p=190}}</ref> but investigations in the late 20th century led to doubt as to whether it was constructed as laid out on original drawings or with more porous core material. The peak of the dam wall is supported either side by embankments with a slope of 1:2.<ref name=tedd140 /> Underneath the dam, the geology includes glacial sands and gravel, [[Till|glacial till]] overlying mudstones, sandstones, shales and coal measures.<ref name=civeng>{{cite web|url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/engineers-battle-night-save-derbyshire-dam-02-08-2019 |title=Engineers battle through night to prevent catastrophic dam failure |last=Horgan |first=Rob  |publisher= New Civil Engineer |access-date= 4 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was known that local coal mining had been a threat to the dam's integrity for many years, with complaints dating from 1880 that water was leaking into coal mines.<ref name=Labrum9 /> After the Whaley Bridge Colliery proposed to work coal below the site, the [[Manchester, Sheffield and Lincolnshire Railway]], who owned the canal at the time, purchased coal measures beneath the reservoir site for \u00a38,550 after evidence of subsidence came to light.<ref>{{harvnb|Boyes|2012|p=79}}</ref>\n\nLeakage was observed from the foot of the dam and investigated in 1931. The leak coincided with a hollow in the upstream slope of the dam which was filled in. In November 1975, low water revealed that another hollow had formed in the same area which led to regular monitoring of the dam. In 1977 it was noted that there had been {{convert|12|cm}} of subsidence since 1975. The reservoir was drained and a four metre wide hole was discovered, partly filled by silt and a tree which appeared to have been drawn in by the flow of water into the hole. Between 1978 and 1980, further investigations included drilling  bore holes into the affected areas. In 1981 a {{convert|1.2|m|adj=on}} diameter masonry culvert was discovered which had probably been built into the dam wall at the time of its construction to divert ground water, which can undermine a dam from below. Leaks had developed around it, as had happened to other dams where pipework or drainage had been built through a clay dam wall creating a weak spot.<ref name=tedd140 /> Repairs were made and a layer of waterproof clay was laid over the weak spot on the upstream face of the dam. The clay core was reinforced by injecting grout along a 60 metre length and the reservoir was refilled in December 1983.<ref name=tedd140 /><!--From Boyes: In 1976\u201377 both Toddbrook and Combs Reservoirs were drained to allow the dams to be checked. A depression {{convert|8|m}} in diameter was discovered on the inner face of the Toddbrook embankment, considered to have resulted from a weakness where the brook passed under the dam, the fault of the original contractor. Grouting was applied and a new wave wall added to the embankment.<ref>{{harvnb|Boyes|2012|p=80}}</ref>-->\n\n[[File:Toddbrook_Reservoir,_the_dam_-_geograph.org.uk_-_77850.jpg|thumb|left |The 1969 dam wall spillway in 2005. Note channel for original spillway in foreground.]]\nIn December 1964, high rainfall resulted in damage to the dam\u2019s [[spillway]]. The water level rose to one metre above the overflow spillway at the side of the reservoir and remained high for 24 hours but did not rise above the main dam wall and the spillway prevented the water flowing over it and washing the earth embankment away. However, the high volume of water damaged the lower part of the spillway channel and escaping water started to erode the right bank at the base of the dam. The damage was repaired in 1965 but flood studies judged the spillway to be inadequate. It was noted by the [[Environment Agency]] that damage had occurred to nine other dams of similar design where the spillway delivered water to the foot of the dam.<ref name=tedd140 />\n\nIn 1969 an additional concrete spillway was built on the downstream face of the dam along a length of {{convert|75|m}}. This new [[weir]] was formed by adding concrete capping to the earth embankment to protect it from flowing water and was set above the existing spillway so that excess water would initially overflow along the original path.<ref name=tedd140>{{cite web |url=http://evidence.environment-agency.gov.uk/FCERM/Libraries/FCERM_Project_Documents/Lessons_from_Historical_Dam_Incidents.sflb.ashx |title=Delivering Benefits Through Evidence Lessons from Historical Dam Incidents |last1=Charles |first1=J Andrew|last2=Tedd |first2=Paul|last3=Warren |first3=Alan |publisher=Environment Agency |access-date=1 August 2019 |page=140}}</ref><ref name=Labrum9 />  In the 1980s, [[British Waterways]] carried out significant repair works to deal with leaks involving the mine shafts around the dam and a culvert was constructed under the current beach/launching area of the reservoir. A stone marker on the main beach showed its location for many years, but was relocated to the footpath opposite Toddbrook Lodge during access work for the 2009 draining.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nThe reservoir was partially drained again in 2009 for inspection<ref>{{Cite|url=http://www.whaleybridge.net/forum/posts/t189-Toddbrook-Reservoir/page2|title = Toddbrook Reservoir forum posts at whalyebridge.net|date=14 September 2009}}</ref> before being fully drained for repairs in 2010. The \u00a3500,000 project entailed fish stocks being moved to other locations before repairing pitching to the wall of the dam. Other work  involved repairs to the 100-year-old pipework used to feed water stored in the reservoir at a controlled rate into the Peak Forest Canal and included; clearing silt and debris from pipework inlets, removing old valves and connections to pipework, cleaning, inspecting and repairing old pipework, re-lining old pipework with a resin \u201csock\u201d liner cured under pressure using ultraviolet lights, replacement of valves, testing of the new system and replacement of screens to intakes.<ref>{{Cite|url=http://www.whaleybridge.com/2011/01/toddbrook-reservoir-refilling-to-start-in-new-year/|title = Toddbrook Reservoir refilling to start in new year|date=5 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==2019 incident==\n[[File:Playground under construction (geograph 3891775).jpg|thumb|right|A view looking down the spillway in 2014 before the concrete slabs to the left of the picture were damaged in 2019]]\nOn 1 August 2019, a major incident was declared and 1,500 residents were evacuated from parts of [[Whaley Bridge]], [[Furness Vale]] and [[New Mills]] after concrete slabs on the 1969 overflow spillway were partially dislodged by high volumes of water following several days of heavy rain.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news| url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-49189955 | title = Whaley Bridge dam collapse: Town evacuated over Toddbrook Reservoir fears| publisher = BBC News | date = 1 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/reservoir-sealed-police-people-told-16681771|title=Thousands of Whaley Bridge residents evacuated as 'danger to life' warning issued over fears dam could burst|work=[[Manchester Evening News]] |first1=Chris |last1=Slater |first2=Damon |last2=Wilkinson |first3=Paul |last3=Britton |first4=Todd| last4=Fitzgerald |first5=Sam |last5=Yarwood |date=1 August 2019 |accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=RAF>{{cite news |date= 2 August 2019 |title=Whaley Bridge dam collapse: RAF Chinook brought in |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-49201467 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=2 August 2019 }}</ref> The [[Environment Agency]] issued a 'danger to life' warning due to the possibility of the dam collapsing. High-volume pumps were deployed to take water from the reservoir to prevent it from overflowing and reduce pressure on the dam. An [[RAF]] [[Boeing Chinook (UK variants)|Chinook helicopter]] dropped 400 tonnes of [[Construction aggregate|aggregate]] into the damaged area<ref name=\"RAF\" /> and specialist contractors added concrete grouting between the bags of ballast to bind them together to support the spillway.<ref>{{cite news |title=Whaley Bridge dam: Threat of storms as repairs continue |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-derbyshire-49217887 |date=3 August 2019 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August the Canal & River Trust confirmed that the target reduction in water level of {{convert|8|m}} had been achieved and that the reservoir was down to 25% of its capacity, which would allow a full inspection of the damage to the structure to be made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-derbyshire-49247226|title=Water level target reached at Whaley Bridge dam|date=6 August 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Fifty residents were allowed to return to their homes on the evening of 6 August and, following a final safety inspection on 7 August, [[Derbyshire Constabulary]] declared that it was safe for the rest of the residents to return also.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rucki |first1=Alexandra |title=Thousands of people evacuated in Whaley Bridge can FINALLY return to their homes after Toddbrook Reservoir deemed safe |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/people-allowed-home-whaley-bridge-16715362 |accessdate=7 August 2019 |work=Manchester Evening News |agency=M.E.N Media |date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported on 7 August that a representative of the Canal & River Trust had told residents, at a meeting on 6 August, that the whole of the reservoir, including the dam, would be completely reconstructed, in a project that would span a number of years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scheerhout, Britton |first1=John |last2=Britton |first2=Paul |title=Toddbrook Reservoir in Whaley Bridge to be completely rebuilt after dam emergency, evacuated residents told at public meeting |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/reservoir-rebuilt-after-dam-emergency-16711011 |accessdate=7 August 2019 |work=Manchester Evening News |publisher=M.E.N. Media |date=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |title=\"The Peak Forest Canal and railway: an engineering and business history\" |first=Grahame |last=Boyes |date=2012 |isbn=9780901461599 |publisher=The Railway and Canal Historical Society |location=Oxford|ref=harv}}{{refend}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n[[Category:Reservoirs of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Canal reservoirs in England]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHigh Peak(link changed toHigh Peak (upland)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toddbrook_Reservoir"}
{"title_page": "Bernard Freyberg, 1st Baron Freyberg", "text_new": "{{short description|Military leader, viceroy, Victoria Cross}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox Governor General\n| honorific-prefix = [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]] [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name          = The Lord Freyberg\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|VC|GCMG|KCB|KBE|DSO3}}\n| image         = General Freyberg.jpg\n| caption       = Bernard Freyberg in 1952\n| order         = 7th\n| office        = Governor-General of New Zealand\n| term_start    = 17 June 1946\n| term_end      = 15 August 1952\n| monarch       = [[George VI]]<br />[[Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor   = [[Cyril Newall, 1st Baron Newall|Sir Cyril Newall]]\n| successor     = [[Willoughby Norrie, 1st Baron Norrie|Sir Willoughby Norrie]]\n| office1        = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start1    = 19 October 1951\n| term_end1      = 4 July 1963\n| predecessor1   = ''[[Baron Freyberg|Peerage created]]''\n| successor1     = [[Paul Freyberg, 2nd Baron Freyberg|The 2nd Lord Freyberg]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1889|3|21}}\n| birth_place   = [[Richmond, London]], England\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1963|7|4|1889|3|21}}\n| death_place   = [[Windsor, Berkshire]], England\n| party         = [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]]\n|nickname       = \"Tiny\"<ref>Mead, p. 146.</ref>\n|allegiance     = United Kingdom (1914\u201337)<br />New Zealand (1939\u201345)\n|branch         = [[Royal Naval Reserve|Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve]]<br />[[British Army]]<br />[[New Zealand Army|New Zealand Military Forces]]\n|serviceyears   = 1914\u20131937<br />1939\u20131945\n|rank           = [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]]\n|unit= [[Queen's Royal Regiment (West Surrey)]]<br />[[Grenadier Guards]]<br />[[Manchester Regiment]]\n|commands= [[X Corps (United Kingdom)|X Corps]] (1943)<br />[[2nd New Zealand Division]] (1939\u201345)<br />2nd [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]] (1939\u201345)<br />1st Battalion, [[Manchester Regiment]] (1929\u201331)<br />[[88th Brigade (United Kingdom)|88th Brigade]] (1917\u201318)<br />[[173rd (3/1st London) Brigade]] (1917)\n|battles= [[First World War]]<br />[[Second World War]] \n* [[Battle of Greece]]\n** [[Battle of Crete]]\n* [[North African campaign]]\n**[[Western Desert campaign]]\n***[[Second Battle of El Alamein]]\n* [[Italian campaign]]\n** Second [[Battle of Monte Cassino]]\n** [[Trieste operation]]\n\n|mawards= [[Victoria Cross]]<br />[[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George]]<br />[[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]<br />[[Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]<br />[[Distinguished Service Order]] & [[Medal bar|Three Bars]]<br />[[Mentioned in Despatches]] (6)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=29664 |date=11 September 1916 |pages=6941\u20136952 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35821 |date=11 December 1942 |page=5446|supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=36065 |date=22 June 1943 |page=2866|supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=37368 |date=27 November 1945 |page=5835|supp=y}}</ref><br />[[Venerable Order of Saint John|Knight of the Venerable Order of St. John]]<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{London Gazette |issue=37417 |date=1 January 1946 |page=203}}</ref><br />[[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de Guerre]] (France)<br />[[Legion of Merit]] (United States)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=37204 |date=31 July 1945 |page=3962|supp=y }}</ref><br />[[Order of George I|Grand Commander with Swords of the Order of George I]] (Greece)<ref name=dg>{{cite web | last = McGibbon | first = Ian | title = Freyberg, VC | work = diggerhistory | url = http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-vc/freyberg-vc.htm | accessdate = 26 November 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080109171155/http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-vc/freyberg-vc.htm | archivedate = 9 January 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><br />[[Cross of Valour (Greece)|Cross of Valour]] (Greece)<ref name=dg /><br />[[Greek War Cross|War Cross]] (Greece)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35519 |date=7 April 1942 |page=1595|supp=y}}</ref>\n|relations=\n}}\n[[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant General]] '''Bernard Cyril Freyberg, 1st Baron Freyberg''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|VC|GCMG|KCB|KBE|DSO3}} (21 March 1889 \u2013 4 July 1963) was a British-born New Zealand soldier and [[Victoria Cross]] recipient, who served as the [[List of Governors-General of New Zealand|7th Governor-General of New Zealand]] from 1946 to 1952.\n\nFreyberg served as an officer in the British Army during the [[First World War]]. He took part in the beach landings during the [[Gallipoli Campaign]] and was the youngest general in the British Army during the First World War,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/publications/pointer/journals/2008/v34n3/personality_profile.html.print.html?Status=1 |title=Youngest General WW1 |publisher=Mindef.gov.sg |accessdate=1 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015162016/http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/publications/pointer/journals/2008/v34n3/personality_profile.html.print.html?Status=1 |archivedate=15 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> later serving on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]], where he was decorated with the Victoria Cross and three [[Distinguished Service Order]]s, making him one of the most highly decorated [[British Empire]] soldiers of the First World War. He liked to be in the thick of the action\u2014[[Winston Churchill]] called him \"the Salamander\" due to his ability to pass through fire unharmed.\n\nDuring the [[Second World War]], he commanded the [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]] in the [[Battle of Crete]], the [[North African Campaign]] and the [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italian Campaign]]. Freyberg was involved in the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] defeat in the [[Battle of Greece]], defeated again as the Allied commander in the Battle of Crete and performed successfully in the [[North African Campaign]] commanding the [[2nd New Zealand Division]], including during the [[Second Battle of El Alamein]].\n\nIn Italy, he was defeated again at the [[Battle of Monte Cassino|Second Battle of Cassino]] as a corps commander but later relieved [[Padua]] and [[Venice]] and was one of the first to enter [[Trieste]], where he confronted [[Josip Broz Tito]]'s [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisans]]. By the end of the Second World War, Freyberg had spent ten and a half years fighting the Germans.<ref name=\"Kay549\">Kay, [http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2-2Ita-c12-1.html#n549 p. 549] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090704003433/http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2-2Ita-c12-1.html#n549 |date=4 July 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Bernard Freyberg diving board.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Bernard Freyberg c. 1904. at Te Aro Baths now the site of<br> [[Freyberg Pool|The Freyberg Pool]]]]\nFreyberg, born in [[Richmond, London|Richmond]], [[Surrey]] to James Freyberg and his second wife, Julia (n\u00e9e Hamilton) was of partial [[Austria]]n-[[German people|German]] descent.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ewer|first=Peter|title=Forgotten Anzacs: The Campaign in Greece, 1941|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KgW4x1Pvh1AC|accessdate=19 October 2013|year=2010|publisher=Scribe Publications|isbn=9781921372759|page=30|quote=By distant ancestry, Freyberg was related to Austrian mercenaries who had fought for the Russian tsar against Napoleon at the [[Battle of Borodino]] in 1812.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231171856/http://books.google.com/books?id=KgW4x1Pvh1AC|archive-date=31 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>Stephen Levine: ''New Zealand As It Might Have Been 2'', Victoria University Press, 2011</ref> He moved to New Zealand with his parents at the age of two. He attended [[Wellington College (New Zealand)|Wellington College]] from 1897 to 1904. A strong swimmer, he won the New Zealand 100-yards championship in 1906 and 1910.<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=McLintock |editor-first=A.H. |editorlink=Alexander Hare McLintock |title=An Encyclopaedia of New Zealand |chapter=Swimming \u2013 national championships |url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/swimming-national-championships |accessdate=10 June 2017 |year=1966 |publisher=Ministry for Culture and Heritage |location=Wellington |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170813142714/https://teara.govt.nz/en/1966/swimming-national-championships |archive-date=13 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 1911, Freyberg gained formal registration as a dentist. He worked as an assistant dentist in [[Morrinsville]] and later practised in [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] and in [[Levin, New Zealand|Levin]]. While in Morrinsville he was asked to take up a [[Subaltern (rank)|subalternship]] in the local Territorial Army unit, but he did not succeed in gaining the King's commission.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nFreyberg left New Zealand in March 1914. A 1942 ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine article claims that Freyberg went to [[San Francisco]] and Mexico around this time, and was a captain under [[Pancho Villa]] during the [[Mexican Revolution]]. Upon hearing of the outbreak of [[First World War|war in Europe]] in August 1914, he travelled to Britain via [[Los Angeles]] (where he won a swimming competition) and [[New York City|New York]] (where he won a [[prizefight]]), to earn money to cross the United States and the Atlantic.<ref name=\"life1942081728\">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v04EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA2&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=true|title=Nazi Shell in Egypt Wounds One of British Empire's Most Fabulous Soldiers|work=Life|date=17 August 1942|accessdate=19 November 2011|page=28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622163810/http://books.google.com/books?id=v04EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA2&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=true|archive-date=22 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==First World War==\nImmediately on the outbreak of the First World War Freyberg went to England and volunteered for service. G. S. Richardson arranged for him to join the 7th \u201cHood\u201d Battalion of the Royal Naval Brigade, and he was on the Belgian front in September 1914. In late 1914 Freyberg met [[Winston Churchill]], then [[First Lord of the Admiralty]], and persuaded him to grant him a [[Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve]] commission in the 'Hood' Battalion, part of the [[2nd (Royal Naval) Brigade]] of \n[[File:Bernard_Cyril_Freyberg_WWII_Personnel_File_(1911_-_1944).jpg|alt=|left|thumb|Bernard Cyril Freyberg cover sheet of Personnel File (1911 - 1944)]]\nthe newly constituted [[63rd (Royal Naval) Division|Royal Naval Division]].{{r|life1942081728}}\n\nIn April 1915 Freyberg became involved in the [[Gallipoli Campaign|Dardanelles campaign]]. On the night of 24 April, during the initial landings by [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] troops following the failed naval attempt to force the straits by sea, Freyberg volunteered to swim ashore in the [[Gulf of Saros]]. Once ashore, he began lighting flares so as to distract the defending Turkish forces from the real landings taking place at [[Gallipoli]]. Despite coming under heavy Turkish fire, he returned safely from this outing and received the [[Distinguished Service Order]] (DSO).{{r|life1942081728}} He received serious wounds on several occasions and left the peninsula when his division evacuated in January 1916.<ref name=dg />\n\n===Victoria Cross===\nIn May 1916 Freyberg was transferred to the [[British Army]] as a [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]] in the [[Queen's Royal Regiment (West Surrey)|Queen's (Royal West Surrey) Regiment]].<ref name=\"Surreys\">{{London Gazette|issue=29626|date=16 June 1916|page=6042|supp=y}}</ref> However, he remained with the 'Hood' Battalion as a seconded temporary [[Major (United Kingdom)|major]]<ref name=\"Surreys\"/> and went with them to France. During the final stages of the [[Battle of the Somme]], when commanding a [[battalion]] as a temporary [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant colonel]], he so distinguished himself in the capture of Beaucourt village that he was awarded the [[Victoria Cross]].<ref name=\"VC\"/>{{r|life1942081728}} On 13 November 1916<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31259 |date=28 March 1919 |page=4157|supp=y}}</ref> at Beaucourt-sur-Ancre, France, after Freyberg's battalion had carried the initial attack through the enemy's front system of trenches, he rallied and re-formed his own much disorganised men and some others, and led them on a successful assault of the second objective, during which he suffered two wounds, but remained in command and held his ground throughout the day and the following night. When reinforced the next morning, he attacked and captured a strongly fortified village, taking 500 [[Prisoner of war|prisoners]]. Although wounded twice more, the second time severely, Freyberg refused to leave the line until he had issued final instructions. The citation for the award, published in the ''[[London Gazette]]'' in December 1916,<ref name=\"VC\"/> describes the events concluding with:\n\n[[File:1919 Bernard Freyberg.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Freyberg in 1919.]]\n{{quote|The personality, valour and utter contempt of danger on the part of this single Officer enabled the lodgment in the most advanced objective of the Corps to be permanently held, and on this point d'appui the line was eventually formed.<ref name=\"VC\">{{London Gazette |issue=29866 |date=15 December 1916 |page=12307|supp=y}}</ref>}}\n\nDuring his time on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] Freyberg continued to lead by example. His bold leadership had a cost: Freyberg received nine wounds during his service in France, and men who served with him later in his career said hardly a part of his body did not have scars.\n\nFreyberg gained promotion to the rank of temporary [[Brigadier (United Kingdom)|brigadier general]]{{r|life1942081728}} (although he still had the permanent rank of only captain)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=30106|date=1 June 1917|page=5400|supp=y}}</ref> and took command of the [[173rd (3/1st London) Brigade]], part of the [[58th (2/1st London) Division]], in April 1917, which reportedly made him the youngest [[general officer]] in the British Army. He was awarded a [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]] the same year. In September a shell exploding at his feet inflicted the worst of his many wounds. When he resumed duty in January 1918 he again commanded [[88th Brigade (United Kingdom)|88th Brigade]] in the [[29th Division (United Kingdom)|29th Division]],<ref name=\"Kay549\"/> performing with distinction during the German [[Spring Offensive]]s of March\u2013April 1918. He won a bar to his DSO in September that year.\n\nFreyberg ended the war by leading a cavalry squadron detached from [[7th Dragoon Guards]] to seize a bridge at Lessines, which was achieved one minute before the armistice came into effect, thus earning him a second bar to the DSO.<ref name=\"DSO1-3\">{{London Gazette |issue=31219 |date=7 March 1919|page=3224|supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31583|date=3 October 1919|page=12214|supp=y}}</ref> By the end of the war, Freyberg had added the French [[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de Guerre]] to his name, as well receiving five [[Mentioned in despatches|mentions in despatches]] after his escapade at Saros. With his VC and three DSOs, he ranked as among the most highly decorated British Empire soldiers of the First World War.\n\n==Interbellum==\nEarly in 1919 Freyberg was granted a [[Regular army|Regular Army]] commission in the [[Grenadier Guards]] and settled into peacetime soldiering, as well as attempts to swim the [[English Channel]].{{r|life1942081728}} He attended the [[Staff College, Camberley]] from 1920 to 1921.<ref name=\"Officers of the New Zealand Army\">{{cite web|url=http://www.unithistories.com/officers/NewZealandArmy_officers.html#Freyberg_BC|title=New Zealand Army officer histories|publisher=Unit Histories|accessdate=2017-07-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306204907/http://www.unithistories.com/officers/NewZealandArmy_officers.html#Freyberg_BC|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> From 1921 to 1925 he was a staff officer in the headquarters of the [[44th (Home Counties) Division]]. He suffered health problems arising from his many wounds, and as part of his convalescence he visited New Zealand in 1921.\n\nOn 14 June 1922 he married [[Barbara Freyberg, Baroness Freyberg|Barbara McLaren]] (a daughter of Sir Herbert and Dame [[Agnes Jekyll]], and the widow of the [[Francis McLaren|Honourable Francis McLaren]]) at [[St. Martha's Hill|St Martha on the Hill]] in [[Surrey]]. Barbara had two children from her previous marriage; she and Freyberg later had a son, [[Paul Freyberg, 2nd Baron Freyberg|Paul]] (1923\u20131993).\n\nIn the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|general election of 1922]] he stood unsuccessfully (coming second) as a [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] candidate for [[Cardiff South (UK Parliament constituency)|Cardiff South]]. \n\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1922 United Kingdom general election|General election 1922]]: Cardiff South<ref>British Parliamentary Election Results 1918\u20131949, FWS Craig</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Unionist Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Sir James Cory, 1st Baronet|Sir James Herbert Cory]]\n|votes  = 7,929\n|percentage  = 36.4\n|change  = -12.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[Bernard Freyberg, 1st Baron Freyberg|Bernard Cyril Freyberg]]\n|votes  = 6,996\n|percentage  = 32.2\n|change  = +7.0\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Labour Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[David Graham Pole]]\n|votes  = 6,831\n|percentage  = 31.9\n|change  = -5.6\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 933\n|percentage  = 4.2\n|change  = -17.9\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 21,756\n|percentage  = 74.9\n|change  = +17.1\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n|winner     = Unionist Party (UK)\n|swing      = -9.5\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nHe represented [[New Zealand Olympic Committee|New Zealand]] on the [[International Olympic Committee]] in 1928\u201330. Promoted to the permanent rank of major in 1927 (having been a substantive captain since 1916),<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33281|date=3 June 1927|page=3629}}</ref> he held a [[Staff (military)|GSO2]] staff appointment at Headquarters, Eastern Command until February 1929 when he was transferred to the [[Manchester Regiment]]<ref name=\"Officers of the New Zealand Army\" /> and promoted to lieutenant colonel and appointed to command the 1st Battalion, Manchester Regiment.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33463|date=4 February 1929|page=867}}</ref>\n\nIn 1931 he was promoted colonel (with seniority backdated to 1922)<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33699|date=17 March 1931|page=1802}}</ref> and was appointed Assistant Quartermaster General of Southern Command. In 1933 he wrote ''A Study of Unit Administration'', which became a staff college textbook on quarter-masters' logistics;<ref>{{cite web|title=FREYBERG, Bernard Cyril|url=http://patria.homestead.com/patriaFREYBERG-BC.html|website=The Pro Patria Project|accessdate=21 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506145947/http://patria.homestead.com/patriaFREYBERG-BC.html|archive-date=6 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> it went into a second edition in 1940.\n\nIn September 1933 he moved to a GSO1 posting at the War Office<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33978|date=15 September 1933|page=6014}}</ref> before being promoted major-general in July 1934.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34070|date=17 July 1934|page=4591}}</ref> With this promotion, at age 45, he seemed headed for the highest echelons of the army. However, medical examinations prior to a posting in India revealed a heart problem. Despite strenuous efforts to surmount this, Freyberg, who was made a [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]] in 1936,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34238 |date=31 December 1935 |page=767}}</ref> was obliged to retire on 16 October 1937.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34444|date=15 October 1937|page=6372}}</ref>\n\n==Second World War==\n[[File:Lieutenant General Freyberg gazes over the parapet.jpg|right|thumb|Freyberg (right) during the Battle of Crete, May 1941.]]\n\nThe British Army had classified Freyberg as unfit for active service in 1937. After the outbreak of war in September 1939, he returned to its active list in December as a specially employed [[Major-general (United Kingdom)|major-general]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34758 |date=22 December 1939|page=8531|supp=y}}</ref> On being approached by the [[Government of New Zealand|New Zealand government]], Freyberg offered his services and was appointed commander of the 2nd [[New Zealand Expeditionary Force]] and of the [[2nd New Zealand Division]].{{r|life1942081728}}\n\nIn the chaos of the retreat from the [[Battle of Greece]] in 1941, Churchill gave Freyberg command of the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] forces during the [[Battle of Crete]]. Although instructed to prevent an assault from the air, he remained obsessed with the (highly improbable) possibility of a naval landing and based his tactics on it, neglecting adequately to defend the airfield at Maleme, ignoring [[Ultra|ULTRA]] intelligence messages, which showed that the assault was coming by air.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/war/the-battle-for-crete/the-controversies|title=The controversies \u2013 The Battle for Crete|work=New Zealand History online|publisher=Ministry for Culture and Heritage|accessdate=9 July 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216071441/http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/war/the-battle-for-crete/the-controversies|archive-date=16 December 2008|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>James Holland, 2015. The War in the West vol.1, Bantam Press - Transworld Publishers, London</ref><ref>[[Antony Beevor]], ''The Second World War'', Weidenfeld & Nicolson, 2014 (paperback edition).{{ISBN|978-1-7802-2564-7}}. See pp. 201\u2013217</ref>\n[[File:Bernard_Cyril_Freyberg_WWII_Personnel_File_(1939_-_1945).jpg|thumb|Bernard Cyril Freyberg, History Sheet of WWII Personnel File ]]\nPromoted to [[Lieutenant-general (United Kingdom)|lieutenant-general]] and knighted as a [[Order of the British Empire|Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]], Freyberg continued to command the 2nd New Zealand Division through the [[North African Campaign|North African]] and [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italian Campaigns]] of the [[Eighth Army (United Kingdom)|Eighth Army]]. He had an excellent reputation as a divisional-level tactician. [[Winston Churchill]], the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|British Prime Minister]], described Freyberg as his \"salamander\" due to his love of fire and wanting to be always in the middle of the action.<ref>Stevens (1962), [http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2Bard-c6-19.html#n121 p. 121.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023043604/http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-WH2Bard-c6-19.html#n121 |date=23 October 2008 }} Ancient superstition had it that the lizard-like salamander could live in fire.</ref> An exploding German shell wounded Freyberg at the [[Battle of Mersa Matruh]] in June 1942 but he soon returned to the battlefield.{{r|life1942081728}} Freyberg disagreed strongly with his superior, [[General (United Kingdom)|General]] [[Claude Auchinleck]], the Eighth Army commander and insisted that as a commander of a national contingent he had the right to refuse orders if those orders ran counter to the New Zealand national interest. Freyberg enjoyed a good relationship with General [[Bernard Montgomery]], the Eighth Army commander from August 1942, who thought highly of the experienced New Zealand commander.\n\nIn the climactic [[Second Battle of El Alamein]] (October\u2013November 1942) the 2nd New Zealand Division played a vital part in the breakthrough by the Eighth Army; for his leadership, Freyberg was immediately promoted to [[Order of the Bath|Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35794 |date=20 November 1942 |page=3|supp=y}}</ref> During the pursuit of the [[Axis powers|Axis forces]] to Tunisia, where they surrendered in May 1943, he led the New Zealanders on a series of well-executed left hooks to outflank Axis defence lines. In April and May 1943 Freyberg briefly commanded [[X Corps (United Kingdom)|X Corps]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=5117&Tab=App&Titl=X |title=Orders of Battle |publisher=Orders of Battle |date= |accessdate=1 November 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bernard Freyberg.jpg|thumb|right|Freyberg at [[Cassino (FR)|Cassino]], Italy, 3 January 1944.]]\n\nFreyberg was injured in an aircraft accident in September 1944. After six weeks in hospital he returned to command the New Zealand Division in its final operations, the [[Spring 1945 offensive in Italy]], which involved a series of river crossings and an advance of {{convert|250|mi|km|abbr=on}} in three weeks. By the time of the German surrender, the New Zealanders had reached Trieste, having liberated both [[Padua]] and [[Venice]], where there was a brief standoff with Yugoslav partisans. This success earned him a third bar to his DSO in July 1945 and he was made a Commander of the United States [[Legion of Merit]].<ref name=\"DSO4\">{{London Gazette |issue=37161 |date=3 July 1945 |page=3490|supp=y}}</ref>\n\nFreyberg had excelled in planning set-piece attacks, such as at [[Operation Supercharge (1942)|Operation Supercharge]] at Alamein, [[Battle of the Mareth Line|Operation Supercharge II]] at [[Tunisia Campaign|Tebaga Gap]], and in the storming of the [[Spring 1945 offensive in Italy|Senio line]] in 1945. The two occasions that Freyberg commanded at Corps level\u2014at Crete and [[Monte Cassino]]\u2014were less successful. Throughout the war he showed a disdain for danger. He showed notable concern for the welfare of his soldiers, taking a common-sense attitude to discipline and ensuring the establishment of social facilities for his men. He had become a very popular commander with the New Zealand soldiers by the time he left his command in 1945.\n[[File:Major General Sir Bernard Cyril Freyberg VC (16160704063).jpg|thumb|right|A portrait of Freyberg, executed by [[Peter McIntyre (artist)|Peter McIntyre]], an official war artist of the 2NZEF]]\nFreyberg is closely associated with the controversial decision to bomb the ancient monastery at Monte Cassino in February 1944. Freyberg, commanding the troops which fought what later became known as the [[Battle of Monte Cassino|Second and Third Battles of Monte Cassino]], became convinced the abbey, founded in 529 AD, was being used as a military stronghold. The analysis of one of Freyberg's divisional commanders, Major-General [[Francis Tuker]] of the [[4th Infantry Division (India)|4th Indian Infantry Division]], concluded in a memo to Freyberg that, regardless of whether the monastery was occupied by the Germans, it should be demolished to prevent its occupation. He pointed out that with {{convert|150|ft|m|abbr=on}}-high walls made of masonry at least {{convert|10|ft|m|abbr=on}} thick, it was impossible for engineers to break in and that bombing with \"blockbuster\" bombs would be the only solution since {{convert|1000|lb|kg|abbr=on}} bombs would be \"next to useless\".<ref>Majdalany, pp. 114\u2013115.</ref> [[General (United Kingdom)|General]] Sir [[Harold Alexander, 1st Earl Alexander of Tunis|Harold Alexander]], commander of the [[15th Army Group]] (later the [[Allied Armies in Italy]]), agreed to the bombing (which did not employ blockbuster bombs). After the monastery's destruction, the ruins were occupied by [[Wehrmacht|German forces]], which held the position until 18 May. Following the war, the abbot of the monastery and other monks said that German troops had not occupied the inside of the abbey and it was not being used for military purposes.<ref>Hapgood, D, & Richardson, D, 1987. Monte Cassino, Gordon and Weed, Inc, New York.</ref>\n\n==Post-war==\n[[File:Bernard Freyberg Lett.jpg|thumb|left|Governor General Sir Bernard Freyberg in 1950]]\n[[File:Bernard freyberg marker.jpg|thumb|right|Freyberg's grave in the churchyard of St Martha on the Hill, near Guildford, Surrey]]\nFreyberg relinquished command of the New Zealand division, on 22 November 1945 having accepted an invitation to become [[Governor-General of New Zealand]] \u2013 the first with a New Zealand upbringing. He left London for his new post on 3 May 1946, after being made a [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=37453|date=1 February 1946|page=767}}</ref> He retired from the army on 10 September 1946.\n\nFreyberg served as Governor-General of New Zealand from 1946 until 1952. In this post he played a very active role, visiting all parts of New Zealand and its dependencies.\n\nOn {{nowrap|1 January 1946}} Freyberg was appointed a [[Knight of Justice of The Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of Saint John of Jerusalem|Knight of the Order of Saint John]]; his wife, Barbara, was made a Dame of the order at the same time.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{London Gazette |issue=37417 |date=1 January 1946 |page=203}}</ref>\n\n[[King George VI]] raised Freyberg to the peerage as [[Baron Freyberg]] of Wellington in New Zealand and of Munstead in the County of Surrey in 1951.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39362 |date=19 October 1951|page=5437}}</ref>\n\nAfter his term as New Zealand Governor-General had finished, Freyberg returned to England, where he sat frequently in the [[House of Lords]]. On 1 March 1953 he became the Deputy Constable and Lieutenant-Governor of [[Windsor Castle]];<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39791 |date=3 March 1953 |page=1243}}</ref> he took up residence in the Norman Gateway the following year.\n\nFreyberg died at Windsor on 4 July 1963 following the rupture of one of his war wounds, and was buried in the churchyard of St Martha on the Hill near [[Guildford]], Surrey. His wife is buried at his side, and their son, who had been awarded the [[Military Cross]], at the end of their graves.\n\n==Tributes==\n[[File:Mount Freyberg NZ.jpg|thumb|Mount Freyberg 1817m]]\n[[File:Lieutenant Colonel Bernard Freyberg commemorative paving stone outside Richmond Station.jpg|thumb|Monument to Bernard Freyberg outside Richmond Station, London]]\nAn athlete as well as a soldier he is memorialised in the name of the Ministry of Defence's headquarters, a stadium in Auckland and Wellington's swimming pool on the site of his early victories. A number of streets are named after him including  [[Freyberg Place]] in front of the [[Metropolis (Auckland building)|Metropolis tower]] in central Auckland where there is a statue of him.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.noted.co.nz/life/urbanism/aucklands-freyberg-place-revamp-is-almost-a-total-triumph/ |title=''Noted'' Revamp 20 September 2017 |access-date=24 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924110027/https://www.noted.co.nz/life/urbanism/aucklands-freyberg-place-revamp-is-almost-a-total-triumph/ |archive-date=24 September 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAuckland's [[Freyberg Place]] (also known as Freyberg Square) was opened in 1946; Wellington's [[Freyberg Pool]] in [[Oriental Bay]] opened in 1963; and Auckland's [[Kiwitea Street|Freyberg Field]] opened in 1965. The 15-story Freyberg Building in Aitken Street, [[Thorndon, New Zealand|Thorndon, Wellington]] was built in 1979. The adjacent Freyberg House built in about 2007 was demolished in 2018 after being damaged by the 2016 Kaikoura earthquake. [[Freyberg High School]] in [[Palmerston North]] opened in 1955.\n\nThe Sir Bernard Freyberg Cup is awarded to the winner in [[single scull]]s at the New Zealand Rowing Championship.<ref>{{cite news |author=Stu Piddington |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/other-sports/4680114/Drysdale-offers-no-excuses |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131101174057/http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/other-sports/4680114/Drysdale-offers-no-excuses |url-status=dead |archive-date=1 November 2013 |title=Mahe Drysdale offers no excuses for loss |work=Stuff.co.nz |date=20 February 2011 |accessdate=1 November 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/sport/3351778/Haighs-back-where-she-belongs |title=Haigh's back where she belongs |work=Stuff.co.nz |accessdate=1 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102154045/http://www.stuff.co.nz/waikato-times/sport/3351778/Haighs-back-where-she-belongs |archive-date=2 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016 a blue plaque was unveiled at 8 Dynevor Road, Richmond, where he was born and a VC commemorative paving stone was unveiled to him outside Richmond Station by the Mayor of Richmond and the present Lord Freyberg.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://libraryblog.lbrut.org.uk/wordpress/2016/11/bernard-freyberg/|title=Follow the Drum: Bernard Freyberg VC|last=|first=|date=3 November 2016|website=Richmond upon Thames Library Services|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017214119/http://libraryblog.lbrut.org.uk/wordpress/2016/11/bernard-freyberg/|archive-date=17 October 2019|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Styles==\n''Note: An asterisk (*) denotes a Bar to the DSO.''\n* 1889\u20131914: Bernard Cyril Freyberg\n* 1914-3 June 1915: [[Commander]] (temp.) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, [[RNVR]]\n* 3 June 1915 \u2013 May 1916: Commander (temp.) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], RNVR\n* May\u2013June 1916: [[Captain (land)|Captain]] Bernard Cyril Freyberg, DSO\n* June\u2013July 1916: Captain (Temp. Major) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, DSO\n* July-12 December 1916: Captain (Temp. [[Lieutenant-Colonel]]) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, DSO\n* 12 December 1916 \u2013 1917: Captain (Temp. Lieutenant-Colonel) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, DSO\n* 1917-1 February 1919: Captain (Temp. [[Brigadier-General]]) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, DSO\n* 1 February \u2013 7 March 1919: Captain (Brevet Lieutenant-Colonel; Temp. Brigadier) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, DSO*\n* 7 March\u2013June 1919: Captain (Brevet Lieutenant-Colonel) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, DSO*\n* June 1919 \u2013 1920: Captain (Brevet Lieutenant-Colonel) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, DSO**\n* 1920\u20131927: Captain (Brevet Lieutenant-Colonel) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]], DSO**\n* 1927\u20131929: Major (Brevet Lieutenant-Colonel) Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, CMG, DSO**\n* 1929\u20131931: Lieutenant-Colonel Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, CMG, DSO**\n* 1931\u20131934: [[Colonel]] Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, CMG, DSO**\n* 1934\u20131935: [[Major-General]] Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, CMG, DSO**\n* 1935\u20131941: Major-General Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, CB, CMG, DSO**\n* 1941\u20131942: [[Lieutenant-General]] Sir Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, [[KBE]], CB, CMG, DSO**\n* 1942\u20131945: Lieutenant-General Sir Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, [[Order of the Bath|KCB]], KBE, CMG, DSO**\n* 1945\u20131946: Lieutenant-General Sir Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, KCB, KBE, CMG, DSO***\n* 1946\u20131951: Lieutenant-General [[Excellency|His Excellency]] Sir Bernard Cyril Freyberg, VC, [[GCMG]], KCB, KBE, DSO***\n* 1951\u20131952: Lieutenant-General His Excellency [[The Right Honourable]] The [[Baron Freyberg|Lord Freyberg]], VC, GCMG, KCB, KBE, DSO***\n* 1952\u20131963: Lieutenant-General The Right Honourable The Lord Freyberg, VC, GCMG, KCB, KBE, DSO***\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = Bernard Freyberg Arms.svg\n|bannerimage =\n|badgeimage =\n|notes = The arms of Bernard Freyberg consist of:\n|adopted =\n|crest =\n|torse =\n|helm =\n|escutcheon = Or, on a chief sable, four mullets or.\n|supporters = Two salamanders enflamed proper.\n|compartment =\n|motto = New Zeal and Honour\n|orders =\n|other_elements = [[Mantling]]\n|banner =\n|badge =\n|symbolism =\n|previous_versions =\n}}\n\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book| first1=Laurie| last1=Barber| first2=John| last2=Tonkin-Covell| title=Freyberg : Churchill's Salamander| year=1989| location=Auckland| publisher=Century Hutchinson| isbn=978-1-86941-052-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ewer|first=Peter|title=Forgotten Anzacs: The Campaign in Greece, 1941|year=2008|publisher=Scribe Publications|location=Carlton North, Vic.|isbn=978-1-921215-29-2|oclc=457093199}}\n* {{cite book| first=Paul| last=Freyberg| title=Bernard Freyberg, VC : Soldier of Two Nations| year=1991| location=London| publisher=Hodder & Stoughton| isbn=978-0-340-39693-3| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/bernardfreybergv00frey}}\n* {{cite book| title=[[VCs of the First World War - The Somme]]| first=Gerald| last=Gliddon| year=1994| location=Phoenix Mill, UK| publisher=A. Sutton| isbn=978-0-7509-0567-1}}\n* {{cite book| title=[[The Register of the Victoria Cross]]| location=Cheltenham| publisher=This England| year=1997| origyear=1981| isbn=978-0-906324-27-1}}\n* {{cite book| title=[[Monuments to Courage|Monuments to courage : Victoria Cross headstones and memorials]]| first=David| last=Harvey| year=1999| location=Weybridge| publisher=K & K Patience| oclc=45224322}}\n* {{cite book|title=Italy Volume II : From Cassino to Trieste | last=Kay| first=Robin| publisher=Historical Publications Branch| year=1967| location=Wellington, N.Z.| series=The Official History of New Zeal