{"title_page": "Barmote court", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\nA '''barmote court''' (also written '''bergjisote''', '''barghmote''', '''bargemote''' and '''barmoot''') is a [[court]] held in the [[history of lead mining in Derbyshire|lead mining]] districts of [[Derbyshire, England]], for the purpose of determining the customs peculiar to the industry and also for the settlements of any disputes which may arise in connection with it.<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Barmote Court|volume=3|page=407}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe barmote courts were set up in 1288, their jurisdiction extending to both the [[crown lands]] of the [[Duchy of Lancaster]] and those under individual ownership, comprising seven clearly defined districts.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/> Great barmote courts with wider powers were in place by the fifteenth century, meeting at [[Easter]] and [[Michaelmas]]. The courts had twenty-four [[juror]]s, and were run by the barmaster and a steward. An appeal from the jurisdiction of the courts lies by way of [[certiorari]],<ref name=\"EB1911\"/> removing proceedings to the [[Queen's Bench|Queen's Bench Division]] of the [[High Court of Justice]].{{sfn|MacSwinney|1884|p=507}}<ref>1851 Act, s. 29; 1852 Act, s. 38</ref>\n\nNoting that \"the Mineral Laws and Customs of the King's Field ... [were] uncertain and undefined, and ... in many respects inapplicable to the present Mining Operations\",<ref>Recitals, 1851 and 1852 Acts</ref> the High Peak Mining Customs and Mineral Courts Act 1851<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Vict/14-15/94|title=High Peak Mining Customs and Mineral Courts Act 1851|website=Legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> and the Derbyshire Mining Customs and Mineral Courts Act 1852<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukla/Vict/16-17/163|title=Derbyshire Mining Customs and Mineral Courts Act 1852|website=Legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=19 August 2010}}</ref> were enacted, declaring that \"the Mineral Laws and Customs ... shall be such as are mentioned and comprised in this Act, and no other alleged Custom or Practice shall be valid\".<ref>1851 Act, s. 16; 1852 Act, s. 25</ref> The areas over which the courts could exercise their jurisdiction were:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=\"50%\"|1851 Act !!1852 Act\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n* in the [[Hundred (county division)|Hundred]] of [[High Peak, Derbyshire|High Peak]], the whole of the King's Field, comprising the [[Liberty (division)|liberties]] or districts of [[Castleton, Derbyshire|Castleton]], Bradwell, Hucklow, Winster, Moniash, Taddington, and Upper Haddon\n* elsewhere within the Hundred, those lands over which the [[Duchy of Lancaster]] is entitled to mineral duties\n|\n* the King's Field found in that part of the [[Soke (legal)|Soke]] and [[Wapentake]] of [[Wirksworth]] not within the Hundred of High Peak\n* the [[manor]]s or liberties of [[Ashford-in-the-Water|Ashford]], Hartington, Peak Forest, [[Tideswell]], Crich (excepting certain proprietors of [[limestone]]), [[Stoney Middleton]] and [[Eyam]] (excepting certain \"ancient freeholds\" therein), [[Youlgreave]], and [[Litton, Derbyshire|Litton]], provided that any such lands therein were subject to mineral customs on 30 June 1852\n|}\n\nWhile giving certainty to the courts' territorial limits,{{sfn|Tapping|1851|p=4}}{{sfn|Tapping|1854|pp=2{{en dash}}5}} this had the effect of ousting their [[criminal jurisdiction]],<ref>outlined in {{cite CommonLII|litigants=Arkwright v Cantrell|link=|reporter=ER|year=1837|num=1066|volume=112|firstpage=583|pinpoint=|parallelcite=7 Ad & E 565|date=|courtname=|juris=}}</ref> as well as matters relating to [[dower]] and [[tithe]]s.{{sfn|Tapping|1851|p=vii}}\n\nWhile the Acts provide for [[subpoena]]s and inspection of property, there are no provisions governing interrogatories or disclosure of documents.<ref>{{cite book |last1= Matthews|first1= Paul|last2= Malek|first2= Hodge M.|date= 2012|title= Disclosure|url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=fCLx6DIspBcC&lpg=PA674&ots=NWQ0fq1gUF&pg=PA674#v=onepage&f=false|location= London|publisher= Sweet & Maxwell|page= 674|isbn=978-0-41404779-2}}</ref>\n\n==Present day==\nThere are two barmote courts, one at [[Monyash]] covering the [[High Peak (upland)|High Peak]], and one at [[Wirksworth]] covering the [[Low Peak]]. In 1814, the Monyash court moved to Wirksworth, and since 1994, the two have met together, once a year, in April.  In line with tradition, bread, cheese, clay pipes and tobacco are provided at the meetings, and a representative of the monarch who is the Lord of the Field attends.\n\nThe courts' archival records are largely held at the Derbyshire Record Office.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F89073|title= Wirksworth barmote court|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher= [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]|access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\nWhile most current meetings have been ceremonial, the courts' jurisdiction still exists, and in 2013 the Low Peak Barmote Court was called upon to rule on lead mining rights in a cavern in [[Castleton, Derbyshire]].<ref>{{cite news|last= Hawley|first= Zena|date= April 20, 2013|title= First ruling in decades for ancient mining court|url= http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/ruling-decades-ancient-mining-court/story-18755029-detail/story.html|newspaper= [[Derby Telegraph]]|location= |access-date= |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151124031109/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/ruling-decades-ancient-mining-court/story-18755029-detail/story.html|archive-date= November 24, 2015|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Treatises===\n* {{cite book |last= Hardy|first= William|date= 1748|title= The Miner's Guide: Or, Compleat Miner |url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=Dm9bAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR1#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= Sheffield|publisher= Francis Lister|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last= Tapping|first= Thomas|date= 1851|title= A Treatise on the High Peak Mining Customs and Mineral Courts Act, 1851 |url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=QLoDAAAAQAAJ&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= London|publisher= Shaw & Sons|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last= Tapping|first= Thomas|date= 1854|title= A Treatise on the Derbyshire Mining Customs and Mineral Court Act, 1852 |url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=oe5iAAAAcAAJ&lpg=PR5-IA1&ots=5vbq6WoRf1&pg=PR2#v=onepage&f=false|location= London|publisher= Shaw & Sons|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last= MacSwinney|first= Robert Forster|date= 1884|title= The Law of Mines, Quarries and Minerals|chapter= Derbyshire Rights, Courts, and Customs{{em dash}}Remaining Local Rights and Customs|chapter-url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=7bYDAAAAQAAJ&lpg=PA501&ots=e8wmWUgeAW&pg=PA500#v=onepage&f=false|location= London|publisher= W. Maxwell & Son|pages= 500{{en dash}}522|ref=harv}}\n\n===Jurisprudence===\n* {{cite court |litigants= Wright v Pitt|vol= LR 3|reporter= Ch|opinion= 809|pinpoint= |court= |date= 1870|url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=VBlHAQAAMAAJ&lpg=PT50&ots=0ok5McmU61&pg=PT50#v=onepage&f=false|accessdate= |quote=}}\n* {{cite court |litigants= Wake v Hall|vol= 8|reporter= AC|opinion= 195|pinpoint= |court= |date= 1883|url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=4wNHAQAAIAAJ&lpg=PA585&ots=UugpRurgwQ&pg=PA585#v=onepage&f=false|accessdate= |quote=}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.derbyshireuk.net/dcustom1.html|title= Derbyshire & Peak District Customs: Barmote Court |website= derbyshireuk.net}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.duchyoflancaster.co.uk/properties-and-estates/historic-properties/barmote-court-wirksworth-derbyshire/|title= Barmote Court, Wirksworth \u2013 Derbyshire|publisher= [[Duchy of Lancaster]]}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://pdmhs.co.uk/peak-district-mining-laws-and-customs |title= Peak District Mining Laws and Customs |publisher=  [[PDMHS - Peak District Mines Historical Society]]}}\n\n[[Category:1288 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:History of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n[[Category:Courts of England and Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\nA '''barmote court''' (also written '''bergjisote''', '''barghmote''', '''bargemote''' and '''barmoot''') is a [[court]] held in the [[history of lead mining in Derbyshire|lead mining]] districts of [[Derbyshire, England]], for the purpose of determining the customs peculiar to the industry and also for the settlements of any disputes which may arise in connection with it.<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{EB1911|inline=y|wstitle=Barmote Court|volume=3|page=407}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe barmote courts were set up in 1288, their jurisdiction extending to both the [[crown lands]] of the [[Duchy of Lancaster]] and those under individual ownership, comprising seven clearly defined districts.<ref name=\"EB1911\"/> Great barmote courts with wider powers were in place by the fifteenth century, meeting at [[Easter]] and [[Michaelmas]]. The courts had twenty-four [[juror]]s, and were run by the barmaster and a steward. An appeal from the jurisdiction of the courts lies by way of [[certiorari]],<ref name=\"EB1911\"/> removing proceedings to the [[Queen's Bench|Queen's Bench Division]] of the [[High Court of Justice]].{{sfn|MacSwinney|1884|p=507}}<ref>1851 Act, s. 29; 1852 Act, s. 38</ref>\n\nNoting that \"the Mineral Laws and Customs of the King's Field ... [were] uncertain and undefined, and ... in many respects inapplicable to the present Mining Operations\",<ref>Recitals, 1851 and 1852 Acts</ref> the High Peak Mining Customs and Mineral Courts Act 1851<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/Vict/14-15/94|title=High Peak Mining Customs and Mineral Courts Act 1851|website=Legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> and the Derbyshire Mining Customs and Mineral Courts Act 1852<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukla/Vict/16-17/163|title=Derbyshire Mining Customs and Mineral Courts Act 1852|website=Legislation.gov.uk|accessdate=19 August 2010}}</ref> were enacted, declaring that \"the Mineral Laws and Customs ... shall be such as are mentioned and comprised in this Act, and no other alleged Custom or Practice shall be valid\".<ref>1851 Act, s. 16; 1852 Act, s. 25</ref> The areas over which the courts could exercise their jurisdiction were:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=\"50%\"|1851 Act !!1852 Act\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n* in the [[Hundred (county division)|Hundred]] of [[High Peak, Derbyshire|High Peak]], the whole of the King's Field, comprising the [[Liberty (division)|liberties]] or districts of [[Castleton, Derbyshire|Castleton]], Bradwell, Hucklow, Winster, Moniash, Taddington, and Upper Haddon\n* elsewhere within the Hundred, those lands over which the [[Duchy of Lancaster]] is entitled to mineral duties\n|\n* the King's Field found in that part of the [[Soke (legal)|Soke]] and [[Wapentake]] of [[Wirksworth]] not within the Hundred of High Peak\n* the [[manor]]s or liberties of [[Ashford-in-the-Water|Ashford]], Hartington, Peak Forest, [[Tideswell]], Crich (excepting certain proprietors of [[limestone]]), [[Stoney Middleton]] and [[Eyam]] (excepting certain \"ancient freeholds\" therein), [[Youlgreave]], and [[Litton, Derbyshire|Litton]], provided that any such lands therein were subject to mineral customs on 30 June 1852\n|}\n\nWhile giving certainty to the courts' territorial limits,{{sfn|Tapping|1851|p=4}}{{sfn|Tapping|1854|pp=2{{en dash}}5}} this had the effect of ousting their [[criminal jurisdiction]],<ref>outlined in {{cite CommonLII|litigants=Arkwright v Cantrell|link=|reporter=ER|year=1837|num=1066|volume=112|firstpage=583|pinpoint=|parallelcite=7 Ad & E 565|date=|courtname=|juris=}}</ref> as well as matters relating to [[dower]] and [[tithe]]s.{{sfn|Tapping|1851|p=vii}}\n\nWhile the Acts provide for [[subpoena]]s and inspection of property, there are no provisions governing interrogatories or disclosure of documents.<ref>{{cite book |last1= Matthews|first1= Paul|last2= Malek|first2= Hodge M.|date= 2012|title= Disclosure|url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=fCLx6DIspBcC&lpg=PA674&ots=NWQ0fq1gUF&pg=PA674#v=onepage&f=false|location= London|publisher= Sweet & Maxwell|page= 674|isbn=978-0-41404779-2}}</ref>\n\n==Present day==\nThere are two barmote courts, one at [[Monyash]] covering the [[High Peak (England)|High Peak]], and one at [[Wirksworth]] covering the [[Low Peak]]. In 1814, the Monyash court moved to Wirksworth, and since 1994, the two have met together, once a year, in April.  In line with tradition, bread, cheese, clay pipes and tobacco are provided at the meetings, and a representative of the monarch who is the Lord of the Field attends.\n\nThe courts' archival records are largely held at the Derbyshire Record Office.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F89073|title= Wirksworth barmote court|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk|publisher= [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]|access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\nWhile most current meetings have been ceremonial, the courts' jurisdiction still exists, and in 2013 the Low Peak Barmote Court was called upon to rule on lead mining rights in a cavern in [[Castleton, Derbyshire]].<ref>{{cite news|last= Hawley|first= Zena|date= April 20, 2013|title= First ruling in decades for ancient mining court|url= http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/ruling-decades-ancient-mining-court/story-18755029-detail/story.html|newspaper= [[Derby Telegraph]]|location= |access-date= |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151124031109/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/ruling-decades-ancient-mining-court/story-18755029-detail/story.html|archive-date= November 24, 2015|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Treatises===\n* {{cite book |last= Hardy|first= William|date= 1748|title= The Miner's Guide: Or, Compleat Miner |url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=Dm9bAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR1#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= Sheffield|publisher= Francis Lister|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last= Tapping|first= Thomas|date= 1851|title= A Treatise on the High Peak Mining Customs and Mineral Courts Act, 1851 |url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=QLoDAAAAQAAJ&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|location= London|publisher= Shaw & Sons|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last= Tapping|first= Thomas|date= 1854|title= A Treatise on the Derbyshire Mining Customs and Mineral Court Act, 1852 |url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=oe5iAAAAcAAJ&lpg=PR5-IA1&ots=5vbq6WoRf1&pg=PR2#v=onepage&f=false|location= London|publisher= Shaw & Sons|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last= MacSwinney|first= Robert Forster|date= 1884|title= The Law of Mines, Quarries and Minerals|chapter= Derbyshire Rights, Courts, and Customs{{em dash}}Remaining Local Rights and Customs|chapter-url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=7bYDAAAAQAAJ&lpg=PA501&ots=e8wmWUgeAW&pg=PA500#v=onepage&f=false|location= London|publisher= W. Maxwell & Son|pages= 500{{en dash}}522|ref=harv}}\n\n===Jurisprudence===\n* {{cite court |litigants= Wright v Pitt|vol= LR 3|reporter= Ch|opinion= 809|pinpoint= |court= |date= 1870|url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=VBlHAQAAMAAJ&lpg=PT50&ots=0ok5McmU61&pg=PT50#v=onepage&f=false|accessdate= |quote=}}\n* {{cite court |litigants= Wake v Hall|vol= 8|reporter= AC|opinion= 195|pinpoint= |court= |date= 1883|url= https://books.google.ca/books?id=4wNHAQAAIAAJ&lpg=PA585&ots=UugpRurgwQ&pg=PA585#v=onepage&f=false|accessdate= |quote=}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.derbyshireuk.net/dcustom1.html|title= Derbyshire & Peak District Customs: Barmote Court |website= derbyshireuk.net}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.duchyoflancaster.co.uk/properties-and-estates/historic-properties/barmote-court-wirksworth-derbyshire/|title= Barmote Court, Wirksworth \u2013 Derbyshire|publisher= [[Duchy of Lancaster]]}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://pdmhs.co.uk/peak-district-mining-laws-and-customs |title= Peak District Mining Laws and Customs |publisher=  [[PDMHS - Peak District Mines Historical Society]]}}\n\n[[Category:1288 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:History of Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n[[Category:Courts of England and Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHigh Peak(link changed toHigh Peak (upland)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barmote_court"}
{"title_page": "Reghin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Mure\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map              = Reghin jud Mures.png\n|map_caption            = Location in Mure\u0219 County\n|image_skyline=Reghin17.JPG\n|image_shield=\n|official_name=Reghin\n|other_name=Sz\u00e1szr\u00e9gen\n|area_total_km2=56.09\n|leader_name=Maria Precup<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=PSD\n|coordinates  = {{coord|46|46|33|N|24|42|30|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website={{url|http://www.primariareghin.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Reghin'''  ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8re\u0261in}}; {{lang-hu|Sz\u00e1szr\u00e9gen}}, {{IPA-hu|\u02c8sa\u02d0sre\u02d0\u0261\u025bn|AUD|Sz\u00e1szr\u00e9gen.ogg}} or ''{{lang|hu|R\u00e9gen}}''; {{lang-de|link=no|(S\u00e4chsisch) Regen}} is a [[Municipalities of Romania|city]] in [[Mure\u0219 County]], [[Transylvania]], [[Romania]], on the [[Mure\u0219 River]]. As of 2011 it has a population of 33,281.<ref name=\"insse_2011_nat\">Rezultatele finale ale Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntului din 2011: {{cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sR_TAB_5.xls|title=Tab.5 Tab5. Popula\u0163ia stabil\u0103 pe sexe \u015fi stare civil\u0103 \u2013 jude\u0163e, municipii, ora\u015fe, comune|publisher=[[Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]] din Rom\u00e2nia|accessdate= 2 February 2016|date=February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nReghin lies 29&nbsp;km north-northeast of [[T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]], extending on both shores of the river Mure\u0219, at the confluence with the [[Gurghiu (river)|Gurghiu]]. It was created by the 1926 union of the German-inhabited (formerly Sz\u00e1szr\u00e9gen) and the Hungarian-inhabited (formerly Magyarr\u00e9gen) city, and later joined with the two smaller communities of Apalina (Hungarian: ''Abaf\u00e1ja''; German: ''Bendorf'') and Iernu\u021beni (Hungarian: ''Radn\u00f3tf\u00e1ja''; German: ''Etschdorf''), added in 1956. Formally, the latter two are separate villages administered by the city.\n\n==History==\n[[File:ReghinChurch.jpg|thumb|190px|left|Transylvanian Saxons' Lutheran Church]]\nReghin was first mentioned in 1228 in a charter of [[List of Hungarian rulers|Hungarian King]] [[Andrew II of Hungary|Andrew II]] as ''Regun'' \u2013 however, evidence of its strategic location and defence system suggests that the town might have been considerably older, possibly founded by [[Ladislaus I of Hungary|Ladislaus I]].\n\nDespite the devastations of the city during the [[Mongol Empire|Mongol invasion]] (1241) and during the [[Tatar invasions|Tatar]] and [[Cumans|Cuman]] incursions (1285), the town developed rapidly: already in the second half of the 13th century the city was the residence and power centre of the families Tomaj and Kacsik, to whom the nearby lands were awarded by the Hungarian Crown. Reghin became a minor ecclesiastical centre in 1330, with the building of the [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] church ([[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] at the time, it now serves the [[Protestant]] community) in the German part of the city; it is still the largest church in the area, and hosts the oldest [[Medieval Latin]] inscription of any church in Transylvania. The Hungarian part of the city has an even older church, initially built in the [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] style.\n\nAt the beginning of the 15th century the settlement gained [[Town privileges|city rights]], and, from 1427, the right to hold fairs. In the 16th and 17th century Reghin was devastated by [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] troops on several occasions. It burned to the ground in 1848. In 1910, the population of the city included 7,310 inhabitants, of which 2,994 were [[Ethnic Germans|Germans]] ([[Transylvanian Saxons]]), 2,947 [[Magyars|Hungarians]], and 1,311 [[Romanians]]. [http://www.talmamedia.com/php/district/district.php?county=Maros-Torda]\n\nIn 1920 Reghin was assigned to Romania by the [[Treaty of Trianon]], together with the rest of Transylvania. In 1940, as a consequence of the [[Second Vienna Award]], the city became part of Hungary, together with the North of Transylvania. Almost 30% of the inhabitants were Jews at that time. In May 1944, the Jews were gathered in the [[Reghin ghetto]] and on 4 June 1944 were deported to Auschwitz. In 1945, the city again became part of Romania.\n\nAfter [[World War II]], Reghin lost some of its former Transylvanian Saxon character \u2013 as many Germans left for [[Western Germany]] during the latter stages of [[Communist Romania]] \u2013 and ethnic [[Romanians]] were settled in their place.  The data of the 1992 census showed a population of 24,601 Romanians, 12,471 Hungarian, 1,790 [[Romani people|Romani]], and 346 Germans. In 1994 Reghin was declared a [[Municipiu|city]].\n\n==Jewish history of Reghin==\n\n[[Jews]] began to settle in Reghin at the close of the 18th century, an organized community was established only during the middle of the 19th century, probably in 1849. The majority of the Jews came from [[Bukovina]] and [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]]. As a result of the battles during the Revolution of 1848 against Austria and the riots in Transylvania, Reghin and its Jewish population suffered severely. The first Jewish settlers, who arrived mainly from Bukovina and Galicia, were Orthodox, and the community remained Orthodox throughout its existence. [[\u1e24asidic]] influence was also felt. Besides the synagogue, there were two prayerhouses (kloyz) where the [[\u1e24asidim]] used to pray and had their own rabbis. A prominent figure in the community during its early years was the Orthodox [[rabbi]] Hillel Pollak (who was spiritually close to the extreme Orthodox rabbi Hillel Lichtenstein).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/reghin|title=Reghin|website=www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org}}</ref>\n\nA Jewish elementary school was founded in 1874. (Later it ceased its activities but was reestablished in 1910 and functioned until 1940.) The language of instruction in the school was Hungarian until 1918 after which it was Romanian. In 1885 the community became the administrative center for all the Jews of the district. The community numbered 282 in 1866, about 40 families in 1889, and 394 persons (about 7% of the total population) in 1891. Jews engaged in commerce, industry, and [[crafts]]. Their trade and industry were mainly connected with timber and some of them owned sawmills; there were also unskilled Jewish workers employed in the timber industry. The institutions of the community assisted the poor. Some of the \u1e24adarim established by the community translated the Pentateuch into German instead of [[Yiddish]] in order to facilitate study of this language by the children. From 1919 there was considerable Zionist activity in Reghin, and many members of the youth organizations emigrated to Ere\u1e93 Israel. The community numbered 1,587 (about 16% of the total population) in 1930, and 1,653 (about 10% of the total) in 1941.\n\nBetween the two world wars the Jews suffered from the nationalist and [[antisemitic]] activities of members of the [[Iron Guard]], and from the official antisemitic policies of most of the Romanian governments. The change of rule in 1940 (from Romanian to Hungarian) did not bring with it any improvement, as was hoped by the Jews, who remembered their legal emancipation in 1867 by the Austro-Hungarian authorities.\n\n===Holocaust and aftermath===\nIn the summer of 1944 the local Jews were concentrated into [[Reghin ghetto|a ghetto]] set up in a brick factory. Jews from the surrounding area were also brought there. From this [[ghetto]] about 6,000 Jews were deported to [[Auschwitz]] by the Hungarian authorities, at the request of the Nazi occupiers.\n\nAfter World War II, in 1947 a community numbering about 820 was formed mostly by survivors of the [[death camps]] and other Jews who had arrived in Reghin from places in different parts of Romania. The community gradually declined as a result of immigration to [[Israel]] and elsewhere. In 1971 there were still some 20 to 25 families living in Reghin and even fewer in the early 21st century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/article.aspx/Reghin|title=YIVO - Reghin|website=www.yivoencyclopedia.org}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\nReghin possesses some of the architectural elements that are unique in [[Transylvania]]. The stylistic details and the wrought iron balconies in the centre of the town are examples that prove the artistry of the local [[Artisan|craftsmen]]. One passes everyday by the apparently modest, yet defining signs of an ancient civilization. They personalize almost each and every building from the center of the town, making the visitor feel the fragrance of times gone by.<ref name=\"Costea\">{{cite book|last=Costea|first=Ioan I. |title=Reghin: Destin \u0219i istorie}}</ref>\n\nThe Evangelical church also known as the \"Saxon church\" has a tower that measures more than 47m high. The four smaller towers are proofs of the town's \"Right to the sword\". The construction of the church began at the end of the 13th century. Over the years, the architecture was modified because the church underwent many dramatic events. It was set on fire in 1400, 1630 and 1778. The documents reveal the use of several styles of early and transition [[gothic style]]. The church was consolidated in 1501 and since 1551, when the Transylvanian Saxons adopted the [[Lutheran Reformation]], on the main wall are written the words: \"Redemption cometh not from war, it is for peace that we all pray.\". Inside the church there is an organ with 20 registers that dates from 1784.<ref name=\"Costea\"/>\n\nThe Huszar Castle, former Bornemisza, situated in Apalina dates from the 13th\u201314th centuries and was restored in the 19th century. In the old mansion of the castle lived between 1584 and 1592 Gyulai P\u00e1l of Apalina (1559\u20131592). He was a royal diplomat, historian, chronicler, doctor and classical poet. The castle was built in the [[Renaissance]] style with [[baroque]] elements. In 1953 the castle was taken over and used by different educational institutions for disabled persons. It has recently been returned to its owners according to the new laws of property.<ref name=\"Costea\"/>\n\n==Culture==\nThe \"Petru Maior\" municipal library has more than 130,000 books, among which one dating from the 16th century. Another important book is [[Petru Maior]]'s \"History of the Romanians' Origins in Dacia\".<ref name=\"Ploie\u0219teanu 2006\">{{cite book|last=Ploie\u0219teanu|first=Grigore |last2=\u0218ara |first2=Marin|title=Reghinul cultural|year=2006|location=Reghin}}</ref>\n\nThe Ethnographic Museum has a rich patrimony, grouped in 49 collections of ethnography, folk art, artistry, records. The edifice is a monument of architecture built in 1892. The items exhibited concern trades, national costumes, and tradition specific to the upper course of the [[Mure\u0219 River]], Gurghiu valley and part of the [[Transylvanian Plain]].<ref name=\"Ploie\u0219teanu 2006\"/>\n\nThe \"Eugen Nicoara\" community centre was built between 1938 and 1939 when Dr. [[Eugen Nicoara]] was the president of the Reghin department of Astra Foundation. Representations of theatre, folk music, dances, chamber music, etc. are held on the stage of this building.<ref name=\"Ploie\u0219teanu 2006\"/>\n\nThe building in which the \"Alexandru Ceusianu\" secondary school functions was constructed in 1870 and housed the local law court. Lately in the post-war period, there was the Hungarian pedagogical school. Close by, was the house of the writer and magistrate [[Alexandru Ceusianu]].<ref name=\"Ploie\u0219teanu 2006\"/>\n\n==Economy==\nThe industry of Reghin is closely related to the traditions of the medieval trades and of the modern cooperative associations. Starting with the resources in the close vicinity, rich in wood and farm produces, the goods of the private producers from Reghin are in the market all over Romania and abroad. The wood processing industry is represented by companies such as Larix, Gralemn, Remex, Bucin-Mob, Prolemn, and Amis. Reghin is well known for the industry of the musical instruments, especially of violins. There are many companies that produces instruments using the famous resonance wood from [[Gurghiu Mountains|Calimani and Gurghiu]] forests. The violins made in Reghin are used abroad. The \"Hora\" Company is the first to manufacture instruments. In time, other companies were set up among which \"Gliga Instrumente Muzicale\". [[Yehudi Menuhin]] used a violin made by \"Gliga\" company.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pop|first=Simion T. |title=Comorile Transilvaniei: REGHIN|year=2008|publisher=ROMGHID|location=Reghin|isbn=978-973-88446-1-2}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\nReghin is presented by [[FCM Av\u00e2ntul Reghin|Av\u00e2ntul Reghin]] at association football. Av\u00e2ntul played in [[Liga I]] in [[1955 Divizia A|1955 season]]. They play in [[Liga III]] for 2015-16 season.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1850 |4227\n|1880 |5652\n|1900 |6057\n|1910 |7310\n|1930 |9290\n|1948 |9599\n|1956 |18091\n|1966 |23295\n|1977 |29903\n|1992 |39240\n|2002 |36023\n|2011 |33281\n}}\n\nIn 1850, the population of the town was 4,227, 2,964 of them being Germans, 644 Romanians, 556 Hungarians and 63 others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kia.hu/konyvtar/erdely/erd2002/msetn02.pdf|title=ERD\u00c9LY ETNIKAI \u00c9S FELEKEZETI STATISZTIK\u00c1JA\n}}</ref> In 1910, Reghin had 7,310 inhabitants, and the ethnic composition was made of 2,994 Germans, 2,947 Hungarians, 1,311 Romanians and 58 others.\n\nEthnic groups (2011 census):<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant.jsp?regiune_id=2568&judet_id=2798&localitate_id=2800|title=Structura Etno-demografic\u0103 a Rom\u00e2niei|website=www.edrc.ro}}</ref>\n*[[Romanians]]: 21,153 (66.81%)\n*[[Hungarians in Romania|Hungarians]]: 8,240 (26.02%)\n*[[Romani people]]: 2,002 (6.32%)\n*[[Germans of Romania|Germans]]: 182 (0.57%)\n*Others.\n\n==Landmarks==\nTraditional German architectural heritage:\n* the Protestant ([[Lutheranism|Lutheran]]) church, built in 1330 in honour of [[Mary, the mother of Jesus|Saint Mary]]. Burnt down in 1708 and in 1848, after which it had been rebuilt.\n* the Roman Catholic Church, which was consecrated in 1781.\n\nTraditional Hungarian architectural heritage:\n* the Protestant (Calvinist) church, 13th century, in 1910 completely rebuilt.\n* a [[Reformed Church in Hungary|Calvinist]] church built in 1890.\n\nTraditional Romanian architectural heritage:\n* the Greek-Catholic church, built in 1744, nowadays Romanian Orthodox.\n* the [[Romanian Church United with Rome, Greek-Catholic|Greek-Catholic]] church, built between 1811 and 1813, nowadays [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Romanian Orthodox]].\n\nNew landmarks:\n* a Romanian Orthodox Cathedral was built in the city in the 1990s.\n* the renowned [[Zoology|zoological]] and [[folklore]] collections.\n\n==Natives==\n* [[R\u00e9ka Albert]] (born 1972), physicist, biologist\n* [[Magda Kun]] (1912\u20131945), actress\n* [[Augustin Maior]] (1882\u20131963), physicist, educator, and inventor\n* [[Georg Maurer]] (1907\u20131971), writer\n* [[Hug\u00f3 Meltzl]] (1846\u20131908), rector of [[Franz Joseph University]]\n* [[Rudolf Wagner-R\u00e9geny]] (1903\u20131969), composer\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Romania}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2013 Sister cities===\nReghin is [[town twinning|twinned]] with:\n* {{flagicon|Republic of Moldova}}  [[Ungheni]], [[Republic of Moldova]]\n* {{flagicon|FRA}}  [[Bourg-la-Reine]], France\n* {{flagicon|ITA}}  [[Salle, Italy]]\n* {{flagicon|NED}}  [[Vianen]], Netherlands\n* {{flagicon|POL}}  [[Lubacz\u00f3w]], Poland\n\n== Images ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Reghin17.JPG|The centre of Reghin\nFile:Reghin2.JPG|The city park\nFile:CenterReghin.jpg|The city centre\nFile:Reghin23.JPG|[[Reformed Church of Romania|Reformed]] church\nFile:Reghin12.JPG|Plaque honouring World War I Hungarian heroes at the Reformed Church\nFile:Reghin22.JPG\nFile:ReghinEntrance.jpg|The monument at the entrance to Reghin, welcoming people\nFile:Reghin_Violins.JPG|The Violins monument in the centre of the city, a symbol of Reghin\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Hungarian exonyms (Mure\u015f County)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Costea|first=Ioan I. |title=Reghin: Destin \u0219i istorie}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ploie\u0219teanu|first=Grigore |last2=\u0218ara |first2=Marin|title=Reghinul cultural|year=2006|location=Reghin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Pop|first=Simion T. |title=Comorile Transilvaniei: REGHIN|year=2008|publisher=ROMGHID|location=Reghin|isbn=978-973-88446-1-2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Reghin}}\n* [http://www.primariareghin.ro/ primariareghin.ro] - official website of Reghin City.\n* {{JewishGen-LocalityPage|1168488|Reghin, Romania}}\n\n{{Mure\u015f County}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Reghin| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Mure\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Transylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Mure\u0219\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map              = Reghin jud Mures.png\n|map_caption            = Location in Mure\u0219 County\n|image_skyline=Reghin17.JPG\n|image_shield=\n|official_name=Reghin\n|other_name=Sz\u00e1szr\u00e9gen\n|area_total_km2=56.09\n|leader_name=Maria Precup\n|leader_party=PSD\n|coordinates  = {{coord|46|46|33|N|24|42|30|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website={{url|http://www.primariareghin.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Reghin'''  ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8re\u0261in}}; {{lang-hu|Sz\u00e1szr\u00e9gen}}, {{IPA-hu|\u02c8sa\u02d0sre\u02d0\u0261\u025bn|AUD|Sz\u00e1szr\u00e9gen.ogg}} or ''{{lang|hu|R\u00e9gen}}''; {{lang-de|link=no|(S\u00e4chsisch) Regen}} is a [[Municipalities of Romania|city]] in [[Mure\u0219 County]], [[Transylvania]], [[Romania]], on the [[Mure\u0219 River]]. As of 2011 it has a population of 33,281.<ref name=\"insse_2011_nat\">Rezultatele finale ale Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntului din 2011: {{cite web|url=http://www.recensamantromania.ro/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sR_TAB_5.xls|title=Tab.5 Tab5. Popula\u0163ia stabil\u0103 pe sexe \u015fi stare civil\u0103 \u2013 jude\u0163e, municipii, ora\u015fe, comune|publisher=[[Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103]] din Rom\u00e2nia|accessdate= 2 February 2016|date=February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\nReghin lies 29&nbsp;km north-northeast of [[T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]], extending on both shores of the river Mure\u0219, at the confluence with the [[Gurghiu (river)|Gurghiu]]. It was created by the 1926 union of the German-inhabited (formerly Sz\u00e1szr\u00e9gen) and the Hungarian-inhabited (formerly Magyarr\u00e9gen) city, and later joined with the two smaller communities of Apalina (Hungarian: ''Abaf\u00e1ja''; German: ''Bendorf'') and Iernu\u021beni (Hungarian: ''Radn\u00f3tf\u00e1ja''; German: ''Etschdorf''), added in 1956. Formally, the latter two are separate villages administered by the city.\n\n==History==\n[[File:ReghinChurch.jpg|thumb|190px|left|Transylvanian Saxons' Lutheran Church]]\nReghin was first mentioned in 1228 in a charter of [[List of Hungarian rulers|Hungarian King]] [[Andrew II of Hungary|Andrew II]] as ''Regun'' \u2013 however, evidence of its strategic location and defence system suggests that the town might have been considerably older, possibly founded by [[Ladislaus I of Hungary|Ladislaus I]].\n\nDespite the devastations of the city during the [[Mongol Empire|Mongol invasion]] (1241) and during the [[Tatar invasions|Tatar]] and [[Cumans|Cuman]] incursions (1285), the town developed rapidly: already in the second half of the 13th century the city was the residence and power centre of the families Tomaj and Kacsik, to whom the nearby lands were awarded by the Hungarian Crown. Reghin became a minor ecclesiastical centre in 1330, with the building of the [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] church ([[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] at the time, it now serves the [[Protestant]] community) in the German part of the city; it is still the largest church in the area, and hosts the oldest [[Medieval Latin]] inscription of any church in Transylvania. The Hungarian part of the city has an even older church, initially built in the [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] style.\n\nAt the beginning of the 15th century the settlement gained [[Town privileges|city rights]], and, from 1427, the right to hold fairs. In the 16th and 17th century Reghin was devastated by [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] troops on several occasions. It burned to the ground in 1848. In 1910, the population of the city included 7,310 inhabitants, of which 2,994 were [[Ethnic Germans|Germans]] ([[Transylvanian Saxons]]), 2,947 [[Magyars|Hungarians]], and 1,311 [[Romanians]]. [http://www.talmamedia.com/php/district/district.php?county=Maros-Torda]\n\nIn 1920 Reghin was assigned to Romania by the [[Treaty of Trianon]], together with the rest of Transylvania. In 1940, as a consequence of the [[Second Vienna Award]], the city became part of Hungary, together with the North of Transylvania. Almost 30% of the inhabitants were Jews at that time. In May 1944, the Jews were gathered in the [[Reghin ghetto]] and on 4 June 1944 were deported to Auschwitz. In 1945, the city again became part of Romania.\n\nAfter [[World War II]], Reghin lost some of its former Transylvanian Saxon character \u2013 as many Germans left for [[Western Germany]] during the latter stages of [[Communist Romania]] \u2013 and ethnic [[Romanians]] were settled in their place.  The data of the 1992 census showed a population of 24,601 Romanians, 12,471 Hungarian, 1,790 [[Romani people|Romani]], and 346 Germans. In 1994 Reghin was declared a [[Municipiu|city]].\n\n==Jewish history of Reghin==\n\n[[Jews]] began to settle in Reghin at the close of the 18th century, an organized community was established only during the middle of the 19th century, probably in 1849. The majority of the Jews came from [[Bukovina]] and [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]]. As a result of the battles during the Revolution of 1848 against Austria and the riots in Transylvania, Reghin and its Jewish population suffered severely. The first Jewish settlers, who arrived mainly from Bukovina and Galicia, were Orthodox, and the community remained Orthodox throughout its existence. [[\u1e24asidic]] influence was also felt. Besides the synagogue, there were two prayerhouses (kloyz) where the [[\u1e24asidim]] used to pray and had their own rabbis. A prominent figure in the community during its early years was the Orthodox [[rabbi]] Hillel Pollak (who was spiritually close to the extreme Orthodox rabbi Hillel Lichtenstein).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/reghin|title=Reghin|website=www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org}}</ref>\n\nA Jewish elementary school was founded in 1874. (Later it ceased its activities but was reestablished in 1910 and functioned until 1940.) The language of instruction in the school was Hungarian until 1918 after which it was Romanian. In 1885 the community became the administrative center for all the Jews of the district. The community numbered 282 in 1866, about 40 families in 1889, and 394 persons (about 7% of the total population) in 1891. Jews engaged in commerce, industry, and [[crafts]]. Their trade and industry were mainly connected with timber and some of them owned sawmills; there were also unskilled Jewish workers employed in the timber industry. The institutions of the community assisted the poor. Some of the \u1e24adarim established by the community translated the Pentateuch into German instead of [[Yiddish]] in order to facilitate study of this language by the children. From 1919 there was considerable Zionist activity in Reghin, and many members of the youth organizations emigrated to Ere\u1e93 Israel. The community numbered 1,587 (about 16% of the total population) in 1930, and 1,653 (about 10% of the total) in 1941.\n\nBetween the two world wars the Jews suffered from the nationalist and [[antisemitic]] activities of members of the [[Iron Guard]], and from the official antisemitic policies of most of the Romanian governments. The change of rule in 1940 (from Romanian to Hungarian) did not bring with it any improvement, as was hoped by the Jews, who remembered their legal emancipation in 1867 by the Austro-Hungarian authorities.\n\n===Holocaust and aftermath===\nIn the summer of 1944 the local Jews were concentrated into [[Reghin ghetto|a ghetto]] set up in a brick factory. Jews from the surrounding area were also brought there. From this [[ghetto]] about 6,000 Jews were deported to [[Auschwitz]] by the Hungarian authorities, at the request of the Nazi occupiers.\n\nAfter World War II, in 1947 a community numbering about 820 was formed mostly by survivors of the [[death camps]] and other Jews who had arrived in Reghin from places in different parts of Romania. The community gradually declined as a result of immigration to [[Israel]] and elsewhere. In 1971 there were still some 20 to 25 families living in Reghin and even fewer in the early 21st century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/article.aspx/Reghin|title=YIVO - Reghin|website=www.yivoencyclopedia.org}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\nReghin possesses some of the architectural elements that are unique in [[Transylvania]]. The stylistic details and the wrought iron balconies in the centre of the town are examples that prove the artistry of the local [[Artisan|craftsmen]]. One passes everyday by the apparently modest, yet defining signs of an ancient civilization. They personalize almost each and every building from the center of the town, making the visitor feel the fragrance of times gone by.<ref name=\"Costea\">{{cite book|last=Costea|first=Ioan I. |title=Reghin: Destin \u0219i istorie}}</ref>\n\nThe Evangelical church also known as the \"Saxon church\" has a tower that measures more than 47m high. The four smaller towers are proofs of the town's \"Right to the sword\". The construction of the church began at the end of the 13th century. Over the years, the architecture was modified because the church underwent many dramatic events. It was set on fire in 1400, 1630 and 1778. The documents reveal the use of several styles of early and transition [[gothic style]]. The church was consolidated in 1501 and since 1551, when the Transylvanian Saxons adopted the [[Lutheran Reformation]], on the main wall are written the words: \"Redemption cometh not from war, it is for peace that we all pray.\". Inside the church there is an organ with 20 registers that dates from 1784.<ref name=\"Costea\"/>\n\nThe Huszar Castle, former Bornemisza, situated in Apalina dates from the 13th\u201314th centuries and was restored in the 19th century. In the old mansion of the castle lived between 1584 and 1592 Gyulai P\u00e1l of Apalina (1559\u20131592). He was a royal diplomat, historian, chronicler, doctor and classical poet. The castle was built in the [[Renaissance]] style with [[baroque]] elements. In 1953 the castle was taken over and used by different educational institutions for disabled persons. It has recently been returned to its owners according to the new laws of property.<ref name=\"Costea\"/>\n\n==Culture==\nThe \"Petru Maior\" municipal library has more than 130,000 books, among which one dating from the 16th century. Another important book is [[Petru Maior]]'s \"History of the Romanians' Origins in Dacia\".<ref name=\"Ploie\u0219teanu 2006\">{{cite book|last=Ploie\u0219teanu|first=Grigore |last2=\u0218ara |first2=Marin|title=Reghinul cultural|year=2006|location=Reghin}}</ref>\n\nThe Ethnographic Museum has a rich patrimony, grouped in 49 collections of ethnography, folk art, artistry, records. The edifice is a monument of architecture built in 1892. The items exhibited concern trades, national costumes, and tradition specific to the upper course of the [[Mure\u0219 River]], Gurghiu valley and part of the [[Transylvanian Plain]].<ref name=\"Ploie\u0219teanu 2006\"/>\n\nThe \"Eugen Nicoara\" community centre was built between 1938 and 1939 when Dr. [[Eugen Nicoara]] was the president of the Reghin department of Astra Foundation. Representations of theatre, folk music, dances, chamber music, etc. are held on the stage of this building.<ref name=\"Ploie\u0219teanu 2006\"/>\n\nThe building in which the \"Alexandru Ceusianu\" secondary school functions was constructed in 1870 and housed the local law court. Lately in the post-war period, there was the Hungarian pedagogical school. Close by, was the house of the writer and magistrate [[Alexandru Ceusianu]].<ref name=\"Ploie\u0219teanu 2006\"/>\n\n==Economy==\nThe industry of Reghin is closely related to the traditions of the medieval trades and of the modern cooperative associations. Starting with the resources in the close vicinity, rich in wood and farm produces, the goods of the private producers from Reghin are in the market all over Romania and abroad. The wood processing industry is represented by companies such as Larix, Gralemn, Remex, Bucin-Mob, Prolemn, and Amis. Reghin is well known for the industry of the musical instruments, especially of violins. There are many companies that produces instruments using the famous resonance wood from [[Gurghiu Mountains|Calimani and Gurghiu]] forests. The violins made in Reghin are used abroad. The \"Hora\" Company is the first to manufacture instruments. In time, other companies were set up among which \"Gliga Instrumente Muzicale\". [[Yehudi Menuhin]] used a violin made by \"Gliga\" company.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pop|first=Simion T. |title=Comorile Transilvaniei: REGHIN|year=2008|publisher=ROMGHID|location=Reghin|isbn=978-973-88446-1-2}}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\nReghin is presented by [[FCM Av\u00e2ntul Reghin|Av\u00e2ntul Reghin]] at association football. Av\u00e2ntul played in [[Liga I]] in [[1955 Divizia A|1955 season]]. They play in [[Liga III]] for 2015-16 season.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1850 |4227\n|1880 |5652\n|1900 |6057\n|1910 |7310\n|1930 |9290\n|1948 |9599\n|1956 |18091\n|1966 |23295\n|1977 |29903\n|1992 |39240\n|2002 |36023\n|2011 |33281\n}}\n\nIn 1850, the population of the town was 4,227, 2,964 of them being Germans, 644 Romanians, 556 Hungarians and 63 others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kia.hu/konyvtar/erdely/erd2002/msetn02.pdf|title=ERD\u00c9LY ETNIKAI \u00c9S FELEKEZETI STATISZTIK\u00c1JA\n}}</ref> In 1910, Reghin had 7,310 inhabitants, and the ethnic composition was made of 2,994 Germans, 2,947 Hungarians, 1,311 Romanians and 58 others.\n\nEthnic groups (2011 census):<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant.jsp?regiune_id=2568&judet_id=2798&localitate_id=2800|title=Structura Etno-demografic\u0103 a Rom\u00e2niei|website=www.edrc.ro}}</ref>\n*[[Romanians]]: 21,153 (66.81%)\n*[[Hungarians in Romania|Hungarians]]: 8,240 (26.02%)\n*[[Romani people]]: 2,002 (6.32%)\n*[[Germans of Romania|Germans]]: 182 (0.57%)\n*Others.\n\n==Landmarks==\nTraditional German architectural heritage:\n* the Protestant ([[Lutheranism|Lutheran]]) church, built in 1330 in honour of [[Mary, the mother of Jesus|Saint Mary]]. Burnt down in 1708 and in 1848, after which it had been rebuilt.\n* the Roman Catholic Church, which was consecrated in 1781.\n\nTraditional Hungarian architectural heritage:\n* the Protestant (Calvinist) church, 13th century, in 1910 completely rebuilt.\n* a [[Reformed Church in Hungary|Calvinist]] church built in 1890.\n\nTraditional Romanian architectural heritage:\n* the Greek-Catholic church, built in 1744, nowadays Romanian Orthodox.\n* the [[Romanian Church United with Rome, Greek-Catholic|Greek-Catholic]] church, built between 1811 and 1813, nowadays [[Romanian Orthodox Church|Romanian Orthodox]].\n\nNew landmarks:\n* a Romanian Orthodox Cathedral was built in the city in the 1990s.\n* the renowned [[Zoology|zoological]] and [[folklore]] collections.\n\n==Natives==\n* [[R\u00e9ka Albert]] (born 1972), physicist, biologist\n* [[Magda Kun]] (1912\u20131945), actress\n* [[Augustin Maior]] (1882\u20131963), physicist, educator, and inventor\n* [[Georg Maurer]] (1907\u20131971), writer\n* [[Hug\u00f3 Meltzl]] (1846\u20131908), rector of [[Franz Joseph University]]\n* [[Rudolf Wagner-R\u00e9geny]] (1903\u20131969), composer\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Romania}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2013 Sister cities===\nReghin is [[town twinning|twinned]] with:\n* {{flagicon|Republic of Moldova}}  [[Ungheni]], [[Republic of Moldova]]\n* {{flagicon|FRA}}  [[Bourg-la-Reine]], France\n* {{flagicon|ITA}}  [[Salle, Italy]]\n* {{flagicon|NED}}  [[Vianen]], Netherlands\n* {{flagicon|POL}}  [[Lubacz\u00f3w]], Poland\n\n== Images ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Reghin17.JPG|The centre of Reghin\nFile:Reghin2.JPG|The city park\nFile:CenterReghin.jpg|The city centre\nFile:Reghin23.JPG|[[Reformed Church of Romania|Reformed]] church\nFile:Reghin12.JPG|Plaque honouring World War I Hungarian heroes at the Reformed Church\nFile:Reghin22.JPG\nFile:ReghinEntrance.jpg|The monument at the entrance to Reghin, welcoming people\nFile:Reghin_Violins.JPG|The Violins monument in the centre of the city, a symbol of Reghin\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Hungarian exonyms (Mure\u015f County)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Costea|first=Ioan I. |title=Reghin: Destin \u0219i istorie}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ploie\u0219teanu|first=Grigore |last2=\u0218ara |first2=Marin|title=Reghinul cultural|year=2006|location=Reghin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Pop|first=Simion T. |title=Comorile Transilvaniei: REGHIN|year=2008|publisher=ROMGHID|location=Reghin|isbn=978-973-88446-1-2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Reghin}}\n* [http://www.primariareghin.ro/ primariareghin.ro] - official website of Reghin City.\n* {{JewishGen-LocalityPage|1168488|Reghin, Romania}}\n\n{{Mure\u015f County}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Reghin| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Mure\u0219 County]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Transylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reghin"}
{"title_page": "Edward Judson", "text_new": "{{for|the British trade union leader|Edward Judson (trade unionist)}}\n{{Baptist}}\n'''Edward Judson''' (1844\u20131914) was an [[United States|American]] [[Baptist]] clergyman, born in [[Moulmein]], [[Myanmar|British Burma]], a son of the missionary [[Adoniram Judson]] and his second wife, [[Sarah Hall Boardman]]. He graduated from [[Brown University]] in 1863. In 1868, he was appointed [[professor]] of Latin and modern languages at Madison (now [[Colgate University|Colgate]]) University. In 1874\u201375, he  traveled abroad, and after being ordained into the Baptist ministry in the latter year, served as pastor of a church in [[Orange, New Jersey|Orange]], [[New Jersey|N. J.]], until 1881. Thereafter to the time of his death, he occupied the pulpit of a [[New York City]] church first known as the Berean Church, later as the Memorial Baptist, and finally as the [[Judson Memorial Church|Judson Memorial]] Church, which was erected on [[Washington Square Park|Washington Square]] to house the congregation. He lectured on [[theology]] at the [[University of Chicago]] (1904\u201306),  on Baptist principles and [[polity]] at [[Union Theological Seminary in the City of New York|Union Theological Seminary]] (1906\u201308), and was named professor of pastoral polity at Colgate. He published a ''biography'' of his father in 1899, and wrote ''The Institutional Church''.\n\n==Works==\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/lifeofadoniramj00juds The Life of Adoniram Judson]'' (1883)\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/newlaudesdominis00robi The New Laudes Domini: A Selection of Spiritual Songs, Ancient and Modern for Use in Baptist Churches]'' (1892)\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/institutionalchu00juds The Institutional Church: A Primer in Pastoral Theology]'' (1899)\n* {{NIE}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Judson, Edward}}\n[[Category:American theologians]]\n[[Category:Christian writers]]\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from New York City]]\n[[Category:Baptist ministers from the United States]]\n[[Category:1844 births]]\n[[Category:1914 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baptists from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the British trade union leader|Edward Judson (trade unionist)}}\n{{Baptist}}\n'''Edward Judson''' (1844-1914) was an [[United States|American]] [[Baptist]] clergyman, born in [[Moulmein]], [[Myanmar|British Burma]], a son of the missionary [[Adoniram Judson]] and his second wife, [[Sarah Hall Boardman]]. He graduated from [[Brown University]] in 1863. In 1868, he was appointed [[professor]] of Latin and modern languages at Madison (now [[Colgate University|Colgate]]) University. In 1874-75, he  traveled abroad, and after being ordained into the Baptist ministry in the latter year, served as pastor of a church in [[Orange, New Jersey|Orange]], [[New Jersey|N. J.]], until 1881. Thereafter to the time of his death, he occupied the pulpit of a [[New York City]] church first known as the Berean Church, later as the Memorial Baptist, and finally as the [[Judson Memorial Church|Judson Memorial]] Church, which was erected on [[Washington Square Park|Washington Square]] to house the congregation. He lectured on [[theology]] at the [[University of Chicago]] (1904\u201306),  on Baptist principles and [[polity]] at [[Union Theological Seminary in the City of New York|Union Theological Seminary]] (1906\u201308), and was named professor of pastoral polity at Colgate. He published a ''biography'' of his father in 1899, and wrote ''The Institutional Church''.\n\n==Works==\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/lifeofadoniramj00juds The Life of Adoniram Judson]'' (1883)\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/newlaudesdominis00robi The New Laudes Domini: A Selection of Spiritual Songs, Ancient and Modern for Use in Baptist Churches]'' (1892)\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/institutionalchu00juds The Institutional Church: A Primer in Pastoral Theology]'' (1899)\n* {{NIE}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Judson, Edward}}\n[[Category:American theologians]]\n[[Category:Christian writers]]\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from New York City]]\n[[Category:Baptist ministers from the United States]]\n[[Category:1844 births]]\n[[Category:1914 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baptists from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Kindly Copyeditor", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Judson"}
{"title_page": "CLH Pipeline System", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n\n[[File:GPSS_marker_plate_-_geograph.org.uk_-_833285.jpg|thumb|right|GPSS marker plate, near [[Heydon, Cambridgeshire]], Great Britain. The marker text: S/SW shows marker is on the Sandy-Saffron Walden link; {{convert|24|km}} is the distance from Sandy; up-arrow indicates that the normal flow is away from the observer looking at the notice]]\n\n[[File:Oil_pipeline_marker_-_geograph.org.uk_-_591698.jpg|thumb|right|GPSS pre-WW2 white marker, with post-WW2 yellow/black post]]\n[[File:Pipeline_crossing_the_Stroudwater_Canal_-_geograph.org.uk_-_344271.jpg|thumb|right|The GPSS crosses the non-navigable [[Stroudwater Canal]], near to [[Whitminster]], [[Gloucestershire]]]]\n\n[[File:TORM_VITA_at_Royal_Portbury_Dock_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1142701.jpg|thumb|right|The tanker TORM VITA discharges aviation fuel at Berth 7, [[Royal Portbury Dock]] near Bristol. Known as the ''Bristol Aviation Fuel Terminal'', it was managed by the Oil and Pipelines Agency, with its intake distributed by the GPSS]]\n\n[[File:Man_Made_Embankment_-_geograph.org.uk_-_118656.jpg|thumb|right|The former Berwick Wood Petroleum Supply Depot (PSD), located in [[Berwick, Gloucestershire]], was one of the original additional storage facilities built to connect to the GPSS]]\n[[File:Railway_Terminal_-_geograph.org.uk_-_293536.jpg|thumb|right|The railway-connected Misterton & Rawcliffe PSDs located in [[Misterton, Nottinghamshire]], which is also connected to the GPSS]]\n\n[[File:Stonesby_PSD_(petroleum_storage_depot)_-_geograph.org.uk_-_594114.jpg|thumb|right|The former [[Stonesby]] PSD located in [[Leicestershire]], now the site of an [[NTL Incorporated|NTL]] transmission site and aerial]]\n\nThe '''CLH Pipeline System (CLH-PS)''', formerly the '''Government Pipelines and Storage System (GPSS)''', is a [[United Kingdom]] pipeline system run by [[Compa\u00f1\u00eda Log\u00edstica de Hidrocarburos]] (CLH). The network at one time consisted of over {{convert|2500|km}} of pipeline and 46 other facilities.  However, several of these facilities were closed before the GPSS was sold in 2015 and a number of the pipelines were mothballed and later 'abandoned'. Earlier the total number of facilities on the GPSS was much larger than 46.  For example, in 1989 there were 40 Petroleum Storage Depots in operation plus large numbers of other facilities such as pump-stations, junctions, and ingress and egress points.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref> It is interconnected with some other commercial pipeline systems.\n\n==Pre-WW2 planning==\n\nAs part of the planning and preparations for [[World War II]], the Air Ministry realised that the ability to distribute [[aviation fuel]] to the RAF's aircraft and [[petrol]] to its ground support vehicles was essential to sustaining any battle, in which superiority would be gained mainly in the air. In 1936, however, the RAF only possessed fuel reserves of 8,000 tons.  These were at the time estimated to be enough for 10 days of war but in reality would have only represented 1 day of peak wartime usage.<ref>The Royal Air Force Builds for War - A History of Design and Construction in the RAF 1935 - 1945 p270. The Stationery Office {{ISBN|0-11-772469-6}}</ref> Authorisation was given to build a series of fuel storage depots with semi-buried tanks in them that would be protected against aerial attack.  Initially in 1936 the figure was set at 90,000 tons but this had been increased to 800,000 tons by 1938.  By the start of World War Two a number of these new protected storage depots were already operational.<ref>A.L.Adams: The Development and Use of the Department of Energy's Oil Pipelines and Storages p5 (Paper 1980).</ref> However, no pipelines were constructed until after the war started, with the first being built in 1941.<ref>D.J.Payton-Smith: Oil - A Study of War-time Policy and Administration p225. HMSO SBN 11 630074 4</ref>\n\n==National pipeline system==\n\nWith the declaration of war and as pre-planned, the Petroleum Board came into operation with all former staff of the separate petrol companies coming under the Petroleum Board.  The entire operation of fuel supplies was controlled from Shell-Mex House in London.<ref>Petroleum at War - The Wartime Story of the Petroleum Board 1956 A reprint of a series of Articles originally printed in the Petroleum Times.</ref> The programme for building protected storage tanks continued and increased with the bulk of construction being between 1940 and 1942.  The value of these protected storage tanks can be seen in that whereas 500,000 tons of above ground tanks were destroyed as a result of German bombing, only two protected storage tanks [8,000 tons], one at Poole in Dorset and one at Falmouth in Cornwall, were destroyed.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p27 and p29. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>\n\nAs fuel imports into Great Britain increased it became more difficult for the existing road and rail network to meet the demand to transfer the fuel eastwards and southwards from the west coast ports, the east coast fuel import facilities were closed because of the bombing.  In April 1941 the go ahead was given for the construction of an oil pipeline from Avonmouth, where a large number of new protected storage tanks had been constructed, to the Thames (A/T pipeline).  Concern as to the vulnerability of the fuel import facilities, led to the construction in 1942 of a pipeline linking the import facilities in the Stanlow area with those at Avonmouth.<ref>D.J.Payton-Smith: Oil - A Study of War-time Policy and Administration p225 and 226. HMSO SBN 11 630074 4</ref>  This was followed by the construction of a pipeline running from off the A/T pipeline to the Southampton area for the stockpiling of fuel for the possible second front (R/H pipeline). During 1943 an entire ring-main linking the Mersey, the Avonmouth area, the Thames and up to the Humber area, was constructed. This was later extended into East Anglia to supply both the RAF and the United States Army Air Force (USAAF).<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p49, p51 to 53 and p62 to 65. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>\n\nLinked to the GPSS were the cross-channel PLUTO pipelines which ran from the Isle of Wight to Cherbourg (code named BAMBI) and from Dungeness to Boulogne (code named DUMBO).  The R/H pipeline had already been constructed but to supply DUMBO a new pipeline was built from the Thames to Dungeness in 1943.<ref>Sir Donald Banks: Flame over Britain p186.</ref> The success of the PLUTO was, however, limited with only 8% of the fuel delivered between D-Day and VE Day being via them.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p84 and p62 to 65. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>  The official history states of them that 'PLUTO contributed nothing to Allied supplies at a time that would have been most valuable' and 'DUMBO was more valuable, but at a time when success was of less importance.' <ref>D.J.Payton-Smith: Oil - A Study of War-time Policy and Administration p448. HMSO SBN 11 630074</ref>\n\n==Post WW2==\n\nImmediately following the end of the war, most of the system was mothballed with surplus fuel disposed of, sites were reduced to minimum manning, and the pipelines filled with water.<ref>A.L.Adams: The Development and Use of the Department of Energy's Oil Pipelines and Storages p7 (Paper 1980).</ref> However, this changed with the 'Cold War' and the decision taken to recommission the network.  One person working on bringing one previously 'mothballed' storage depot back into operation related how it was \u2018buried beneath rubbish and long grass\u2019.<ref>'This is My Life' in Pipevine Issue No 10 December 1978.  'Pipevine' was the in-house magazine of the British Pipelines Agency from 1976 to 1992.</ref> Two new fuel importation complexes were built in the 1950s, one to the south west of Bristol and one in the Stanlow area.  A very large storage depot using salt caverns was constructed in Cheshire for storing both crude and refined oils.<ref>A.L.Adams: Storage of Government Oil Reserves in Salt Cavities - Paper given to the SMRI in October 1982</ref> On being recommissioned, the WW2 cross-Pennine pipeline was found to be badly corroded and in the 1950s a new pipeline was built from the Stanlow area to the Humber.  New storage depots were built on this pipeline and a third new import facility was constructed on the Humber.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p95 to p101. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>\n\nThe first commercial usage of the system was immediately after the war to supply a depot on the River Severn from Avonmouth.<ref>A.L.Adams: The Development and Use of the Department of Energy's Oil Pipelines and Storages p7 (Paper 1980).</ref> In the early 1950s some aviation fuel was pumped from Avonmouth to a depot on the Thames to supply Heathrow airport by road tanker from there.  Esso also used the network to pump aviation fuel from the Fawley refinery to the Thames depot to supply Heathrow.  The late 1950s also saw a spur off one of the PLUTO pipelines, originally from the Thames to Dungeness, brought back into operation to pump fuel from the Isle of Grain to the Thames Depot.  From there aviation fuel was carried to Heathrow Airport, no longer by road tanker but via the first commercial pipeline which was constructed by Shell-Mex & BP in 1959.<ref>A.L.Adams: The Development and Use of the Department of Energy's Oil Pipelines and Storages p8 (Paper 1980).</ref>\n\nIn 1967 an agreement was reached with Conoco for leasing five petroleum storage depots for road loading of ground fuels.  These were all supplied from the Immingham refinery which was connected to the GPSS pipeline network.  During the late 1970s and early 1980s two commercial road loading facilities and two additional refineries were also connected to the GPSS.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p115 to 117. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>  There were a substantial number of depots that were not on the pipeline network.  In the 1970s most of these were closed down.  In the 1980s it was decided by the government that large scale strategic storage of petroleum as a civil reserve was no longer required.  The salt cavities and some of the storage depots previously used for civil reserve storage were either closed or leased commercially.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p126 to 133 and 141 to 142. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>\n\nThe management of civil storage depots and the pipeline network initially came under the Board of Trade and then in 1942 under the Ministry of Fuel Power.  This became the Department of Energy in the 1970s.  In 1975 the British National Oil Corporation (BNOC) was set up and took over the running of the Department's system.<ref>A.L.Adams: The Development and Use of the Department of Energy's Oil Pipelines and Storages p9 (Paper 1980).</ref> In 1985 the government closed BNOC but kept the GPSS and the [[Oil and Pipelines Agency]] (OPA) was set up by Act of Parliament purely to manage the GPSS.<ref>HMSO: The Oil and Pipelines Act 1985</ref>  Air Ministry storage depots and spur pipelines had been managed by the ministry and later by the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] (MoD) but in 1989 it was decided by the government to merge these sites and pipelines with the rest of the GPSS under the management of OPA.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p149 to 150. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref> Although the GPSS remained officially secret until the end of the Cold War, knowledge of it was in fact already in the public domain through the publication of various books an papers such as the Official History, Adams' papers and the series of articles in the Petroleum Times - 'Petroleum at War'.\n\nPrivate-sector usage was encouraged, but limited; the OPA's task was to provide \"maximum development of private sector usage of the GPSS, provided this did not impinge upon its primary purpose of supplying the required fuel for defence purposes and did not require capital investment from public funds.\" As a result, the pipeline was extended and developed to allow connection to: all UK-based oil refineries and major fuel processing depots; as well as all major civilian airports - including [[London Heathrow|Heathrow]], [[London Gatwick|Gatwick]], [[Stansted Airport|Stansted]] and [[Manchester Airport|Manchester]] - during the period of the [[Cold War]]. As a result of the [[Fuel protests in the United Kingdom|2000 fuel protests]], Defence Secretary [[Geoff Hoon]] instructed the MoD to plan for extension of the GPSS to beat any future fuel blockade.<ref name=GuardUKOil>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/apr/06/uk.oil</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n\nDuring World War Two to protect the pipeline from damage or look for possible leaks, a team of men and women was employed to patrol the pipeline.  Each person was responsible for a section of pipeline eight to ten miles long.<ref>Pathe News - Trans-Britain Pipeline</ref> This was clearly very manpower intensive and later it was possible to use commercial not RAF helicopters to patrol the pipelines on a fortnightly basis and helicopter landing pads were constructed on the depots.  In the 1950s a means of preventing pipeline corrosion known as [[cathodic protection]] became available.  This applies a voltage to the pipeline such that the natural electrical action which takes place between pipe and soil leading to corrosion is reversed.  Cathodic protection was applied to the pipeline system on a rolling programme which started in 1954 and was completed in 1970.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 2017 p121. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>\n\nAfter the war the locations of the pipelines were marked with identification posts with bright yellow roofs with a thick black line. Even so, in March 2000 at [[Furness Vale]] near [[Whaley Bridge]], [[High Peak, Derbyshire|High Peak]], [[Derbyshire]] one of the lines was cut by workmen.\n\n==Privatisation: CLH-PS==\nIn May 2012 the [[UK Government]] announced plans to sell all or part of the GPSS<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/05/22/uk-britain-fuel-network-idUKBRE84L0YM20120522|title=UK considers sale of aviation fuel network|date=22 May 2012|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> and legislation to enable it to do so was included in the [[Energy Bill 2012\u201313 (UK Parliament)|Energy Act 2013]].\n\nThree years after announcing the plan to sell GPSS, on 20 March 2015, the GPSS was acquired by Spanish oil network operator [[Compa\u00f1\u00eda Log\u00edstica de Hidrocarburos]] (CLH) for \u00a382m.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clh.es/section.cfm?id=4&side=53&lang=en&nid=477 |title=CLH acquires UK oil distribution network |publisher=Compa\u00f1\u00eda Log\u00edstica de Hidrocarburos |accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref> The MoD also signed a contract with CLH for the military to be continued to be supplied with fuel via the GPSS. It was stated that over the next ten years the MoD would pay \u00a3237 million for the use of the system.<ref>Government Pipeline and Storage System Sale Update: Written statement - HCWS434 made on 20 March 2015.</ref>  MoD had previously paid nothing for the use of the GPSS and also gained from the surplus of income over expenditure that OPA used to generate from running the GPSS.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 p205 published 2017. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>  \nThe sale did not include the six coastal Oil Fuel Depots owned by the MoD, which continued to be operated and maintained by the residual OPA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2015-03-20/HCWS434/ |title=Government Pipeline and Storage System Sale - HCWS434 |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing its acquisition by CLH, the GPSS was subsequently renamed the CLH Pipeline System (CLH-PS).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tankterminals.com/news_detail.php?id=3176 |title=CLH Begins Operating the UK\u2019s Largest Fuel Pipeline Network |publisher=TankTerminals.com |accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> Since CLH have taken over the ownership of the GPSS a number of the pipelines that make up the system have been closed down.<ref>https://www.airfieldresearchgroup.org.uk/forum/fuel-depots/5499-government-pipelines-and-storage-system-gpss?start=220#151415{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[UK oil pipeline network]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}\n* D.J.Payton-Smith: Oil - A Study of War-time Policy and Administration. HMSO SBN 11 630074\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Government Pipelines and Storage System}}\n*[http://www.linewatch.org.uk/sites/default/files/2017-12/LWC-2017-01-JZ-GEN-CLH%20Pipeline%20System_2.pdf Schematic Map of CLH Pipeline System]\n*[https://www.secret-bases.co.uk/secret3.htm?permalink=GPSS GPSS on Secret Bases website]\n*[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)]] - [https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/35893/gpss_booklet.pdf Legislation to enable the sale of the Government Pipeline and Storage System], April 2011\n\n{{Oil storage and distribution in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Oil pipelines in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n\n[[File:GPSS_marker_plate_-_geograph.org.uk_-_833285.jpg|thumb|right|GPSS marker plate, near [[Heydon, Cambridgeshire]], Great Britain. The marker text: S/SW shows marker is on the Sandy-Saffron Walden link; {{convert|24|km}} is the distance from Sandy; up-arrow indicates that the normal flow is away from the observer looking at the notice]]\n\n[[File:Oil_pipeline_marker_-_geograph.org.uk_-_591698.jpg|thumb|right|GPSS pre-WW2 white marker, with post-WW2 yellow/black post]]\n[[File:Pipeline_crossing_the_Stroudwater_Canal_-_geograph.org.uk_-_344271.jpg|thumb|right|The GPSS crosses the non-navigable [[Stroudwater Canal]], near to [[Whitminster]], [[Gloucestershire]]]]\n\n[[File:TORM_VITA_at_Royal_Portbury_Dock_-_geograph.org.uk_-_1142701.jpg|thumb|right|The tanker TORM VITA discharges aviation fuel at Berth 7, [[Royal Portbury Dock]] near Bristol. Known as the ''Bristol Aviation Fuel Terminal'', it was managed by the Oil and Pipelines Agency, with its intake distributed by the GPSS]]\n\n[[File:Man_Made_Embankment_-_geograph.org.uk_-_118656.jpg|thumb|right|The former Berwick Wood Petroleum Supply Depot (PSD), located in [[Berwick, Gloucestershire]], was one of the original additional storage facilities built to connect to the GPSS]]\n[[File:Railway_Terminal_-_geograph.org.uk_-_293536.jpg|thumb|right|The railway-connected Misterton & Rawcliffe PSDs located in [[Misterton, Nottinghamshire]], which is also connected to the GPSS]]\n\n[[File:Stonesby_PSD_(petroleum_storage_depot)_-_geograph.org.uk_-_594114.jpg|thumb|right|The former [[Stonesby]] PSD located in [[Leicestershire]], now the site of an [[NTL Incorporated|NTL]] transmission site and aerial]]\n\nThe '''CLH Pipeline System (CLH-PS)''', formerly the '''Government Pipelines and Storage System (GPSS)''', is a [[United Kingdom]] pipeline system run by [[Compa\u00f1\u00eda Log\u00edstica de Hidrocarburos]] (CLH). The network at one time consisted of over {{convert|2500|km}} of pipeline and 46 other facilities.  However, several of these facilities were closed before the GPSS was sold in 2015 and a number of the pipelines were mothballed and later 'abandoned'. Earlier the total number of facilities on the GPSS was much larger than 46.  For example, in 1989 there were 40 Petroleum Storage Depots in operation plus large numbers of other facilities such as pump-stations, junctions, and ingress and egress points.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref> It is interconnected with some other commercial pipeline systems.\n\n==Pre-WW2 planning==\n\nAs part of the planning and preparations for [[World War II]], the Air Ministry realised that the ability to distribute [[aviation fuel]] to the RAF's aircraft and [[petrol]] to its ground support vehicles was essential to sustaining any battle, in which superiority would be gained mainly in the air. In 1936, however, the RAF only possessed fuel reserves of 8,000 tons.  These were at the time estimated to be enough for 10 days of war but in reality would have only represented 1 day of peak wartime usage.<ref>The Royal Air Force Builds for War - A History of Design and Construction in the RAF 1935 - 1945 p270. The Stationery Office {{ISBN|0-11-772469-6}}</ref> Authorisation was given to build a series of fuel storage depots with semi-buried tanks in them that would be protected against aerial attack.  Initially in 1936 the figure was set at 90,000 tons but this had been increased to 800,000 tons by 1938.  By the start of World War Two a number of these new protected storage depots were already operational.<ref>A.L.Adams: The Development and Use of the Department of Energy's Oil Pipelines and Storages p5 (Paper 1980).</ref> However, no pipelines were constructed until after the war started, with the first being built in 1941.<ref>D.J.Payton-Smith: Oil - A Study of War-time Policy and Administration p225. HMSO SBN 11 630074 4</ref>\n\n==National pipeline system==\n\nWith the declaration of war and as pre-planned, the Petroleum Board came into operation with all former staff of the separate petrol companies coming under the Petroleum Board.  The entire operation of fuel supplies was controlled from Shell-Mex House in London.<ref>Petroleum at War - The Wartime Story of the Petroleum Board 1956 A reprint of a series of Articles originally printed in the Petroleum Times.</ref> The programme for building protected storage tanks continued and increased with the bulk of construction being between 1940 and 1942.  The value of these protected storage tanks can be seen in that whereas 500,000 tons of above ground tanks were destroyed as a result of German bombing, only two protected storage tanks [8,000 tons], one at Poole in Dorset and one at Falmouth in Cornwall, were destroyed.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p27 and p29. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>\n\nAs fuel imports into Great Britain increased it became more difficult for the existing road and rail network to meet the demand to transfer the fuel eastwards and southwards from the west coast ports, the east coast fuel import facilities were closed because of the bombing.  In April 1941 the go ahead was given for the construction of an oil pipeline from Avonmouth, where a large number of new protected storage tanks had been constructed, to the Thames (A/T pipeline).  Concern as to the vulnerability of the fuel import facilities, led to the construction in 1942 of a pipeline linking the import facilities in the Stanlow area with those at Avonmouth.<ref>D.J.Payton-Smith: Oil - A Study of War-time Policy and Administration p225 and 226. HMSO SBN 11 630074 4</ref>  This was followed by the construction of a pipeline running from off the A/T pipeline to the Southampton area for the stockpiling of fuel for the possible second front (R/H pipeline). During 1943 an entire ring-main linking the Mersey, the Avonmouth area, the Thames and up to the Humber area, was constructed. This was later extended into East Anglia to supply both the RAF and the United States Army Air Force (USAAF).<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p49, p51 to 53 and p62 to 65. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>\n\nLinked to the GPSS were the cross-channel PLUTO pipelines which ran from the Isle of Wight to Cherbourg (code named BAMBI) and from Dungeness to Boulogne (code named DUMBO).  The R/H pipeline had already been constructed but to supply DUMBO a new pipeline was built from the Thames to Dungeness in 1943.<ref>Sir Donald Banks: Flame over Britain p186.</ref> The success of the PLUTO was, however, limited with only 8% of the fuel delivered between D-Day and VE Day being via them.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p84 and p62 to 65. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>  The official history states of them that 'PLUTO contributed nothing to Allied supplies at a time that would have been most valuable' and 'DUMBO was more valuable, but at a time when success was of less importance.' <ref>D.J.Payton-Smith: Oil - A Study of War-time Policy and Administration p448. HMSO SBN 11 630074</ref>\n\n==Post WW2==\n\nImmediately following the end of the war, most of the system was mothballed with surplus fuel disposed of, sites were reduced to minimum manning, and the pipelines filled with water.<ref>A.L.Adams: The Development and Use of the Department of Energy's Oil Pipelines and Storages p7 (Paper 1980).</ref> However, this changed with the 'Cold War' and the decision taken to recommission the network.  One person working on bringing one previously 'mothballed' storage depot back into operation related how it was \u2018buried beneath rubbish and long grass\u2019.<ref>'This is My Life' in Pipevine Issue No 10 December 1978.  'Pipevine' was the in-house magazine of the British Pipelines Agency from 1976 to 1992.</ref> Two new fuel importation complexes were built in the 1950s, one to the south west of Bristol and one in the Stanlow area.  A very large storage depot using salt caverns was constructed in Cheshire for storing both crude and refined oils.<ref>A.L.Adams: Storage of Government Oil Reserves in Salt Cavities - Paper given to the SMRI in October 1982</ref> On being recommissioned, the WW2 cross-Pennine pipeline was found to be badly corroded and in the 1950s a new pipeline was built from the Stanlow area to the Humber.  New storage depots were built on this pipeline and a third new import facility was constructed on the Humber.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p95 to p101. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>\n\nThe first commercial usage of the system was immediately after the war to supply a depot on the River Severn from Avonmouth.<ref>A.L.Adams: The Development and Use of the Department of Energy's Oil Pipelines and Storages p7 (Paper 1980).</ref> In the early 1950s some aviation fuel was pumped from Avonmouth to a depot on the Thames to supply Heathrow airport by road tanker from there.  Esso also used the network to pump aviation fuel from the Fawley refinery to the Thames depot to supply Heathrow.  The late 1950s also saw a spur off one of the PLUTO pipelines, originally from the Thames to Dungeness, brought back into operation to pump fuel from the Isle of Grain to the Thames Depot.  From there aviation fuel was carried to Heathrow Airport, no longer by road tanker but via the first commercial pipeline which was constructed by Shell-Mex & BP in 1959.<ref>A.L.Adams: The Development and Use of the Department of Energy's Oil Pipelines and Storages p8 (Paper 1980).</ref>\n\nIn 1967 an agreement was reached with Conoco for leasing five petroleum storage depots for road loading of ground fuels.  These were all supplied from the Immingham refinery which was connected to the GPSS pipeline network.  During the late 1970s and early 1980s two commercial road loading facilities and two additional refineries were also connected to the GPSS.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p115 to 117. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>  There were a substantial number of depots that were not on the pipeline network.  In the 1970s most of these were closed down.  In the 1980s it was decided by the government that large scale strategic storage of petroleum as a civil reserve was no longer required.  The salt cavities and some of the storage depots previously used for civil reserve storage were either closed or leased commercially.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p126 to 133 and 141 to 142. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>\n\nThe management of civil storage depots and the pipeline network initially came under the Board of Trade and then in 1942 under the Ministry of Fuel Power.  This became the Department of Energy in the 1970s.  In 1975 the British National Oil Corporation (BNOC) was set up and took over the running of the Department's system.<ref>A.L.Adams: The Development and Use of the Department of Energy's Oil Pipelines and Storages p9 (Paper 1980).</ref> In 1985 the government closed BNOC but kept the GPSS and the [[Oil and Pipelines Agency]] (OPA) was set up by Act of Parliament purely to manage the GPSS.<ref>HMSO: The Oil and Pipelines Act 1985</ref>  Air Ministry storage depots and spur pipelines had been managed by the ministry and later by the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] (MoD) but in 1989 it was decided by the government to merge these sites and pipelines with the rest of the GPSS under the management of OPA.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017 p149 to 150. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref> Although the GPSS remained officially secret until the end of the Cold War, knowledge of it was in fact already in the public domain through the publication of various books an papers such as the Official History, Adams' papers and the series of articles in the Petroleum Times - 'Petroleum at War'.\n\nPrivate-sector usage was encouraged, but limited; the OPA's task was to provide \"maximum development of private sector usage of the GPSS, provided this did not impinge upon its primary purpose of supplying the required fuel for defence purposes and did not require capital investment from public funds.\" As a result, the pipeline was extended and developed to allow connection to: all UK-based oil refineries and major fuel processing depots; as well as all major civilian airports - including [[London Heathrow|Heathrow]], [[London Gatwick|Gatwick]], [[Stansted Airport|Stansted]] and [[Manchester Airport|Manchester]] - during the period of the [[Cold War]]. As a result of the [[Fuel protests in the United Kingdom|2000 fuel protests]], Defence Secretary [[Geoff Hoon]] instructed the MoD to plan for extension of the GPSS to beat any future fuel blockade.<ref name=GuardUKOil>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/apr/06/uk.oil</ref>\n\n==Operations==\n\nDuring World War Two to protect the pipeline from damage or look for possible leaks, a team of men and women was employed to patrol the pipeline.  Each person was responsible for a section of pipeline eight to ten miles long.<ref>Pathe News - Trans-Britain Pipeline</ref> This was clearly very manpower intensive and later it was possible to use commercial not RAF helicopters to patrol the pipelines on a fortnightly basis and helicopter landing pads were constructed on the depots.  In the 1950s a means of preventing pipeline corrosion known as [[cathodic protection]] became available.  This applies a voltage to the pipeline such that the natural electrical action which takes place between pipe and soil leading to corrosion is reversed.  Cathodic protection was applied to the pipeline system on a rolling programme which started in 1954 and was completed in 1970.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 2017 p121. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>\n\nAfter the war the locations of the pipelines were marked with identification posts with bright yellow roofs with a thick black line. Even so, in March 2000 at [[Furness Vale]] near [[Whaley Bridge]], [[High Peak (England)|High Peak]], [[Derbyshire]] one of the lines was cut by workmen.\n\n==Privatisation: CLH-PS==\nIn May 2012 the [[UK Government]] announced plans to sell all or part of the GPSS<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2012/05/22/uk-britain-fuel-network-idUKBRE84L0YM20120522|title=UK considers sale of aviation fuel network|date=22 May 2012|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> and legislation to enable it to do so was included in the [[Energy Bill 2012\u201313 (UK Parliament)|Energy Act 2013]].\n\nThree years after announcing the plan to sell GPSS, on 20 March 2015, the GPSS was acquired by Spanish oil network operator [[Compa\u00f1\u00eda Log\u00edstica de Hidrocarburos]] (CLH) for \u00a382m.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clh.es/section.cfm?id=4&side=53&lang=en&nid=477 |title=CLH acquires UK oil distribution network |publisher=Compa\u00f1\u00eda Log\u00edstica de Hidrocarburos |accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref> The MoD also signed a contract with CLH for the military to be continued to be supplied with fuel via the GPSS. It was stated that over the next ten years the MoD would pay \u00a3237 million for the use of the system.<ref>Government Pipeline and Storage System Sale Update: Written statement - HCWS434 made on 20 March 2015.</ref>  MoD had previously paid nothing for the use of the GPSS and also gained from the surplus of income over expenditure that OPA used to generate from running the GPSS.<ref>Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 p205 published 2017. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}</ref>  \nThe sale did not include the six coastal Oil Fuel Depots owned by the MoD, which continued to be operated and maintained by the residual OPA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2015-03-20/HCWS434/ |title=Government Pipeline and Storage System Sale - HCWS434 |publisher=UK Parliament |accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing its acquisition by CLH, the GPSS was subsequently renamed the CLH Pipeline System (CLH-PS).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tankterminals.com/news_detail.php?id=3176 |title=CLH Begins Operating the UK\u2019s Largest Fuel Pipeline Network |publisher=TankTerminals.com |accessdate=20 May 2015}}</ref> Since CLH have taken over the ownership of the GPSS a number of the pipelines that make up the system have been closed down.<ref>https://www.airfieldresearchgroup.org.uk/forum/fuel-depots/5499-government-pipelines-and-storage-system-gpss?start=220#151415{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[UK oil pipeline network]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Tim Whittle: Fuelling the Wars - PLUTO and the Secret Pipeline Network 1936 to 2015 published 2017. {{ISBN|9780992855468}}\n* D.J.Payton-Smith: Oil - A Study of War-time Policy and Administration. HMSO SBN 11 630074\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Government Pipelines and Storage System}}\n*[http://www.linewatch.org.uk/sites/default/files/2017-12/LWC-2017-01-JZ-GEN-CLH%20Pipeline%20System_2.pdf Schematic Map of CLH Pipeline System]\n*[https://www.secret-bases.co.uk/secret3.htm?permalink=GPSS GPSS on Secret Bases website]\n*[[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)]] - [https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/35893/gpss_booklet.pdf Legislation to enable the sale of the Government Pipeline and Storage System], April 2011\n\n{{Oil storage and distribution in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Oil pipelines in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHigh Peak(link changed toHigh Peak, Derbyshire) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CLH_Pipeline_System"}
{"title_page": "PSO J030947.49+271757.31", "text_new": "{{Quasar\n | name = PSO J030947.49+271757.31\n | epoch = [[J2000]]\n | ra = {{RA|03|09|47.49}}\n | dec = {{DEC|+27|17|57.31}}\n | constellation name = [[Aries (constellation)|Aries]]\n | z = 6.1\n | type = [[Blazar]]\n | dist_ly = 13 billion ly (4.0 billion pc) (light travel distance)<br />30 billion ly (9.0 billion pc) (proper distance)\n | appmag_v = \n | size_v = 0.0025 x 0.0025\n | notes =\n | names = PSO J0309+27\n}}\n'''PSO J030947.49+271757.31''' is the most distant known [[blazar]] located in the Aries constellation. The blazar has a [[redshift]] of 6.1, meaning its light took almost 13 billion years to reach Earth, when the universe was about 1 billion years old, and its present comoving distance is about 30 billion light-years. It was discovered by a team of researchers led by Silvia Belladitta, a Ph.D. student at the [[University of Insubria]], working for the Italian National Institute for Astrophysics (INAF) in [[Milan]], [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Astronomers report most distant blazar ever observed |url=https://phys.org/news/2020-03-astronomers-distant-blazar.html |website=phys.org |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{Cite web|title=Astronomers report most distant blazar ever observed|publisher=[[phys.org]]|date=March 9, 2020|url=https://phys.org/news/2020-03-astronomers-distant-blazar.html}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Citation|title=The first blazar observed at z>6|authors=\nS. Belladitta, A. Moretti, A. Caccianiga, C. Spingola, P. Severgnini, R. Della Ceca, G. Ghisellini, D. Dallacasa, T. Sbarrato, C. Cicone, L. P. Cassar\u00e0, M. Pedani|journal=[[Astronomy & Astrophysics]]|date=6 February 2020|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201937395}}\n\n{{2020 in space}}\n\n[[Category:Blazars]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 2020]]\n[[Category:Aries (constellation)]]\n\n\n{{astronomy-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Quasar\n | name = PSO J030947.49+271757.31\n | epoch = [[J2000]]\n | ra = {{RA|03|09|47.49}}\n | dec = {{DEC|+27|17|57.31}}\n | constellation name = [[Aries (constellation)|Aries]]\n | z = 6.1\n | type = [[Blazar]]\n | dist_ly = 13 billion ly (4.0 billion pc) (light travel distance)<br />30 billion ly (9.0 billion pc) (proper distance)\n | appmag_v = \n | size_v = 0.0025 x 0.0025\n | notes =\n | names = PSO J0309+27\n}}\n'''PSO J030947.49+271757.31''' is the most distant known [[blazar]] located in the Aries constellation. The blazar has a [[redshift]] of 6.1, meaning its light took almost 13 billion years to reach Earth, when the universe was about 1 billion years old, and its present comoving distance is about 30 billion light-years. It was discovered by a team of researchers led by Silvia Belladitta, a Ph.D. student at the [[University of Insubria]], working for the Italian National Institute for Astrophysics (INAF) in [[Milan]], [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Astronomers report most distant blazar ever observed |url=https://phys.org/news/2020-03-astronomers-distant-blazar.html |website=phys.org |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite web|title=Astronomers report most distant blazar ever observed|publisher=[[phys.org]]|date=March 9, 2020|url=https://phys.org/news/2020-03-astronomers-distant-blazar.html}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Citation|title=The first blazar observed at z>6|authors=\nS. Belladitta, A. Moretti, A. Caccianiga, C. Spingola, P. Severgnini, R. Della Ceca, G. Ghisellini, D. Dallacasa, T. Sbarrato, C. Cicone, L. P. Cassar\u00e0, M. Pedani|journal=[[Astronomy & Astrophysics]]|date=6 February 2020|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201937395}}\n\n{{astronomy-stub}}\n{{2020 in space}}\n[[Category:Blazars]]\n[[Category:Astronomical objects discovered in 2020]]\n[[Category:Aries (constellation)]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PSO_J030947.49%2B271757.31"}
{"title_page": "1978\u201379 Yugoslav First League", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition        = [[Yugoslav First League]]\n| season             = 1978\u201379\n| winners            = [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]\n| promoted           = \n| relegated          = [[NK Zagreb]]<br />[[OFK Beograd]]\n| continentalcup1    = [[1979\u201380 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers =  [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]\n| continentalcup2    = [[1979\u201380 European Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers =  [[HNK Rijeka|Rijeka]]\n| continentalcup3    = [[1979\u201380 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers =  [[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]<br />[[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]]\n| league topscorer   = [[Du\u0161an Savi\u0107]] (24)\n| dates              = {{nowrap|12 August 1978 \u2013 17 June 1979}}\n| biggest home win   = \n| biggest away win   = \n| highest scoring    = \n| matches            = 272\n| total goals        = 761\n| longest wins       = \n| longest unbeaten   = \n| longest losses     = \n| highest attendance = \n| lowest attendance  = \n| average attendance = \n| prevseason         = [[1977\u201378 Yugoslav First League|1977\u201378]]\n| nextseason         = [[1979\u201380 Yugoslav First League|1979\u201380]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1978\u201379 [[Yugoslav First League]] season''' was the 33rd season of the First Federal League ({{lang-sh|Prva savezna liga}}), the top level [[association football]] competition of [[SFR Yugoslavia]], since its establishment in 1946. [[Hajduk Split]] won the league title.\n\nA total of 18 teams competed in the league, with the [[1977\u201378 Yugoslav First League|defending champions]] [[FK Partizan|Partizan]] nearly relegated, finishing the season in the 15th place one point clear of the relegation zone. [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]] and [[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] both finished the season on 50 points, but Hajduk won the championship having the better goal difference. However, there was a controversy in the first round when [[HNK Rijeka|Rijeka]] defeated Dinamo 2\u20131 at [[Stadion Kantrida|Kantrida]]. Dinamo claimed that [[Edmond Tomi\u0107]], who joined Rijeka that season from [[KF Liria|Lirija]], didn't serve a one-match suspension following two yellow cards received while playing for his former club. They appealed and after two months it has been decided to award the match 3\u20130 to Dinamo. After several appeals from both sides, in spring 1979 [[Football Association of Yugoslavia]] ruled in favour of Rijeka. The case was brought to Employment Appeal Tribunal, which four years later ruled Dinamo as champions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ezadar.hr/clanak/neodigrana-utakmica-rijeka-dinamo-novi-slucaja-tomic |title=Neodigrana utakmica Rijeka \u2013 Dinamo, novi Slu\u010daja Tomi\u0107? |last=ts/eZd |first= |date=2 November 2008 |work=ezadar.hr |language=Croatian |accessdate=21 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe season began on 12 August 1978 and concluded on 17 June 1979. This was the third and last national title win for Hajduk under the guidance of manager [[Tomislav Ivi\u0107]], who previously led the club to four consecutive [[Yugoslav Cup]] wins in 1972, 1973, 1974 and 1976 (not contested in 1975). Striker [[Du\u0161an Savi\u0107]] of [[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]] was the top goalscorer with 24 goals. This was the second achievement for Savi\u0107, who previously topped the scoring table in the [[1974\u201375 Yugoslav First League|1974\u201375 season]]. [[HNK Rijeka|Rijeka]] entered the [[1979\u201380 European Cup Winners' Cup]], after defeating [[FK Partizan|Partizan]] in the final of [[Yugoslav Cup]] with an aggregate score 2\u20131.\n\n==Teams==\nA total of eighteen teams contested the league, including sixteen sides from the [[1977\u201378 Yugoslav First League|1977\u201378 season]] and two sides promoted from the 1977\u201378 [[Yugoslav Second League]] (YSL) as winners of the two second level divisions East and West. The league was contested in a [[double round robin]] format, with each club playing every other club twice, for a total of 34 rounds. Two points were awarded for wins and one point for draws.\n\n[[NK \u010celik Zenica|\u010celik Zenica]] and [[FK Trep\u010da|Trep\u010da Kosovska Mitrovica]] were relegated from the [[1977\u201378 Yugoslav First League]] after finishing the season in bottom two places of the league table. The two clubs promoted to top level were [[FK Napredak Kru\u0161evac|Napredak Kru\u0161evac]] and [[FK \u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo|\u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo]].\n\n{{Location map+ |Yugoslavia |float=right |width=350 |caption=Locations of teams' home cities in the 1978\u201379 Yugoslav First League |places=\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=44.766667 |long=17.183333 |label=[[Banja Luka]] |position=left }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=44.820556 |long=20.462222 |label=[[Belgrade]] |position=right}}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=43.583333 |long=21.316667 |label=[[Kru\u0161evac]] }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=46.051389 |long=14.505556 |label=[[Ljubljana]] }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=43.33     |long=17.80     |label=[[Mostar]] }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=43.30     |long=21.90     |label=[[Ni\u0161]] |position=right }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=45.255    |long=19.845    |label=[[Novi Sad]] }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=45.544937 |long=18.695705 |label=[[Osijek]] |position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=45.339202 |long=14.380959 |label=[[Rijeka]] }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=43.8476   |long=18.3564   |label=[[Sarajevo]] }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=43.519444 |long=16.431667 |label=[[Split (city)|Split]] }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=42.47     |long=19.28     |label=[[Podgorica|Titograd]] }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=44.538056 |long=18.676111 |label=[[Tuzla]] |position=left}}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=45.818858 |long=16.018078 |label=[[Zagreb]] }}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n!width=\"130\"| Team\n!width=\"100\"| Location\n!width=\"200\"| [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia#Federal subjects|Federal Republic]] \n!width=\"90\"| Position<br />in [[1977\u201378 Yugoslav First League|1977\u201378]]\n|-\n|[[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac Banja Luka]]\n|[[Banja Luka]]\n|{{flag|SR Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">012</span>12th\n|-\n|[[FK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost]]\n|[[Podgorica|Titograd]]\n|{{flag|SR Montenegro}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">011</span>11th\n|-\n|[[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n|[[Zagreb]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">004</span>4th\n|-\n|[[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]\n|[[Split (city)|Split]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">003</span>3rd\n|-\n|[[FK Napredak Kru\u0161evac|Napredak Kru\u0161evac]]\n|[[Kru\u0161evac]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n|[[OFK Beograd|OFK Belgrade]]\n|[[Belgrade]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">016</span>16th\n|-\n|[[NK Olimpija Ljubljana (1911)|Olimpija Ljubljana]]\n|[[Ljubljana]]\n|{{flag|SR Slovenia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">010</span>10th\n|-\n|[[NK Osijek|Osijek]]\n|[[Osijek]]\n|{{flag|SR Croatia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"display:none\">013</span>13th\n|-\n|[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n|[[Belgrade]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=\"gold\"|<span style=\"display:none\">001</span>1st\n|-\n|[[FK Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161|Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161]]\n|[[Ni\u0161]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"display:none\">014</span>14th\n|-\n|[[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]]\n|[[Belgrade]]\n|{{flag|SR Serbia}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |<span style=\"displ