arajevo|\u017deljezni\u010dar]]\n|match_\u017dEL_BOR=3\u20130\n|match_\u017dEL_BUD=1\u20131\n|match_\u017dEL_DIN=0\u20131\n|match_\u017dEL_HAJ=2\u20132\n|match_\u017dEL_NAP=1\u20131\n|match_\u017dEL_OFK=3\u20131\n|match_\u017dEL_OLI=2\u20130\n|match_\u017dEL_OSI=2\u20131\n|match_\u017dEL_PAR=2\u20132\n|match_\u017dEL_RNI=1\u20130\n|match_\u017dEL_RSB=0\u20131\n|match_\u017dEL_RIJ=1\u20130\n|match_\u017dEL_SAR=[[Sarajevo derby|4\u20132]]\n|match_\u017dEL_SLO=1\u20130\n|match_\u017dEL_VEL=1\u20130\n|match_\u017dEL_VOJ=2\u20134\n|match_\u017dEL_ZAG=2\u20131\n\n|update=complete\n|source= \n}}\n\n==Top scorers==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Rank\n!Player\n!Club\n!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|1\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Du\u0161an Savi\u0107]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]]\n|24\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|2\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Vahid Halilhod\u017ei\u0107]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[FK Vele\u017e Mostar|Vele\u017e]]\n|16\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|3\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Safet Su\u0161i\u0107]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[FK Sarajevo|Sarajevo]]\n|15\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|4\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Slobodan Santra\u010d]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n|14\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|5\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Snje\u0161ko Cerin]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|13\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Abid Kova\u010devi\u0107]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac Banja Luka]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Zlatko Kranj\u010dar]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Ivan Luka\u010devi\u0107]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[NK Osijek|Osijek]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|9\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Muhamed Ibrahimbegovi\u0107]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[FK Borac Banja Luka|Borac Banja Luka]]\n|rowspan=\"5\"|12\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Vladimir Joci\u0107]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[FK Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161|Radni\u010dki Ni\u0161]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Milo\u0161 Kosti\u0107]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[OFK Beograd|OFK Belgrade]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Srebrenko Rep\u010di\u0107]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[FK Sarajevo|Sarajevo]]\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Slavi\u0161a \u017dungul]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]\n|}\n<!-- Source: http://img244.imageshack.us/img244/7599/p4220004.jpg from http://www.parapsihopatologija.com/forums/index.php?showtopic=1130&st=870-->\n\n==See also==\n*[[1978\u201379 Yugoslav Second League]]\n*[[1978\u201379 Yugoslav Cup]]\n*[[1978\u201379 NK Hajduk Split season]]\n\n==External links==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesj/joeghist.html Yugoslavia Domestic Football Full Tables]\n\n{{Yugoslav First League}}\n{{1978\u201379 in European Football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1978-79 Yugoslav First League}}\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League seasons]]\n[[Category:1978\u201379 in European association football leagues|Yugo]]\n[[Category:1978\u201379 in Yugoslavian football]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition        = [[Yugoslav First League]]\n| season             = 1978\u201379\n| winners            = [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]\n| promoted           = \n| relegated          = [[NK Zagreb]]<br />[[OFK Beograd]]\n| continentalcup1    = [[1979\u201380 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers =  [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]]\n| continentalcup2    = [[1979\u201380 European Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers =  [[HNK Rijeka|Rijeka]]\n| continentalcup3    = [[1979\u201380 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers =  [[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]<br />[[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]]\n| league topscorer   = [[Du\u0161an Savi\u0107]] (24)\n| dates              = {{nowrap|12 August 1978 \u2013 17 June 1979}}\n| biggest home win   = \n| biggest away win   = \n| highest scoring    = \n| matches            = 272\n| total goals        = 761\n| longest wins       = \n| longest unbeaten   = \n| longest losses     = \n| highest attendance = \n| lowest attendance  = \n| average attendance = \n| prevseason         = [[1977\u201378 Yugoslav First League|1977\u201378]]\n| nextseason         = [[1979\u201380 Yugoslav First League|1979\u201380]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1978\u201379 [[Yugoslav First League]] season''' was the 33rd season of the First Federal League ({{lang-sh|Prva savezna liga}}), the top level [[association football]] competition of [[SFR Yugoslavia]], since its establishment in 1946. [[Hajduk Split]] won the league title.\n\nA total of 18 teams competed in the league, with the [[1977\u201378 Yugoslav First League|defending champions]] [[FK Partizan|Partizan]] nearly relegated, finishing the season in the 15th place one point clear of the relegation zone. [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]] and [[NK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] both finished the season on 50 points, but Hajduk won the championship having the better goal difference. However, there was a controversy in the first round when [[HNK Rijeka|Rijeka]] defeated Dinamo 2\u20131 at [[Stadion Kantrida|Kantrida]]. Dinamo claimed that [[Edmond Tomi\u0107]], who joined Rijeka that season from [[KF Liria|Lirija]], didn't serve a one-match suspension following two yellow cards received while playing for his former club. They appealed and after two months it has been decided to award the match 3\u20130 to Dinamo. After several appeals from both sides, in spring 1979 [[Football Association of Yugoslavia]] ruled in favour of Rijeka. The case was brought to Employment Appeal Tribunal, which four years later ruled Dinamo as champions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ezadar.hr/clanak/neodigrana-utakmica-rijeka-dinamo-novi-slucaja-tomic |title=Neodigrana utakmica Rijeka \u2013 Dinamo, novi Slu\u010daja Tomi\u0107? |last=ts/eZd |first= |date=2 November 2008 |work=ezadar.hr |language=Croatian |accessdate=21 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe season began on 12 August 1978 and concluded on 17 June 1979. This was the third and last national title win for Hajduk under the guidance of manager [[Tomislav Ivi\u0107]], who previously led the club to four consecutive [[Yugoslav Cup]] wins in 1972, 1973, 1974 and 1976 (not contested in 1975). Striker [[Du\u0161an Savi\u0107]] of [[Red Star Belgrade|Red Star]] was the top goalscorer with 24 goals. This was the second achievement for Savi\u0107, who previously topped the scoring table in the [[1974\u201375 Yugoslav First League|1974\u201375 season]]. [[HNK Rijeka|Rijeka]] entered the [[1979\u201380 European Cup Winners' Cup]], after defeating [[FK Partizan|Partizan]] in the final of [[Yugoslav Cup]] with an aggregate score 2\u20131.\n\n==Teams==\nA total of eighteen teams contested the league, including sixteen sides from the [[1977\u201378 Yugoslav First League|1977\u201378 season]] and two sides promoted from the 1977\u201378 [[Yugoslav Second League]] (YSL) as winners of the two second level divisions East and West. The league was contested in a [[double round robin]] format, with each club playing every other club twice, for a total of 34 rounds. Two points were awarded for wins and one point for draws.\n\n[[NK \u010celik Zenica|\u010celik Zenica]] and [[FK Trep\u010da|Trep\u010da Kosovska Mitrovica]] were relegated from the [[1977\u201378 Yugoslav First League]] after finishing the season in bottom two places of the league table. The two clubs promoted to top level were [[FK Napredak Kru\u0161evac|Napredak Kru\u0161evac]] and [[FK \u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo|\u017deljezni\u010dar Sarajevo]].\n\n{{Location map+ |Yugoslavia |float=right |width=350 |caption=Locations of teams' home cities in the 1978\u201379 Yugoslav First League |places=\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=44.766667 |long=17.183333 |label=[[Banja Luka]] |position=left }}\n{{Location map~ |Yugoslavia |lat=44.820556 |long=20.462222 |label=[[Belgrade]] |position=right}}\n{{Location map~ 